heavily dependent on speed as they are vision, footwork, balance, and short-area quickness. If Jacobs can avoid serious injury during his career, he could have a long career and frustrate fantasy players at the end by preventing more athletic talents from earning full-time action.


Jacobs has tremendous versatility and it doesn’t come at the cost of him lacking excellence in any of those areas. He’s a cutback runner with effective zone-scheme savvy. He’s also an aggressive gap runner who can accelerate into the crease. He possesses an excellent balance between patience and decisiveness for each scheme, which is indicative of a player well-versed in both types of blocking.


Jacobs has the burst to beat linebackers to the hole and all the way through it. If attacking the short edge of the field, he’s quick enough to work past linebackers and some defensive backs to reach it.


The greatest weakness in Jacobs’ athletic profile is long speed. A safety with a good angle over top can beat Jacobs to the edge on runs off-tackle and he’ll get caught from behind on runs where breakaway threats will earn longer gains.


However, long speed is useless to a back if he lacks the footwork, quickness, and acceleration to reach open field. For Jacobs this is not a problem and he has these traits all day long.


Whether it’s gap or zone or in the crease or at the edge, Jacobs will find secondary creases and quickly navigate his way through them. If there’s penetration early in the play, he’ll identify it and find the escape route to bounce towards.


Jacobs’ footwork is the basis for his skill. He can alter his stride length, pattern, and tempo to set up creases or change direction—even in tight quarters.


Jacobs possesses dramatic changes of direction. He has good lateral movement set up by a drop of his weight with strong deceleration. When he needs to bend an angle, he has the hips and ankles to drop his weight and execute that curvilinear movement around defenders in tight quarters.


He can point his toe to open his hips after making a hard downhill cut to weave back to the outside. He spins off indirect hits and can slalom cut as well as anyone with the way he drops his weight and dips.


His first-step quickness helps him make the first man miss with a hop or dip inside and away from contact. Jacobs possesses all of the dynamic movements, but he’s economical with their use.


Even when the creases are small, he’ll create space with an aggressive attack to knife through or push his linemen forward. He knows how to hit a crease hard and with just the right amount of body lean into a linebacker head-on to push past and force the defender to wrap from behind and hang on for a short ride. If the linebacker attacks low, Jacobs often breaks these wraps and continues into open space.

Defensive backs in Jacobs’ path better get square and deliver or they’ll earn a shoulder-full of punishment. He’ll even slice through linebackers in the crease like he tore through a paper banner at the beginning of a high school game.


When the linebacker or safety can deliver a strong hit from a direct angle, Jacobs has the balance to maintain his footing and wait for reinforcements to start a scrum that will propel him forward another 4-5 yards. This is also true when defensive linemen deliver hits from indirect angles.


His burst, patience, footwork, attack, and body lean also make Jacobs and effective short-yardage runner. He’ll push a pile, pull through reaches, and keep his feet moving until the whistle blows or he’s on the ground.


When Jacobs reaches the other end of a crease untouched, he can tear through reaches from defensive backs and linebackers. He’s notably skilled with the stiff- arm, demonstrating excellent timing and placement of the device against all three levels of the defense. He’ll use it to ward off the reach of defenders as well as to pry them off his frame.


Jacobs practices high and tight ball security with the correct arm away from pursuit angles. His elbow can be a little tighter but he also uses both arms as he encounters heavy traffic. Even on the occasion that Jacobs’ arm drifts low and loose, he’s shown he can withstand swats to that arm and maintain possession. He’s a strong runner with a good grip of the ball.


Jacobs will earn early playing time with his strong pass protection abilities. He works well from the middle of the pocket to the edge and effectively squares edge defenders. He'll read the cornerback blitz and earn position as the second line of defense behind his tackle. He can occasionally set up too wide on these edge blitzes.


He reads A- and B-gap blitzes and executes cut blocks with a shoot that’s late enough that it isn’t telegraphed. When issuing a block from his feet, Jacobs will step up and earn good depth in the pocket to attack the opponent.


Ask Jacobs to lead block on a run play and he’ll lead his runner through the open crease or the edge of the formation and open the lane for big gains thanks to a strong uppercut and a roll of his hips after a running start to his collision point. Don’t think Jacobs can only make one block on a play. He’ll hit defenders in succession.


Jacobs is a better puncher in the run game than he is with pass protection. He shields defenders well but the punch isn’t as consistent. When Jacobs faces a defensive lineman, he’ll overcompensate for his lack of a consistent punch by leaning. This overextension is rarely effective.


While Jacobs has potential to become an excellent blocker, he’s already an excellent receiver. He catches the ball with the appropriate hands techniques for the location of the target. He tracks the ball well and can make plays over his shoulder. And he also possesses the hand-eye coordination to pluck difficult targets from the

air, including one-hand catches on passes lacking pinpoint accuracy.


Contact at the catch point doesn’t faze Jacobs and neither does the prospect of high-pointing the ball or adjusting his frame for a back-shoulder target. He runs a good whip route and reads the leverage of his coverage well enough to adjust his routes up the seam.


Although Jacobs has the career workload of a lightweight, he’s a top heavyweight as a running back prospect. With the exception of breakaway speed, and an actual documented track record of heavy volume, Jacobs has proven he can do everything on the field required of a feature back.


Considering the illustrious list of runners who’ve been in the same situation as collegians entering the NFL, Jacobs should be at or near the top of your list.


Tampa Bay, Atlanta, and Philadelphia come to mind as teams that could really use his services. He’d fit with any team.


RSP Film Room: Joshua Jacobs


Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: The wide receiver class is good enough that Jacobs and his lack of long speed and light workload could lead to a slight drop to the middle of the first round. If this happens, it would be wise to pounce.


Jacobs’ versatility and refinement should make him a consistent pro. Give him a top-notch line and he can be a top-five producer at the position. Give him a below- average line and he’ll still deliver starter production in most fantasy leagues.


Give him good health for his career and 15 years later, he’ll be like Frank Gore: still running circles around that new NFL wunderkind who worshipped him back in the first grade.


  1. David Montgomery, Iowa St. (5-10, 222)


    Depth of Talent Score: 85.85 = Starter: Starting immediately with large role and learning on the go.


    In October, ESPN went viral with an overzealous graphic hyping Montgomery’s skills. The graphic indicated Montgomery had the feet of Saquon Barkley, the vision of Le’Veon Bell, the strength of Ezekiel Elliott, and the athletic ability of Sony Michel.


    I learned my lesson after big media football analysts compared Reggie Bush to Gale Sayers. Comparisons are rarely meant to be direct correlations of talent, but rather a commentary about similar styles of play. Of course, these subtleties are only reserved for programming scheduled for the wee hours of the morning.


    Comparisons are made in most performance mediums. Jazz musicians are subjected to them all of the time.


    “He sounds like Coltrane…”


    “No, he sounds like Sonny Rollins…”


    “I hear a lot of Joe Henderson to his playing…”


    “That style of high-octave honking is just like Stanley Turrentine…”


    “He even owes a debt to James Brown!”


    The more you study performers in a performance medium and learn its history, the more you realize that performers are an amalgamation of several influences.


    The example above is a partial list of influences for one of my favorite musical performers, Michael Brecker. A Grammy Award-winning jazz musician, he played on over 900 albums from every genre of music ranging from Horace Silver to Steely Dan to Joni Mitchell before making his first solo album in the mid-1980s. Known as one of the great modern jazz improvisers, he also had an indelible R&B sound.


    According to my wife, Steve Harvey once committed the sin during his nationally syndicated radio show of ending Cameo’s hit, “Candy” before Brecker’s iconic solo. The national audience called up in mass to chide Harvey on- air for the omission.


    When I listen to Brecker, I hear several of the influential musicians he studied to create his musical persona. In one sense, he sounds like all of these musicians, but because he expresses these influences through the lens of his personality and musical sensibilities, he has a unique musical voice and language that has led to others borrowing from him.


    The range of ESPN’s comparisons bestowed on Montgomery may seem ridiculous, but only if you’re making a direct correlation to talent. A big network using this comparison at the beginning of a game is meant to draw viewers and maintain interest. They don’t mind if the viewer sees the analysis as a direct correlation to all of these players—even if the spirit of the comparison is meant to be merely stylistic.


    I played the saxophone. I had peers tell me I sounded like a mix of Wayne Shorter, Joe Henderson, Sonny Rollins, John Coltrane, and Ben Webster. No one ever meant I played anywhere near their level of musicianship. They could hear the influences despite all of us knowing that Blue Note Records wasn’t ever going to knock on my door with a recording contract.


    Football fans would benefit from this perspective.


    Here’s a hot take for you: Montgomery doesn’t have to be as talented as the players assigned to him in each of these areas of his game to be one of the better prospects in this class of runner. He doesn’t need to be fast, either.


    The greatest difference between him and Jacobs is footwork. Montgomery is more creative and dramatic with his moves, which occasionally has a downside him losing yards. Jacobs is more economical, which may not lead to as many larger creases that Montgomery can access.


    Montgomery worked in shotgun, pistol, and one-back offenses with gap and zone plays. Like Jacobs,

    Montgomery will hit creases hard when the scheme calls for it or he’ll show patience to set up the hole with a good press deep into the line or some creative movement.


    If there’s no crease and a bounce is too risky for the down-and-distance situation, Montgomery will bury his frame into the backside of a blocker and generate push to get the pile moving. He’ll also take what the defense gives him.


    In addition to successful initiations of scrums and the ability to carry larger men on his back for significant yards through contact, Montgomery is an excellent finisher. This sets him apart from most of his peers.


    Montgomery can widen his stride and lower his pads into a crease or a defender so he’s generating optimal momentum to drive through contact. Montgomery’s quickness, leverage, sense of balance, and creative movement makes him capable of breaking multiple tackles on any play.


    His low center of gravity reminds me of Doug Martin and Ray Rice and bounces off contact to his frame—even early in runs while still in the backfield. He’s strong enough to pull through wraps—don’t even try to wrap him high. His stiff-arm is good enough to ward off the reach of defensive linemen.


    The stiff arm isn’t Montgomery’s only successful tool against defensive linemen. He has the balance to bounce off hard hits from indirect angles. This is a rare trait for a college running back.


    Montgomery even weaponizes his pad level, using his shoulder to uppercut through contact from linebackers. He’ll drop his pads low to knock linebackers to the turf and continue down field.


    When he can’t win direct collisions, he’ll spin off contact, attack with contact and then spin away, or balance-touch to regain his footing. He finishes with good extension of his upper body to earn yardage at the end of a play.


    Montgomery’s vision supports excellent movement solutions against problems defenses pose. He reads penetration quickly and finds bounce-out opportunities. His quickness is good enough to stop, reverse his field, and cut downhill just inside edge containment for positive yards.


    More dramatic movements allow linebackers to react with greater ease to Montgomery’s movement. When he keeps his steps short, he wins more often in these situations.


    Although his acceleration allows him to reach the secondary, he lacks the deep speed to separate from defensive backs. He relies on his change-of-direction quickness and stamina to work from one side of the field to the other.


    Montgomery is fast enough to outrun linebackers and some safeties—or at least maintain separation he earned against them early in the play. He will get rundown by backside linebackers before he reaches a crease if penetration forces Montgomery to execute multiple moves before accelerating through a downhill crease.


    Off-tackle runs are effective, but working around the edge is difficult for Montgomery unless he’s earning an option toss. He can beat linebackers to the corner, but defensive backs are tougher assignments.


    While Montgomery is quick and fast enough to employ multiple moves in sequence while behind the line of scrimmage or in a crease, he’s even more effective in the open field. Jukes, stop-start moves, cuts, spins, shakes, and head fakes are all weapons in Montgomery’s arsenal.


    When he employs adjustments to his stride length, he navigates expertly though traffic and he’s especially difficult to bring down. Montgomery will avoid shots to his legs, dip away from pursuit, and even stop over wraps coming from odd angles.


    There’s a tendency with Montgomery to hop and turn from penetration, but that hop takes him closer to the penetrating defender and in an off-balanced position. Instead he should slow his pace and bend his path away from the opponent. This will keep him outside a defender’s radius of attack.


    A skilled receiver, Iowa State used Montgomery wide, from the slot, and from the backfield. He extends well for the target, snares the ball quickly, and often transitions to a runner efficiently. He’ll take a hit while securing the ball and maintain possession—this includes one-handed, over-the-shoulder targets in the short range of the field.


    He can also make difficult adjustments to targets arriving into his frame at awkward angles. Tracking the ball over his shoulder is not a challenge.


    Montgomery is a competent blocker with room to improve. He can use a one-arm technique on defensive backs off the edge with good leverage. He's willing to throw his body across the pocket to reach a blitzing edge defender.


    Cut blocks often arrive at knee height and could be a little higher. He has an effective outside-in approach versus edge assignments in the pocket.


    In play-action situations, Montgomery squares his targets and delivers his arms into the opponent. With double teams or chips, he’ll lead with his pads. He can shield defenders from his quarterback off the edge, but needs to be a beat faster with his decisions to set up against the pressure.


    Montgomery must begin punching against linemen or he’ll risk getting pushed backwards. His hand position is solid but the force behind them is something he must cultivate.


    Montgomery has Star Caliber ball security, fumbling once per 208 touches. He uses the correct arm to carry the ball based on his path and the pursuit. His carriage is high and when necessary, he’ll use both arms to protect the ball.


    An Eagle Scout, Iowa State coaches call Montgomery a culture changer. In addition to whatever off-field leadership Montgomery has, his hard-running, tackle breaking style gets teammates excited on the field.


    ESPN may see an amalgamation of Barkley, Michel, Elliott, and Bell, but I also see a combination of stylistic influences that resemble Maurice Jones-Drew, Ray Rice, and Devonta Freeman.


    Expect Montgomery to earn immediate playing time. If he performs well, he should become a productive feature back. Imagine him as the heir-apparent behind Freeman in Atlanta or spelling James Conner in Pittsburgh.


    RSP Boiler Room: Smart Footwork—Montgomery and Arian Foster

    RSP Boiler Room: Open-Field Decision-Making RSP Boiler Room: Depth of Step


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Montgomery will be a top-five back in most rankings although his lack of speed could generate some variability in pre-draft rankings around the industry. If he’s available as a late first-round pick, he’s a bargain.


    Tier II: The three in this tier may not have the draft capital to earn a starting job right away, but each is skilled enough to contribute immediately and earn an opportunity to be a central figure in an offense within 2-3 years, maximum.


  2. Damien Harris, Alabama (5-10, 216)


    Depth of Talent Score: 82.85 = Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths.


    Even if their argument comes up a little short of the mark, Alabama fans can at least offer a compelling debate that their school—not Georgia—is Running Back

    U. The duo of Jacobs and Harris is this year’s version of Nick Chubb and Sony Michel—gifted runners both capable of assuming starting roles in the NFL.


    Harris successfully runs zone and gap schemes. He alters his pacing to set up blocks and will occasionally use some stride alteration. He needs to do this a little more often instead of depending as much on jump cuts and jump stops—although both are often excellent choices in the moment.


    Harris has the patience to press and cut. He has the dynamic cutting ability to work from left guard to right tackle and accelerate out of the move. Although not as dynamic as backs like LeSean McCoy or Matt Forte during their primes, Harris has enough hip mobility to drop his weight, execute sudden stops, and bounce runs to the perimeter.


    He does good work as a zone runner. He uses angular cuts to make quick turns downhill as he reaches the edge of the line and does so with one cut and only 1-2 steps of preparation. He finds backside creases quickly against penetration and while you don’t see many small creases for him to exploit at Alabama, he’s comfortable doing so.


    Harris employs a stutter step to set up creases and is quick in and out of slalom cuts through small creases. He has more to his repertoire than angular changes of direction. He can bend runs around obstacles with good

    quickness and acceleration to the edge. Even with the varieties of setups, Harris hits creases decisively.


    Despite the variety of movement to set up creases, he’s not as deceptive once he’s past the line of scrimmage. At his best, he finds a second cutback lane under the linebackers or safeties. However, he can do a better job setting up two-way-gos.


    Harris has notable acceleration around the edge. He has enough burst to reach the corner on designed plays as well as unplanned bounce-outs to the short side of the field.


    When conditions are right at the line of scrimmage, Harris can break a run 50-75 yards, but he lacks the top gear to sustain his pace and the fastest cornerback on the opposing team will catch him from behind. Even a fast linebacker will have a chance on runs approaching 40 yards in length.


    Harris lacks the size to be a true banger that knocks down linebackers in the hole with a direct collision, but he has starter-caliber balance and power. He’ll stalemate linebackers and defensive backs until his teammates can generate a mass push of the pile. He routinely runs through reaches to his frame and he’ll pull through wraps to his ankles.


    Harris’ pad level is good enough to drag a linebacker or defensive lineman wrapped around his waist, chest, or shoulders. When he can time the use of his pads appropriately, he can earn 2-3 yards over or under a linebacker in a direct collision. As for defensive backs, he can run them over or knock them backwards when he drops the pads and can do so from a variety of angles of approach.


    Harris’ stiff-arm is functionally effective at warding off wraps to his torso by linebackers and defensive backs. The stiff-arm forces them to slide down Harris’ frame and wrap the back at the ankles. The stiff arm is most successful when pushing defensive backs off balance.


    He’ll often extend through wrap-ups and pull past with the aid of a sound, balance-touch technique with his free hand. He’s skilled at delivering an extra leap or dive to earn a final 1-3 yards as he’s losing balance.


    Harris had only 3 fumbles on 557 touches at Alabama, which is Star-Caliber ball security. He carries the ball high and tight under the arm working away from pursuit angles. He takes contact to the ball and maintains good security.


    Harris should develop into a good blocker. He identifies blitzes well bothpre-snap and early post-snap. He can work across the pocket and set quickly at a 45-degree angle to handle edge pressure. When there’s double A- gap pressure, Harris chooses the correct linebacker so his quarterback has room to work away from the other.

    Overall, he’s patient with handling pressure and it results in effective work.


    He can mirror the movements of opponents off the edge and work himself into a position where he uses the defender’s momentum to his advantage. If he can’t square a defender in time when working across the

    pocket to an assignment, he’ll shoot with his pads or elbow towards his opponent’s chest.


    Harris earns good height on his cut blocks and he will shoot through the opponent’s body. He doesn’t always reach the outside leg of the opponent, though, lessening the impact of the effort.


    He must become more consistent with his punch. He’ll sometimes get his hands into good position to deliver a punch and only shove the opponent. He can punch with an uppercut motion, but needs to develop force with the shots, which requires a roll of his hips. Even so, he’s ahead of a player like Kareem Hunt in his rookie season and they have a lot of commonalities to their style of play.


    Harris is a competent receiver. He catches the ball well in stride with his breaks. He’ll extend for throws away from his frame—high or low—and he snatches the ball from the air with proper hands techniques. He tracks the ball well over his shoulder or when targets arrive into his frame and behind his break point.


    The worst case scenario for Harris is that he’s a jack-of- all-trades back like Pierre Thomas, the former Saint. The best case is he offers some of the talents Hunt provided in Kansas City. He’s not as powerful as Hunt, but he’s a superior pass protector.


    He’d be a nice co-starter for a lot of teams if he’s not chosen early to challenge for a feature role. Among others, Atlanta, San Francisco, and Buffalo would be good fits.


    Damien Harris Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Harris one of the safest skill prospects in the draft. His fantasy draft stock will range from late in the first round to early third round, depending when he’s selected in the NFL Draft (think rounds 2-4).

  3. Rodney Anderson, Oklahoma (6-0, 224) Depth of Talent Score: 82.65 = Rotational Starter:

    Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their

    strengths.


    Anderson tore his ACL in early September. The good news is that Anderson has never suffered a knee injury in the past and he should be ready for playing time in advance of the NFL’s opener. Despite recent individual cases where running backs with ACL tears are performing well sooner than ever—including one of the most famous Oklahoma running backs who played at an elite level after nine months of rehab—expectations for Anderson should remain modest until the rookie proves otherwise.


    None of this should preclude you from considering Anderson early—especially if your expectation is that any first-year success is a surprise. With that reasonable expectation, Anderson becomes a priority selection—and likely a bargain for any team.


    Like his contemporaries at the top of the class, Anderson possesses a good balance of patience and decisiveness. He can run inside zone and gap. He’ll press creases with

    zone plays and find cutbacks and he has just the right amount of patience to set up pulling blocks in gap schemes.


    Once in the open field, Anderson also presses downfield blocks and sets up two-way-goes with impressive craft. Even in gap schemes, Anderson will find the rare but appropriate cutback opportunity.


    Despite a naturally long gait, Anderson has the footwork to adjust the length of his stride. He’s is able to lift his feet up to work over defenders shooting for his lower legs in the hole.


    He can pair his stride adjustments with cuts when he spots run blitzers in the backfield. Anderson won’t ever be mistaken for Jamaal Charles or LeSean McCoy, but he has an effective jump cut and he’s capable of sequencing moves to create space against defenders blocking the rushing lane. Anderson can drop his weight and make a safety look silly in the open field.


    As fun as these open-field jukes are to watch, Anderson also does the play-to-play footwork well. He plants his foot and delivers sharp downhill cuts. When running to the perimeter, and turning the corner, Anderson only needs 1-2 steps to transition from an East-West trajectory to a North-South path.


    A well-built runner, Anderson splits defenders and pulls through contact for extra yards. He can lean through initial contact and extend for extra yardage. His second effort in a pile earns him positive yards.


    Anderson is a mature decision maker who won’t try to bounce runs in every instance when a crease lacks a clear opening. He’ll push into the backs of his teammates when short yardage or field position dictates he should.


    Also a strong finisher, Anderson will drop his pads and attack opponents. His ability to extend his frame comes in handy near the first-down marker or pylon. He possesses good balance-touch technique to regain his stride when defenders disrupt his footing. And he has a stiff-arm that wards off or punishes oncoming defenders.


    Anderson has enough balance to maintain his footing after indirect contact from defensive linemen. He’ll drag linemen for extra yards when they hit and wrap.


    When he reaches the other side of a crease, Anderson has the acceleration to beat linebackers to the secondary. His burst is enough to extend runs 40-50 yards—even when a linebacker is athletic enough to eventually run him down.


    Anderson isn’t a homerun threat. He’s likely to be caught from behind more frequently in the NFL. Think of him as a doubles hitter who can break off multiple gains of 15- 20 yards during a game.


    Anderson has potential to become an excellent blocker. He slides quickly to the spot of his assignment, squares his opponents, and often delivers the first strike— especially to defensive backs rushing from the edge. He identifies the corner blitz well and often forces the defender to redirect his path. Inside pressure can be more difficult for Anderson to accurately diagnose.


    Anderson was a willing lead blocker in Oklahoma’s offense. He’ll earn good angles on safeties in the hole and push them to the ground. He can also cut defenders when assigned to the edge of the pocket.


    On occasion—once each in four blocks during one game— Anderson would overextend his reach into the chest of an opponent. He must improve the accuracy and force of his punches and despite his tendency to earn first strikes against smaller opponents, he must also be first to hit when facing defenders his size and larger. Otherwise defenders bounce off his contact and earn a direct path to the quarterback.


    An accompanying issue with his extension is the lowering and leaning of his head into contact. When he catches contact from defenders, he’s immediately at a disadvantage for the rest of the assignment.


    Still, expect Anderson to earn playing time on passing downs because these are correctable flaws and he’s an excellent receiver. Anderson snatches targets with a strong catch radius. He tracks the ball well enough to win targets on back-shoulder fades. He also has the refinement to turn back for the ball with his torso while maintaining his path downhill.


    Anderson tracks the ball well as it arrives over his shoulder, and he also high-points difficult targets in tight coverage. He’ll take a hit during the catch and still maintain possession. He’s a runner who will win wheel routes up the sideline and bullet routes up the seam but can be used with even more versatility.


    Anderson’s ball security is high to his chest and he uses the appropriate arm based on the location of the pursuit. He’s good at switching the ball while on the move.


    Injuries will scare some off Anderson. In addition to the 2018 ACL tear, he broke his left leg in 2015 and then a bone in his neck in 2016. He’s effectively missed two years at Oklahoma.


    Running back is a position with high turnover but as we discussed with Joshua Jacobs, injuries and workload are difficult to predict. Before Saquon Barkley, Ki-Jana Carter was the most athletic runner in Penn State history and was considered freakish like Barkley. He didn’t have an injury history in college but suffered multiple injuries early in his NFL career.


    Johnathan Franklin carried the load for UCLA. Drafted alongside Eddie Lacy in Green Bay, Franklin impressed during the second half of a contest against the Bengals early in the season—carrying his team to a fourth-quarter victory. It was the last game he ever played due to a neck injury.


    Gore tore both ACLs in college and he’s coming off a decent 15th season. Willis McGahee also had a strong career after a late-season ACL tear at the University of Miami. If you’re staying away from Anderson for these reasons, you’re engaging more in fears than facts.


    Thoughts on Two Plays of Rodney Anderson’s



    Rodney Anderson Highlights



    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Anderson will be the potential bargain of fantasy drafts. If other backs on this list within the same tier earn decent landing spots, Anderson will be available after they’re gone. It may prove the case even if the picture is cloudy for these runners.


    Anderson reminds me of Ryan Mathews in style. Both are strong, swift, agile runners with receiving skill who can carry the load. Mathews had more breakaway speed and better contact balance.


    However, Mathews lacked self-esteem early on and didn’t put in the consistent work. It led to an inconsistent career. If Anderson is a willing worker in the offseason, he can do more than Mathews with a little less ability.


    Anderson would fit well in Chicago, Oakland, Kansas City, Atlanta, and Pittsburgh. He’d be a nice value for the Steelers because it could let him heal and let Pittsburgh roll with James Conner for another year.


  4. Alexander Mattison, Boise State (5-11, 221)


    Depth of Talent Score: 82.45 = Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths.


    A detailed evaluation process helps me identify learning opportunities as an evaluator. Two years ago, one of my favorite backs was Jamaal Williams. He earned the No.6 spot on my board—ahead of Aaron Jones, Kareem Hunt, James Conner, and Alvin Kamara.


    He earned this spot ahead of these runners because I thought he had better acceleration and quickness than his NFL Combine data indicated. I also thought this was true of Samaje Perine, who I also ranked in the same range as Williams.


    Although Williams has held his own as a committee back with Jones, his acceleration and quickness have not translated as I projected. The same is obviously true with Perine.


    The mistake I made has to do with projection. I veered away from my metric thresholds and projected improvement in two athletic areas—acceleration and change of direction quickness.


    I did this after the NFL Combine when Williams’ acceleration and elusiveness scores fell just shy of the tier I ultimately placed him. I noted this in the publication, explaining that I believed Williams and Perine would improve in these areas with additional training.


    The problem is that they had already done enough work for me to see that if they were going to make significant gains it would have happened during that event or a Pro Day.


    Williams hasn’t been a bust, but he hasn’t shut the door on his competition thus far and there’s only the slimmest of chances that he will in the future. Perine has completely under-performed my expectations.

    I share this to inform you that Alexander Mattison reminds me a lot of what I thought I saw in Williams in 2017. This time, there’s no projection on my part—the NFL Combine data for acceleration and change of direction match, if not exceed, what I incorrectly projected for Williams’ athletic development.


    To be clear, I’m not projecting possible improvement for Mattison’s athleticism. His tiers for acceleration and change of direction quickness are 100 percent earned.


    He’s an underrated runner with an all-around game. The biggest thing he lacks is long speed.


    He’s a smooth mover who adjusts his stride and pace to set up creases as a zone runner. However, he’s versatile enough to run gap or zone. Like most top backs, he understands when to be decisive and hit a crease and when to be patient and set up a block.


    Mattison has excellent footwork. He executes timely jump cuts away from penetration and has quick enough stop- start footwork to freeze defenders while in the crease.


    Mattison dips away from penetration, executes effective spins, and knows how to reduce his shoulder from reaches as he does so. When transitioning from East- West to North-South, Mattison only needs a step or two to make the move.


    He has the hip mobility to point the toe, open the hips, and make a sharp turn at a good rate of speed. He often runs with a slashing style.


    However, Mattison doesn’t rely solely on hard cuts and stop-start movement. He can use curvilinear movement to bend away from oncoming defenders.


    Mattison’s comfort level and footing on poor field conditions is impressive. He put on a bad weather display of agile footwork in heavy snow at the end of the year.


    Although Mattison appears to have a slim build, he’s a sturdy 221 pounds and wins collisions against the big boys. He’ll take on middle linebackers head-on and win the collision with good pad level for a gain of 3-4 yards after the hit. He can do the same to a defensive tackle in the crease and earn at least 1-2 yards of push.


    When these same war daddies wrap Mattison high, he displays the strength to pull through wraps and even drag them for a yard or two. This takes explosive acceleration and strength.


    His functional strength during collisions is even more striking against defensive backs. Here’s a highlight of Mattison playing the boat and a defensive back playing the part of the flailing water skier dragged across the green and blue waters of Air Force’s turf.


    In terms of strength and explosion, there was a contest this year where the defense needed a defensive tackle, linebacker, and defensive back to push Mattison backwards when they met in the hole. This isn’t to imply that Mattison is Adrian Peterson incarnate. However, Mattison is a strong back with good body lean who attacks defenders in direct collisions and wins against linebackers.


    He’s a back with starter size who knows how to win in tight spaces with his pads, a stiff-arm, or his legs. As the game unfolds, Mattison begins running through multiple tackle attempts as he accumulates carries.


    He’s quick enough to reach the edge and then cut down- hill off a safety attempting to contain the play. He won’t earn routine gains of 40 yards but, like Rodney Anderson, he’ll be an effective “doubles hitter,” earning 10-15 multiple times in a game and, if the defense is worn down and loses discipline with containment, will exploit it for even longer gains.


    Mattison earned 55 receptions during his past two seasons with Boise State. He catches with his hands and can take contact to his back as he’s securing the ball.


    Mattison extends well for the ball away from his frame. He also makes catches on targets arriving at odd angles to his frame -- like his back hip while breaking away from the ball.


    His routes from the slot require more attention to detail. His whip route and flat route weren’t precise and he failed to win separation because he used a spin for his breaks or failed to sell the off coverage with a compelling stem.


    A runner with good ball security, Mattison carries the ball high to his chest and uses the arm away from pursuit.

    Mattison is more consistent than most backs when it comes to practicing sound ball security throughout the course of a run.


    He recognizes blitzes well. He showed a good slide across the face of the quarterback in the pocket to get a push on the blitzing linebacker to force him just outside the quarterback. Mattison is willing to deliver his pads against a defensive tackle trying to execute a twist to the edge of the pocket.


    Mattison’s blocking has positives, but consistency and more attention to details are needed for him to challenge for significant playing time in an offense that needs him to pass protect. He can set fast and deliver a strong uppercut punch on blitzing linebackers. This includes rolling his hips through the punch to generate force.


    Then there are plays where Mattison will dip his head toward the collision and lead with his forearms or shoulder instead of a punch. On other plays, he’ll lean too much into a punch. Although the results were there, the processes were not ideal when projecting for more skillful NFL pass rushers. Mattison can also miss the occasional blitz pick-up, not spotting the pre-snap indication that a blitz was coming.


    I expect Mattison will be, at best, a third- or fourth-round selection. Because he’ll lack the draft capital to earn an immediate opportunity to start without blowing away the coaching staff this summer, it may be a year or two before he earns a shot to show his full potential as a lead back.


    Although not remotely factored into his grade, another positive for Mattison’s development is that he’s a grounded individual with a tight family bond that didn’t

    crumble when the unit dealt with financial adversity. Whether Mattison and his family were renting a home or moved in with extended family, he still excelled in school.


    A native of San Bernardino, California—known as California’s most dangerous city due to high rate of poverty and gang-related violence—Mattison enrolled in an immersive program that taught courses in Spanish and English. Fluent in Spanish, Mattison graduated summa cum laude with a 4.6 GPA—although personally, I’m more impressed he learned Trig in Spanish.


    You can learn more about Mattison and his high school



    education here. Mattison is a smart kid with purpose and lots of practice at preparation for long-range accomplishments. I’ll bet on his success.


    Mattison would be good fit in Chicago as Tarik Cohen’s long-term complement. Mattison could be a more compelling replacement to Mark Ingram in New Orleans than Latavius Murray. I’ve mentioned in various podcasts that Mattison is a good mix of Aaron Jones and Jamaal Williams—if he winds up in Green Bay, he’ll face a tough battle. However, he might come out the biggest winner.


    If Oakland wants to maintain a power component to its run game, Mattison will be a good match if Isaiah Crowell or Chris Warren III doesn’t earn serious consideration. Of course Chicago had the right idea when it brought him in for a visit. He’d also serve as an excellent No.2 in Atlanta to Devonta Freeman—and possibly take the job and never give it back if Freeman is breaking down.


    RSP Boiler Room: Alexander Mattison


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Go into drafting Mattison with expectations that he won’t deliver weekly production until his second or third season. This may change if a team drafts him earlier, and he earned a team visit to Chicago—an indication some teams have a strong grade on him.


    Tier III: This trio of backs could earn strong starter volume one day, but their likeliest ceilings will come as high-volume contributors. In the right scheme, they could become every-down starters.


  5. Bruce Anderson, North Dakota State (5-11, 210)


    Depth of Talent Score: 80.3 = Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths (on the cusp of Contributor Tier).


    Anderson reminds me of Thurman Thomas. Like Thomas, Anderson runs with underrated balance and power. His quickness and movement makes him a mismatch as a runner and receiver, and he’s fast enough to stress a secondary.


    Anderson makes quick decisions as a gap runner and can spot and access the rare cutback lane on trap plays.

    When running split zone, he can weave between the tackles, then burst through and out to the flat so suddenly that pursuit has to work hard to reach him. He’s even skilled pressing creases outside-in, in addition to

    the traditional inside-out. He will give a little fake dip to that outside area before breaking inside.


    Anderson is a patient runner. If a power scheme doesn’t operate on-time, he can create a liittle more time for his teammates without veering off course. He can press and cut a second time when he’s past the line of scrimmage and facing down linebackers and safeties.


    He adjusts his stride length whenever necessary to generate space and runs with his knees high to avoid shots to his feet and ankles. He uses this technique to avoid penetration at the line, punctuate his position, and accelerate thorugh the opening. He often avoids multiple points of penetration with smart footwork.


    Anderson points the toe and opens his hips for sharp changes of direction from North-South to East-West or vice versa. He only needs 1-2 steps to transition downhill. He does this well after tightly pressing the line of scrimmage and it helps him win the edge on bounce- outs.


    He’s patient and sets up creases with strong footwork with plays such as counter, sweep, and outside zone.


    He has a good feel for ducking under wraps and spinning his way for extra yards when finishing a run in traffic. He uses this technique to eliminate good angles by defensive tackles in the hole. He has stop-start quickness while in the crease. Anderson can also drop his weight, maintaining a flat back for a sudden stop and turn. He keeps his feet from crossing on lateral moves when sliding outside defenders.


    He consistently beats safeties with his speed in the open field. He isn’t a top breakaway threat, but he has deep speed and it doesn’t take much for him to win angles in the secondary. He’s a productive return specialist and a special teams ace on kick coverage. He ran an 11.05- second 100 meters and 22.34-second 200 meters in high school.


    Anderson’s balance is one of the reasons he has potential to become a lead back or even a starter in the right system. He runs through direct contact against safeties and even generates a small push against defensive linemen.


    When facing contact from an indirect angle, he can win against all three levels of defenders. However, because of the level of competition he faced, giving Anderson full credit as a star caliber athlete in this area of balance is too much.


    His technique and strength as a power runner is befitting the starter tier. He gets his pads under defenders when finishing and can pull through wraps of large linebackers wrapped at his waist in the crease. He’ll stalemate legit- sized linemen.


    If defenders reach for him, he’ll break through them—and will do so multiple times within the same run. He extends his body through contact to bleed every yard when he’s in finishing mode.


    Anderson is a maestro with a straight-arm. He uses it to set up spins. He can shorten it like a sawed-off shotgun

    and deliver the forearm shiver. He often uses it as a weapon to attack first at the collision point. His stiff-arm has the placement and sturdiness to work past defensive ends.


    Anderson fumbled the ball at a rate of once every 191 touches. He’s good at switching the ball to the arm away from defensive pursuit and he’ll cover it with both arms in traffic. His carriage is a little loose at the elbow when not in traffic but otherwise high and tight. His technique has withstood a lot of hits to the ball as an interior runner, receiver, and return specialist.


    He’s an adept cut-blocker when pass protecting. He can work inside-out on defensive ends and linebackers and work across their legs. He is aware of delayed blitzes and late pressure after working double-team assignments.


    He’ll square defenders and extend hands into defenders, including defensive ends. He squats well enough at the point of attack to push and roll through his hips as a method of generating power even if the punch isn’t well- timed.


    He maintains his position well against smaller linebackers after initial contact and it helps double-up his punches and direct his opponents outside the pocket. Against larger linebackers and defensive linemen, his punch technique breaks down and he tends to drop his head into the effort. When punching these defenders, his uppercuts only have the pop of light jabs.


    When needed in the run game, Anderson delivers as well. He’s a capable lead blocker and will work to a defender on the edge with a stalk block and cut off the opponent’s angle to the ball carrier.


    Anderson is an adept threat on intermediate and deep routes against zone and off-man coverage. He can track the ball over his head and adjust to high throws. He even displays the awareness to shield defenders as he pulls the ball down.


    Anderson has a good catch radius and can extend fully for the ball while maintaining boundary technique with both feet inbounds. He’s a frequent weapon on bullet routes up the seam, and wheel routes in the flats and sidelines. He’ll also work from the slot on post and corner routes—even running the occasional out.


    He’s a mismatch for linebackers on these routes and able to swipe past linebackers trying to reroute him. In the shallow zones, he was uncoverable during the first day of Senior Bowl practices before a minor injury sidelined him.


    He missed 5 of 14 games in 2016 due to a pair of ankle sprains. Otherwise, Anderson has proven durable, versatile, and productive. He won’t be regarded as a top prospect in the draft, because he’s a small-school player.


    He didn’t get a chance to truly wow onlookers during the pre-draft process and his lack of time at the Senior Bowl probably led to an NFL Combine snub (and there were a lot of unfortunate choices this year). Still, Anderson’s work appears to be starter quality.


    If I’m incorrect, I’ve overestimated the level of competition. However, the FCS has good football players

    that have made the successful jump to the NFL. Anderson will be one of them.


    RSP Film Room: Bruce Anderson In-Depth

    RSP Boiler Room: The Tackle-Breaking Benefits of Good Ball Security


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Want a premiere wide receiver and/or tight end prospect and still get a shot at a starter talent at running back? Anderson might be the target that makes this strategy work. I bet he’ll be drafted late enough by an NFL team that he’ll be available in the third round of fantasy drafts—if not later.


  6. Darwin Thompson, Utah State (5-8, 200)


    Depth of Talent Score: 80.3 = Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths (on the cusp of Contributor Tier).


    This guy has been sitting in the RSP’s Top 10 for a while. He’s a freakish athlete whose purported 4.4-second, 40- yard dash shows up pretty easily on tape (he ran 4.5 seconds at is Pro Day). He has a recorded vertical leap of

    40.5 inches, which is an indicator of explosive leg strength. Then there’s his ability to squat 515 pounds for 7 reps.


    Most impressive, this leg strength and explosiveness shows up on this 200-pound, running back’s tape.

    Repeatedly. There are Tarik Cohen comparisons thrown out there, but Cohen is shiftier and a more dynamic receiver.


    Thompson is a good receiver. He’s also more powerful than Cohen.


    During a lost episode of the RSP Film Room with occasional contributor Eric Stoner, we were studying Donnell Pumphrey, the star back from San Diego State who drew comparison to Darren Sproles. More small backs get compared to Sproles and Warrick Dunn—and don’t come close to measuring up—than any other 1:1 comparison I see during a draft season.


    So, we pulled some tape of Sproles at Kansas State. After watching his strength, balance, footwork, and vision used to its fullest capacity, we concluded that if Sproles had his same athletic ability with Marshawn Lynch’s height and weight, Sproles would be as good as Lynch.


    Or better, because he’s quicker and faster than Lynch.


    Darwin Thompson is closer in style to Sproles than he is Cohen. He’s also bigger and stronger than Sproles at close to Sproles’ height. The listed height above is how Utah State listed him—and colleges are notorious exaggerators of this data.


    The point isn’t that Thompson is a mini-Beast Mode. It’s that he’s a freakishly strong and balanced runner with breakaway speed, strong acceleration, and third-down skills. He may not be the public’s traditional idea of a starting-caliber prospect, but he can become a significantly productive weapon the way Cohen has blossomed in Chicago—or as Sproles did with the Chargers and Saints years prior.

    Thompson runs gap plays and zone plays with patience and has the ability to find the appropriate cutbacks for both schemes. He’s light on his feet and has flexible hips for sudden turns and sharp cuts. Like most of the backs discussed in this range, he can transition East-West to North-South with a sharp cut.


    His cuts are precise enough to work tight creases or find difficult cutback lanes while navigating penetration at the line of scrimmage or the backfield. Occasionally, Thompson may try one cut too many when the defense has done good work to contain gaps. However, he’s quick and wise enough to minimize the fallout and get down- hill for a short gain rather than compound the issue with a bounce-out for a loss.


    He’s an especially patient outside runner. He has the acceleration to take the short corner and get downhill and the speed to work the long corner. Once in traffic and heading downhill, Thompson varies his stride length to work around pursuit.


    He’ll also set up cutbacks or bounces with stop-start moves, jump cuts, and jump stops. He’ll occasionally jump cut in situations where he could be more efficient by pointing his toe where he wants to go and flipping his hips. This would prevent him from jumping towards the pursuit he’s trying to avoid.


    Just as impressive as his zone and gap patience is his willingness to hit creases hard. He’ll take a small crease on a trap play and hit it so decisively that he’s blowing past the linebackers and challenging the safeties more quickly than the average back.


    He can challenge the fastest corner on any run and he times his acceleration well—sometimes not flipping the switch until he’s already in the secondary. And his acceleration is notable.


    When he’s in the open field, Thompson uses head fakes and dips to set up defenders. He’ll use some of that freakish vertical leap to hurdle defenders near the boundary.


    Thompson’s leg strength grounds him when he takes on contact. This might be the most impressive—and occasionally confounding—part of his game.


    Thompson’s leg strength, pad level, and leverage are why 60 percent of his yardage in 2018 came after contact. Again, yards after contact includes “fly-swatter hits” that grazes a ball carrier. Even so, the extreme data point is an indication of Thompson’s power and balance.


    Whether it is a linebacker, defensive end, or defensive tackle, I’ve seen Thompson repeatedly pull through reaches and wraps around his waist. He’ll take 300- pound linemen for a ride on his back for gains of 2-5 yards—and sometimes more.


    Whether working downhill or to the edge, Thompson has broken through linebacker’s wraps to his torso and stiff- armed defensive linemen to the ground after they tried to reach him in the backfield. Edge rushers wrapping Thompson’s thighs frequently slide off them.

    His pad level in the crease is low enough for him to squirt past the reach of pursuit. When he hits a crease hard and squares up, he has stalemated a defensive tackle until his teammates arrived to generate a push. Thompson keeps his feet moving through contact and he’ll extend through collisions and wraps for an extra 2-3 yards.


    Thompson likes using the forearm shiver. He leads collisions with his forearm and will rock safeties backward when he can achieve good placement of it.


    Despite his size, Thompson’s blocking isn’t a liability. He can work inside the chest of a defensive end and deliver a forceful chip. He squares his targets and delivers an effective uppercut punch. He identifies edge pressure, cross blitzes, and stunts.


    His legs are strong enough that he can anchor a defensive tackle long enough that the tackle has to change his move to a one-arm technique to earn better leverage. While he didn’t stop the tackle, it’s impressive to see Thompson slow an opponent of this size and force an adjustment. He can fall in the trap of leaning and extending into the largest opponents rather than trusting his position and punch.


    Thompson only fumbled 1 in 176 touches, which is on the cusp of star-caliber ball security. He uses the arm that’s away from the pursuit but the technique can get a little loose at the chest and the elbow.


    Thompson has the speed to earn wheel and bullet routes. He tracks the ball over his shoulder. However, he has tracked a deeper route over the wrong shoulder and missed an opportunity.


    Thompson uses the correct hand techniques for the location of the target. He can make back-shoulder catches and high-point targets. Wherever he catches the ball, he transitions quickly downfield.


    Widely considered a NFL Combine snub, Thompson is still on a lot of team’s radars. He probably won’t be drafted in a round commensurate with his talent and potential.


    Thompson would be a good fit for teams that run outside zone, gap plays, or use spread concepts from shotgun or pistol. There’s a danger he’ll turn into a gadget for an offensive coordinator who constantly loses his clicker in the couch cushion of the facility’s film room. But Thompson has the ability to be a productive big-play contributor with consistent volume is there.


    Dion Lewis is 5-8, 195 and not nearly as sturdy and still has been a compelling producer. Thompson is a true 200 pounds.


    RSP Twitter Analysis



    Darwin Thompson Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Unless a team goes all- in on Thompson as a Cohen-Sproles option and intends to use him as a centerpiece, he’s likely a fourth- or fifth- round draft pick, at best. With that low draft capital, it may take time for him to prove his worth.

    He’ll be a fourth or fifth-round option in leagues and likely a waiver stash. If he’s a UDFA, you’ll want to monitor from afar.

  7. Elijah Holyfield, Georgia. (5-10, 217) Depth of Talent Score: 80 = Rotational Starter:

    Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths (on the cusp of Contributor Tier).


    Holyfield reminds me of a quicker and taller Travis Henry, whose running style was once described as a bowling ball of knives. Holyfield is on the cusp of the starter- contributor talent scale. He lacks speed and his NFL Combine performance in the 40-Yard Dash shouldn’t have been a major surprise to anyone who studied his game.


    Holyfield’s game is all acceleration and he has no extra gear after those first 20 yards to separate from defenders. However, his acceleration, balance, power, agility, and vision are all good enough for him to produce for an NFL team—and with volume.


    Holyfield runs inside zone well enough to press creases and bounce it outside as needed. He’s adept at changing his stride length to set up openings with patience. He does this well as he reaches the cutback point on off- tackle plays or when reading line slants in anticipation of a cutback or bounce-out.


    Although not a speedster, his burst is good enough to be effective on runs to the edge. He’s going to be better running to the short corner, but his vision and change of direction is good enough that he won’t be a liability running to the long side of the field, either.


    Most teams will prize Holyfield for his work between the tackles or off-tackle. He adjusts competently to backfield penetration and doesn’t abandon downhill opportunities.


    When creases are set up quickly, Holyfield will hit them hard. He will split defenders to get down hill as he takes the edge. He shows some patience to stay inside after bouncing outside penetration, but doesn’t take the corner until he presses inside to leverage the safety.


    Holyfield displays the selectiveness to be aware of a potential bounce-out opportunity but sticks with a wiser course between the tackles. When creases are limited, Holyfield will work to a soft spot and push into his linemen.


    When he works to the outside, his acceleration is good enough to beat box safeties or outside linebackers to the edge and pull through any reaches to his frame.

    Holyfield’s cuts also have excellent quickness which, paired with his physical style and intensity makes him toughest to handle within the first 10-15 yards of the line.


    Holyfield’s stiff-arm lacks a quality punch because he doesn’t have great timing with it. At best, he wards off contact and forces the opponent to slide down to Holyfield’s ankles.


    His forearm shiver is a better weapon. He cinches it high to his chest and leans the same-side shoulder into

    defenders so he can connect with it. Holyfield uses that forearm as his means of first-contact to punish opponents.


    He’s a strong and intense runner who will pull through reaches at the line of scrimmage and the occasional wraps of a defensive linemen. He is a pile pusher who will drive forward when wrapped and bounce off glanching contact. Linebackers and safeties often lose confrontations with Holyfield. I have seen him push a defensive tackle backwards a couple of yards during a direct collision in the crease.


    Holyfield also has the quickness and explosion to spin off contact or even hurdle it. It’s also the basis for his starter-caliber footwork and elusiveness.


    Holyfield can transition from East-West to North-South with one hard cut and not lose much speed. His jump cuts are dynamic enough to bounce to the backside corner when needed or make penetration miss in the backfield. Holyfield can jump-cut from penetration and one step later turn 90 degrees to the sideline and take the corner.


    His downhill cuts are sharp and he’ll pair them with his stiff arm or shoulder lean/forearm shiver combo to ward off contact in the hole. His hip mobility is good and he knows how to point his toe in the direction he wants to turn and make the sharp change of direction.


    Holyfield also employs head fakes, stop-start moves, and pivots to avoid pursuit. He can execute slalom cuts in succession to weave through creases up the middle.


    His decision-making is a good blend of patience and aggression and he’s skilled with gap and zone schemes. Because he’s so explosive and punishing early in runs, he can be an effective gap runner in the NFL despite lacking the breakaway speed that man gap runners possess.

    Split zone is also a good blocking scheme for him.


    Holyfield carries the ball high and tight to his chest and uses the correct arm for the side he intends to run. When appropriate to do so, he’ll switch the ball to the opposite arm during a run. He can take a hit to the ball and maintain possession. His elbow can be a little tighter.


    Holyfield should eventually endear himself to a team as a pass protector. He squares up his opponents consistently and moves well laterally against edge pressure. When he reads an edge rusher take an inside path, he’ll step up and deliver a well-positioned punch.


    He spots corner blitzes and works quickly to the spot so he can cut off the pressure. When linebackers blitz up the middle, he’ll hold his ground with minimal backwards movement.


    Holyfield’s uppercut lacks optimal power, because he doesn’t roll through his hips when he punches. He must learn to sustain his contact and control his opponents more often. He has a desire to blow up his assignment at the point of attack and will abandon a punch to do this— or his punches don’t transition well to locking onto his opponent.

    Holyfield catches the ball with his hands and uses the appropriate techniques for the target location. He was primarily used as an outlet receiver on wide routes, flat routes, and swing routes.


    Other than time missed in 2015 with an ankle injury, Holyfield has remained healthy.


    Although a good running back, the NFL will have a polarizing opinion of him as a starter. There will be a small contingent of teams that question whether he has starter talent, but the more salient debate will be if Holyfield is skilled enough to warrant using a high draft pick worthy of a lead back.


    I don’t think teams will see enough lead back potential to draft Holyfield early. It’s the problem that Henry and C.J. Anderson faced as starter talents who lack that sizzle because they can’t author breakaway runs. Holyfield will likely produce whenever he has an opportunity and wherever he goes. The problem is that there’s an increased likelihood that he goes to multiple places during his career in search of an opportunity to be the man—and it will never last long enough.


    Elijah Holyfield Highlights



    RSP Boiler Room: Elijah Holyfield


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Holyfield may have high fantasy demand at various points in his career. But that value may be fleeting and sporadic. He’s not a great bargain in the second round. If you can get in him the third or fourth round, he’s a better deal based on the Anderson-Henry issue stated above.


    Tier IV: The next 13 players could easily belong in the third tier because they have starter or high-end contributor potential. They also have one or two flaws that might require more work before they can earn a consistent workload. Depending on their NFL landing spot, they may never reach their potential.


  8. Miles Sanders, Penn State (5-11, 211)


    Depth of Talent Score: 79 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope (on the cusp of Rotational Starter Tier).


    Emerging from the titanic shadow that is Saquon Barkley’s legacy in Happy Valley, Sanders managed an impressive showing. There’s no sense in comparing Barkley and Sanders, but it doesn’t make Sanders a bad NFL prospect.


    One of the immediate obstacles Sanders must overcome is a desire to play like Barkley when he isn’t that type of player. If he can slightly alter his decision-making to fit his skills and most importantly protect the ball, Sanders can become an NFL starter.


    If he acclimates quickly, Sanders could be a factor for an offense this year. He’s a shifty runner with speed, receiving skills, and enough functional power to do all the work demanded of him between the tackles.

    Sanders operates with good pad level. He’s not going to push defensive tackles and linebackers with tremendous frequency, but he is strong enough to push a pile and sustain productive volume as an inside runner.


    Sanders’ best work comes when he gets to the other side of a crease. He will drop the pads low enough to get under the chest of defensive backs in the open field. He earns accurate placement with his stiff-arms and they’re good enough to knock safeties to the turf. If the stiff-arm isn’t an option, Sanders also spins off contact effectively and falls forward.


    Sanders’ game is quickness through the first level to minimize contact. If he can earn creases where the only contact are reaches and wraps to his lower legs, Sanders wins these interactions and is off to the second level.

    When this happens, the fun begins.


    A lot of people don’t understand what it means to run with a wiggle. It means that the runner’s gait is relaxed enough that it’s a little loose. This helps him make ancillary movements that can bait defenders into poor angles.


    Boxers call it “sugar” after famed fighter Sugar Ray Robinson, who could operate with this loose movement that supported fluid action while also throwing off opponents. Runners with a wiggle to their gait often have success in one-on-ones with defenders.


    Sanders runs with a wiggle. He also has the stop-start quickness to avoid penetration into the backfield and get downhill afterwards.


    Blessed with excellent hip mobility, Sanders points the toe in a direction to open his hips for dramatic turns with economy. He can also flip his hips in tight spaces on outside runs and cut downhill within the next step.


    His footwork complements his hip flexibility and peripheral vision. Sanders also alters his stride length and pacing to set up creases in tight spaces and can then bend at the knees to drop his weight to shift towards the open crease—all the while, keeping his pads low if he needs to work under or spin off contact.


    Sanders is quick enough to run gap plays and he’s also a skilled cutback artist with zone plays. He’s good at working to his left or right with zone plays. Despite having quickness and agility, he’s a disciplined runner who often takes what’s available at the line of scrimmage.


    When there’s a need and opportunity to win with dramatic action, Sanders excels. He reads the penetration and has the jump cuts and 90-degree turns to work away from oncoming defenders shooting the gap and continue through the crease. He’ll set up these 90- degree cuts downhill with variations of pacing.


    His slalom cuts have a deep bend and earn dynamic range of movement to his left or right. Sanders is also explosive enough to hurdle defenders without much lead time to the hurdle point.


    He’s capable of sequencing a dynamic movement alongside an efficient one to work inside or outside an

    oncoming opponent and immediate get downhill. Does an offense need Sanders to leap over the goal line? Done.

    Does it need him to drop his pads and push a bank vault door of human flesh a yard? He can do that, too.


    Sanders can combine his explosive movements with physicality. He’ll use a head fake or juke to set up a leverage advantage with a stiff-arm that will knock a defender to the ground.


    His footwork is precise enough to side-step stray body parts in creases while still following his linemen. This skill reminds me of Cadillac Williams when he started at Auburn.


    Run blitzes and defenders shooting gaps can get the better of him when he can’t process the movement fast enough. He’s a little slow reading these blitzes and figuring out how to attack them. The same is true of any early penetration that disrupts gap plays like the counter.


    While his processing needs to improve against pressure, Sanders has excellent quickness. He can beat all three levels of defenders in pursuit and from a lot of angles.


    Sanders will make defensive backs miss who have an angle when they fill the crease from an angle over the top. He can do the same against them as he works outside of them to the flat.


    Sanders outruns linebackers to the short corner and gets downhill. On runs to the long corner, he can earn a slight angle on an outside linebacker. He has trouble beating defensive backs on attempts to reach the long corner.

    He’s a quick accelerator and has good speed but a safety with a good angle will handle that early acceleration and make the play.


    Sanders is a competent pass protector at the college level with a little more work to do to become a good blocker in the pro game. He can work across the pocket to handle corner blitzes. He’ll also deliver chips with a hard shoulder into the body of the opponent.


    Squaring his opponents is the strength of his game. He squares well at the edge of the defense or when he climbs the pocket to greet a linebacker.


    He moves his feet well enough to force the edge rush further outside. He identifies the proper assignment on a cross blitz.


    When Sanders gets his hands on opponents he’ll push. He must learn to punch with force rather than push, or lead with his shoulder. This shoulder-based method of attack leads to him tipping off his blocks and giving defenders time to redirect or he has no method to stop his opponents from bouncing off him on the way to the quarterback.


    An offense will want to use Sanders more often as a receiver. He catches the ball with proper hands technique, keeps his eyes on the ball until he secures it to his frame, and transitions well downfield. He can make the back-shoulder turn and his acceleration and speed makes him a mismatch for linebackers and safeties.

    Sanders uses a high carriage technique with the ball and totes the ball under his left or right arm based on his path and the defensive pursuit. Still, his ball security is the most significant concern with his game.


    Sanders fumbled the ball 10 times in 346 touches. This is the worst of any prospect studied this year. Although five fumbles occurred during his first 97 touches, the next five during his final 249 still would have placed him in the same tier of rampantly bad technique.


    The ball comes loose too often as he’s attempting dynamic movement or in the open field. He must become more diligent or else he’ll face a similar fate as an even more promising prospect like former Giants runner David Wilson.


    Sanders could have easily been the No.4 back on the RSP’s board, but a bad history with ball security isn’t usually met with patience from coaches. It also messes with the minds of players and can wreck promising careers.


    For perspective, Sony Michel practiced sound technique like Sanders and still had a rate of 1 per 59.5. Michel played last year for the same coach who had to bench perpetual fumbler, Stevan Ridley. Michel only fumbled once in 216 touches.


    Sanders is a promising player. Let’s hope he fixes this issue before opponents fixate on the ball more than they already do.


    Pittsburgh, Tampa Bay, Oakland, Atlanta, and San Francisco could all be decent fits for Sanders from a schematic perspective.


    Miles Sanders Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Sanders will be a consensus top-10 back in this class with a range as high as one of the top 3 and as low as the 7-10 range. I like his game and if Michel is a reasonable case study, there’s reason not to be too consumed with the fumbling issue if you’re drafting Sanders as a long-term investment. If you’re hoping to win now with Sanders, you may opt for a more conservative selection because for every Michel there’s a Wilson and Ameer Abdullah.


    Although my colleague Adam Harstad notes that fumble stats aren’t predictive of more fumbles, ball security woes have a cause-and-effect with fumbling on the field. There may not be an accurate determination of how the rate increase or decreases at this time, but until there’s proof otherwise, I’ll consider bad ball security in traffic a common sense cause for fumbling.

  9. Jacques Patrick, Florida State (6-3, 234)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.9 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    I’m a fan of this big, tough, and versatile team player. Patrick is a better runner than credited, because he worked in the shadow of Cam Akers and before Akers, Dalvin Cook. He also played in the middle of a coaching transition at FSU.


    Patrick is good at what one would expect from a back of his dimensions, which hasn’t always been the case in recent years with big men. He generates movement in collisions with defensive linemen and linebackers. He can win direct collisions with all three levels of the defense.


    When faced with bouncing a run outside or lowering the pads and taking on a defender at the line of scrimmage, Patrick will opt for the one-on-one, physical confrontation. Although he’s a tall runner, he will drop the pads and attack his opponents so he can hit and slide over top for extra yardage.


    Box defenders that wrap Patrick will get taken for a ride around the block. Defenders in the secondary that hop aboard will need a passport.


    Patrick can break multiple reaches, wraps, and hits during the course of a run. He is the best power back in this class and few are talking about it. It’s probably because he earned criticism at some point during his college career for not using his size to his advantage.


    Patrick does a good job of splitting defenders and working through small creases with good pad level— including defensive linemen. He’s nimble and powerful enough that he can cut downhill from an East-West path and still run through a linebacker.


    Patrick has a capable stiff-arm that he can use to generate a push when meeting a defender head-on. When he loses his balance, he’s flexible enough to balance-touch to regain his footing.


    Hip flexibility and footwork are the most underrated aspects of his game and it’s why he could surprise as a productive runner. Patrick drops his weight and makes sharp down-hill cuts. Combined with facile displays of stride variation to avoid penetration and redirect to a crease, Patrick is a nimble runner with tremendous control of his feet.


    When penetration reaches the exchange point, Patrick displays the refinement to point the toe and open his hips towards an escape without a jump cut. There are many NFL backs that don’t possess this awareness and skill.

    Patrick also runs with his knees high to keep his feet away from reaches for his ankles in the hole.


    In 2016 and 2018, his burst showed up on tape, but not so much in 2017. Patrick tore cartilage in his knee in 2017 and only missed two games when he discovered there wasn’t any ligament damage. This could have been a contributing factor.

    The positive exposures of Patrick’s burst reveal a back that can freeze linebackers with stop-start movement and then sprint past them to the short corner and up the sideline. Patrick is not a burner, but he can read the line, stop fast, maintain good balance, find open space, and re-accelerate to reach the hole. This is strong work for any college prospect.


    His footwork and functional quickness to execute small jump cuts, drop his weight into quick stops, and step over fallen bodies, makes him a capable runner from shotgun and pistol alignments. When he reaches the edge on perimeter runs, he can cut downhill with 90- degree turns thanks to his flexible hips.


    Patrick also has a nice lateral cut where he uses his free arm to swipe past a defender over top. When he first began running from pistol, he pattered his feet to set up changes of direction and it limited his transition time downhill. He was also late to make cutbacks on counter plays from the formation.


    Patrick’s best fit is as a single back or behind a fullback in the I-formation. However, he improved his work from spread alignments and makes subtle and dynamic adjustments that lead to production.


    Still, put Patrick in the I-formation, and he’s good at ISO, off-tackle, and inside zone plays. He squeezes through small creases and manipulates the defense with pacing and adjustments to his stride length to set up his lead blocker.


    He has enough acceleration to extend a run nearly 70 yards when he breaks through a defense stacked at the line of scrimmage. He can hold off pursuit for 40-45 yards.


    Patrick is a mature runner. When cut off at the edge by penetration, he won't try to outrun them. Instead, he'll take the mature route to stay up the middle, taking what he can get.


    Patrick has the size and feet to become a blocker on the skill level of L.J. Scott, the best pass protector in this class. He can slide inside-out to attack defensive ends working around the edge of the pocket and is quick enough to force a wider path with his movement.


    Patrick moves quickly enough across the pocket to square a linebacker blitzing from the edge. He extends his hands to deliver a push and will try the uppercut punch with assignments up the middle.


    The uppercut motion is there, but the roll of the hips is not. It can lead to him getting hit first rather than delivering the first strike. He also drops his head too often into his blocks and overextends his frame.


    His cut blocks earn good position across the opponent’s frame, but he can aim a little higher. He’s also a beat slow with recognizing linemen twists and stunts.


    Patrick is a reliable receiver and a good check-down outlet. He catches the ball with his hands away from his frame and tracks it well over his shoulder.

    He baits defenders with slow movements to set up the screen and then snaps into a quick break for the target. Patrick will make the catch with his back to an opponent and take contact while doing so.


    His ball security needs improvement. He fumbled the ball 1 every 82 touches, squarely in the committee tier for runners. He uses the correct arm to keep the ball away from pursuit, but he lets the ball swing too loose at the elbow and away from the chest—especially after he’s hit the first time by a defender.


    Although earning a five-star rating as a recruit is far from a guarantee of a productive pro career as a starter, it’s often a distinction that the player is an advanced athlete when he enters the college ranks.
