Patrick was a five-star recruit and Rivals’ and ESPN’s No.3 back in the 2015 class.


    Big-time recruits sometimes earn the reputation as divas who don’t work. Patrick is known as a selfless teammate with an excellent work ethic. These types of players often stick to NFL rosters. With the skills he possesses, he has the kind of profile to emerge from draft anonymity as a Sunday contributor.


    RSP Twitter Vids on Jacques Patrick RSP Boiler Room: Downhill Thumpin’


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Patrick will be available at the end of fantasy drafts and he’s a decent investment as a target for leagues with practice squads. Otherwise, monitor closely and be prepared to add him as a free agent if injuries create on opportunity sooner than expected.


  10. Dexter Williams, Notre Dame (5-11, 212)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.85 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Notre Dame’s rushing offense featured guards pulling wide and across Williams’ face while taking the exchange from a pistol formation. This forced him to display patience and efficient creativity in heavy traffic. Some will consider him too hesitant and prone to dancing. I saw an efficient runner.


    Williams displays cutback ability against containment on outside zone runs to transform a certain loss into a minimal gain. He sets up then squeezes through tight creases and has enough size and burst to drag a linebacker with him for a couple of yards.


    Williams needed to alter his stride a lot at Notre Dame to be successful and managed to balance it with decisive cuts downhill. He did a good job of taking what was available, rather than trying too hard to create space that wasn’t there.


    When he hits an open crease he can reach the secondary in a hurry because of his acceleration (4.16-second, 20 Shuttle at the NFL Combine). With that burst, his 4.57- second long speed is enough to maintain separation for 40-60 yards, depending on the location of defensive backs when he reaches the third level of the defense.

    This acceleration allows him to reach the edge with relative ease. His 7.00 second Three-Cone time is a reflection of starter-caliber change of direction quickness. He can transition downhill within 1-2 steps. He can jump cut as well as drop his weight to come to sudden stops and make sharp turns.


    These two athletic displays help Williams beat defensive backs to the flat and leave them at a standstill. Whether it is inside or outside zone, Williams displays patience and when he can make one cut downhill, he can break big plays.


    Williams has the size to hold up between the tackles but he’s more of a “creaser” than a “banger.” He displayed limited skill to win direct collisions with linebackers at the end of the crease, which is a decent litmus test for every- down runners who aren’t operating from spread-heavy systems.


    Williams has the size and explosion to win direct collisions with defensive backs and generate a push. He’ll also work through indirect collisions from linebackers as well as reaches and wraps to his lower body.


    One of Williams’ better weapons to win against contact is his stiff-arm and a forearm shiver. He’ll also drop his pads and work under contact from defensive linemen and linebackers for extra yardage.


    Small creases don’t dissuade Williams from sticking with play designs. He runs zone and gap blocks effectively. I only saw him “dance” too much on a play early in a game and after that play he was far more refined and decisive with his play.


    When carrying the ball, Williams uses the arm away from defensive pursuit. He can take a hit to the ball head-on and maintain possession. His elbow can be a little loose, but his high carriage towards his chest is sound. His rate of 1 fumble per 142 touches is squarely in the starter tier for ball security.


    Williams has promise as a blocker. He can quick-set to a 45 degree angle and pick up edge blitzes by defensive backs. He delivers an effective two-hand punch against similar-sized opponents—including linebackers. He moves his feet well after the punch and can send opponents outside the path of the quarterback. He also takes good angles against defensive ends working around the edge.


    His angles on cut blocks need improvement. He’s also a step slow on reading some blitzes and arrives late.


    Williams uses the correct position with his hands that correspond to the location of his targets. He also tracks the ball over his shoulder. He’s adept at the angle route that begins in the backfield, widens the linebacker towards the hash during the stem of the route, and breaks back to the inside.


    Williams was suspended four games this year for an undisclosed reason. In 2016, he was one of five Notre Dame teammates arrested for marijuana possession. In 2017, Williams missed three weeks with an ankle injury and a quad contusion.

    Williams has the vision, footwork, acceleration, burst, and change of direction of a starter. A lot of backs in the NFL do. And there will be a lot more backs coming into the league that will also be bigger, faster, and break more tackles than Williams.


    Although Williams wins the Breadth of Talent tiebreaker to earn the spot ahead of Darrell Henderson, it’s Henderson that has the trump card of speed and downfield receiving skills. Of the two, Henderson will likely have more appeal because of his superior game- changing athletic ability.


    RSP Boiler Room: Downhill Thumpin’ RSP Twitter Vids: Jacques Patrick


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Williams has a shot at earning a pick between rounds 3-5 of the NFL Draft. This is the range he’ll likely be available in dynasty rookie drafts. He’s good enough to produce but is most likely a patience play this year and next.


  11. Darrell Henderson, Memphis (5-8, 208)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.85 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    If you covet breakaway threats, Henderson is one of the two most exciting running backs in this class. Watch his highlights and you’ll see him flying through the open field, pulling away from safeties and holding off the opponent’s fastest cornerback who only managed to make up ground after Henderson gained 40-60 yards.


    If Reggie Bush and Dalvin Cook walked into Dr. Frankenstein’s laboratory, Darrell Henderson would be the monster that walked out.


    All three backs are versatile players. Like Bush, Henderson can win as a vertical receiver. Like Cook, Henderson’s style of movement is underappreciated in the draft community and often criticized for what’s misunderstood as limited athletic ability.


    Running backs come in a wonderful variety of body types and styles of play. I’m still working on defining specific archetypes and am not yet ready to finalize categories, but here’s a rough sketch of five different archetypes.


    Flanker-Backs: These players look like your average- sized wide receiver—roughly 5’10” to 6’0” and weight 195-210 pounds. The have slim builds and if they wore a wide receiver uniform, you’d mistake them for a player like Robert Woods or Odell Beckham, Jr. Like Beckham, they’re extraordinarily sudden and flexible athletes with special acceleration, change of direction, and speed. They have underrated toughness at the point of contact because they often strike first to take the opponent off- balance and then run around him in tight quarters.

    They’re also gifted receivers due to their suddenness and speed. Reggie Bush and Jamaal Charles are representatives of this archetype.


    Body Punchers: These runners have thick lower bodies with powerful trunks. They run with great force but are able to make powerful and dynamic lateral cuts on a dime. Stamina is more common than speed in these

    players. Whether they are slower or faster than the average running back, they maintain a steady and powerful intensity with their movement until the play is over or they run out of steam. These backs are like the realistic embodiment of Rocky Balboa—rugged athletes who can still wear out younger peers. Marion Barber, Marshawn Lynch, and Adrian Peterson are three examples of Body Punchers who, in their primes, were slow, moderately fast, and breakaway fast, respectively.


    Power Gliders: Grace is the defining characteristic of this archetype. They appear to be gliding when they run which makes their breakaway speed, pile moving power, and rock-solid balance deceptive. They tend to run upright—even when their pads have a lean, the position of their hips and overall gait makes it appear otherwise. Even their lateral cuts appear deceptive. Eddie George, Robert Smith, and Eric Dickerson were excellent representatives of this archetype in their primes.


    Jumping Spiders: Backs who fit this description often play as if they have eight eyes that give them accentuated peripheral vision and great estimation of a defender’s range, direction, and speed of movement. They tend to be shorter players with powerfully developed legs that allow them to move with great force and uncommon agility. They’re the backs often described by coaches as “short but not small.” Their low center of gravity gives them tremendous contact balance. They’re more gifted at flipping their hips to change direction and don’t make as many hard cuts as you’d imagine and they possess run stamina that rivals the Body Punchers.

    Maurice Jones-Drew and Barry Sanders are prime examples. Although he may seem like he’s a different archetype, I think Walter Payton could be the closest thing to the human embodiment of a Jumping Spider.


    Street Bikes: A less common archetype because the larger versions of this archetype tend to be too slow for NFL preferences—James Wilder, Jr. (the CFL’s Most Outstanding Rookie in 2017). However, the smaller players are the ones that most commonly make teams in the NFL, because they possess strong acceleration and deep speed. Regardless, both types possess good balance when it comes to contact to their upper body.

    They can dish out punishment on the move and withstand hits to their torsos without losing balance. The versions we typically encounter in the NFL confound metric-heavy evaluators because they don’t depend as much on hard cuts to change direction and their explosion and change of direction drills are sometimes underwhelming. These backs maintain speed while changing direction with curvilinear movements. Think of a street motorcycle bending around a curve or a cheetah chasing its prey. I haven’t fleshed out this archetype as well as the others, but I think the Street Bike Archetype tend to have less stamina over distance. They usually don’t need it because they have just enough of it to bend a run 2-3 times while maintaining a high rate of speed that will leave defenders in the dust.


    This is where Dalvin Cook and Darrell Henderson return to the conversation.


    Henderson is a smooth runner who can get his legs over the trash of a crease without getting touched. He’ll alter his stride length to set up angles toward open space.

    Although representative of a Street Bike runner that favors curvilinear motion, this archetype isn’t solely reliant on it. Henderson can make quick cuts, execute strong jump stops at a high rate of speed, and make small but effective lateral cuts. He can also give the dead-leg juke to a defender and work around the opponent after freezing him.


    As is the case with his archetype, Henderson spins off larger defenders hitting him in the torso and he’s quick enough to avoid a wrap. Once he reaches open grass, he’s like a cheetah getting chased by lions—and yes, lions prey on cheetahs. If he’s not caught early, it’s less likely he’ll be caught at all.


    Henderson has the acceleration to work the short corner and then bend to curl his motion past the chasing linebacker and inside any defenders pursuing from over top while staying inside the boundary.


    He reads penetration well and can react with stop-starts, and jump cuts. Most often, he’ll simply open his hips and bounce the run with great economy.


    Watching how Henderson processes the direction of his opponents and executes escapes, you can see the movements most natural to his game. Although he can run behind a fullback, it’s preferable he do so on runs off- tackle or to the perimeter. If he’s working between the tackles, he needs enough of a crease to hop or slalom cut when making a move off the lead blocker.


    Henderson isn’t as effective when he has to shorten his stride and make harder cuts.


    It’s probably why Henderson’s traits make him a better fit for gap blocking. Sophisticated manipulation of box defenders and dynamic changes of direction are more important tools in zone running, and he lacks that quality of movement. It leaves him in a position where he’s hit square and knocked backwards.


    Henderson needs to practice downhill cuts and work on getting his back foot set in a more stable position during the cut. When this doesn’t happen, he slips.


    A team will get the most from Henderson early on if it uses gap. Henderson ran a lot of counter and counter draw plays at Memphis. He did show patience without outside zone plays and could be successful if some outside zone is paired with steady doses of power, counter, gap, ISO, and toss..


    As is the case with the shorter versions of this archetype, Henderson’s low center of gravity makes it difficult for opponents to knock him to the ground with hits above the waist. He’s also blessed with a momentum-aided

    stiff-arm. When he’s running at a good clip, he’ll land the stiff arm with precision and power, putting the opponent to the ground.


    He’ll also employ the forearm shiver to ward off contact in the crease. He can even drop the pads and bounce off glancing blows as he accelerates. He routinely bounced off multiple defensive backs in the open field and didn’t need as much momentum as one might expect. However, it’s even more fun to watch him accelerate into contact as he dips his shoulder into a defensive back. It’s like

    watching a fast-moving object purposely clip a slower or stationary object in its path so it can send the object flying in its wake.


    Henderson is powerful enough to force stalemates in collisions with linebackers. He also has the strength to pull through wraps to his lower body. While not nearly as effective a finisher against the front-seven of the defense, he can push through contact in the secondary for additional yardage.


    Not a powerful back, Henderson runs through wraps and spins off contact, but expecting him to win direct collisions and move the chains isn’t a smart strategy for an offensive coordinator. He has enough body lean to extend through contact but without the accompanying push and initial force of power, there’s not much value in this area of the field. Don’t expect him to create creases with force.


    Henderson carries the ball high and tight and usually with his left arm—even when he should be using his right arm. There are enough exposures where Henderson uses his right arm with similar good ball security, but he must be more conscientious about using this arm in situations where it’s optimal to do so. In addition to good ball security technique with one-arm carriage, Henderson will cover the ball with both arms as needed.


    Henderson must learn to punch to become a complete pass protector. He gets his hands in a position to deliver a push, but he allows opponents to get the first hit and he lacks the size to anchor against defenders larger than cornerbacks and small safeties.


    He’s at his best against larger opponents when he can cut block. He works across the legs accurately and can cut from a square position or on the move as the lead blocker on sprint outs.


    Henderson does a good job of squaring and shielding defenders at the edge of the pocket. When he fails, it’s often due to him becoming complacent with his movement and the defender out-hustles him to the corner.


    He’ll have to block in the NFL but any team that selects Henderson is also prizing his receiving skills. He catches the ball with proper hands position based on the location of the target.


    He patiently sets up screen passes, which will complement his tendency to shield defenders rather than punch them—baiting them into thinking they’ve made easy work of him.


    Henderson big-play receiving skill is a key reason he ranks highly. He makes back-shoulder catches look easy because he tracks the ball well and makes smooth adjustments. Taking contact and making the catch isn’t a problem, either.


    Memphis often placed Henderson in the slot and utilized his ability to catch the ball over his shoulder, near his waist, and even a little behind his frame. He’ll need to improve the sharpness of his breaks to continue earning time in the slot.

    When split wide, Henderson’s speed and acceleration will get him behind defenders that can’t or won’t put their hands on him. However, he’ll need to improve his releases or physical- and technically-sound opponents will reroute him.


    As an added bonus to his repertoire, Henderson has some skill to throw the ball on a run-pass option.

    Memphis liked using this play in the red zone.


    Although Carolina isn’t the optimal place for Henderson, he could be an excellent committee piece with Christian McCaffrey. Imagine both players in the backfield and motioning McCaffrey to the slot but still having the home run threat of Henderson engaged in the zone read with Cam Newton or motioning on a jet sweep?


    Indianapolis doesn’t need a running back, but if it wanted to consolidate the skills of Marlon Mack and Nyheim Hines and keep Jordan Wilkins as the thunder to Henderson’s lightning, it could be a great fit.


    Jacksonville’s gap-heavy scheme would make sense as would the outside zone running game of San Francisco. However, Philadelphia’s quick-hitting offense would be the best fit for Henderson. If Atlanta tries to replace Tevin Coleman so it can continue the Freeman-Coleman roles in its offense, Henderson could be a candidate there.


    Darrell Henderson Highlights



    RSP Twitter Vids: Darrell Henderson


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advise: For those comfortable with risk, Henderson is worth taking as one of the top six backs. He will likely be in demand during the first 15 picks in a dynasty draft conducted before the NFL Draft.


    His ranking may not reflect is potential value, because his upside is more dependent on fit than the players preceding him. However, his upside is as high as any player in this class with the right fit.


    There’s always a chance that Henderson winds up miscast early in his career, but those willing to embrace the risk could earn a significant reward. His post-draft value will rise significantly if he earns a good landing spot.


  12. L.J. Scott, Michigan State (6-0, 227)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.8 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Scott is one of the most compelling prospects to evaluate in this running back class. There are specific skills that remind me of Matt Forte, but his athletic ability is more in line with James Conner and Jeremy Hill.


    Scott is a mature decision-maker. He takes what’s available and if it means a short loss while pushing a creaseless middle of the line, so be it. Scott reads the helmets of defenders engaged in blocks and determines his crease choice with these reads.


    Whether its zone plays, gap plays, screen passes, or pass protecting against edge rushers, Scott’s patience is a

    virtue. He can delay, delay, delay, and hit a crease with burst, which is why he earns some of the comparisons to Le’Veon Bell.


    He’s patient with pulling blocks, but knows when to begin pushing the pile. He’s big and strong enough to push piles for gains of 3-4 yards and finish with good body lean.


    He possesses refined variation of his stride length to set up creases and then executes changes of direction with flexible hips. He can bend the short corner on a perimeter run and get downhill.


    Whether it’s picking and sliding to the next crease over, making dynamic lateral cuts away from penetration, or stepping over the legs of fallen players as he works through a small hole, Scott’s footwork is starter quality and helps him turn potential losses into small gains.


    He transitions between footwork techniques seamlessly. He can make a lateral cut, get the knees high, and then hit traffic with low pad level. He can jump-cut to his right or left and within a step, get downhill.


    The ability to layer moves at his size and do so this seamlessly may be enough to override concerns about his short-area stop-start quickness—especially when he pairs starter-level leg strength and explosion with starter-level acceleration.


    He identifies pursuit fast and is quick to juke, stutter, lateral cut, and/or spin. Scott knows when to push the pile and when to make people miss. His hip mobility and ankle flexion are strong, allowing him to transition from East-West to North-South with a small hop or 1-2 steps.


    Scott can cut inside or outside a defender and then hurdle a player within the next step. He accelerates through cuts and paces his gait to set up a crease.


    He has the acceleration to the reach the secondary. On tape, he appeared quick enough to consistently make the first man miss despite reserve-caliber quickness metrics at the NFL Combine. He displayed the quickness to spin past a safety screaming into the backfield.


    But Scott does not have a second gear to transition from his initial acceleration to a top speed that will continue to pull him away from pursuit. After 20 yards, defenders he accelerated past—including cornerbacks—will begin catching up.


    In terms of quickness, he excels at spins, dips, and fluid displays of footwork where he can use his initial explosion with economy. Force Scott to stop his feet or execute deep bends at the knees and hips and he’s not quick enough to execute and maintain separation with these change of direction (C.O.D.) methods.


    Since he’s consistent at leveraging the strengths of his

    C.O.D. game, I’m a little more optimistic than some about his quickness translating to the NFL. His acceleration is definitely on par with starters. His C.O.D. is committee caliber because his actual quickness is on par with reserves while his footwork, acceleration, and explosion are on-par with starters.

    Scott also converts quickness to power. He’ll make a defender miss a direct angle and then clean up with a strong push. Or, he’ll put a shake move on an opponent and drop the pads through them.


    Scott is strong enough to lean through wraps and extend his frame for extra yards at the end of plays—including quick-penetrating defensive linemen that greet him behind the line of scrimmage. He can spin off hard, direct contact from linebackers and break the tackle.


    When he hits a crease hard, he can drop the hammer on linebackers and lighter defensive tackles, sending them a few steps backwards before the scrum kicks in. He has a strong stiff-arm capable of sending linebackers to the ground.


    Scott carries the ball under the appropriate sideline arm but his elbow isn’t tight enough to his frame. He fumbled 10 times in 654 career touches, which translates to a low-end committee tier for ball security.


    Scott has excellent hands, hand-eye coordination, and a strong catch radius. He makes plays on targets thrown harder than they should have been. He can do this at awkward target angles behind his break point and into his frame. He tracks the ball well over his shoulder.


    Scott displays some promise as a route runner. When split from the formation, he runs hitches that look like the work of a good college receiver.


    He will set up a defender with an outside move and then swipe past defenders at the line of scrimmage to the inside seam. He’ll also work through his first break to help out his quarterback. Scott shows some potential to work downfield and was targeted twice as a first read during the first quarter of the Ohio State game.


    He’s the best pass blocker in this class. He’s patient with edge defenders that try to throw moves at him. He’s also capable of sliding across the width of the pocket to square an opponent and finish with an uppercut punch from a position tight to the defender.


    His punch technique is sound enough that linebackers don’t get much push off the edge. He’s as good sliding to the edge of the pocket as he is leading a quarterback sprint.


    Scott accurately identifies a variety of blitzes and line twists and earns good position to make the block. He’s mature with how he handles delayed blitzes. Scott is a consistent cut blocker. When he struggles to cut a defensive end working the corner, he will at least force him wide of the pocket.


    Scott dealt with ankle and hamstring injuries that cost him seven games in 2018. He had offseason surgeries prior to the 2017 season, but the school didn’t mention the specifics of the procedures and he played the entire season.


    Scott served a suspension while at Michigan for getting arrested for the seventh time for driving with a suspended license.

    If he shows starter-level quickness when changing direction, he could be on the cusp of feature back talent. As it appears to me, he’s a capable contributor and productive spot-starter. However he’s probably too slow and a little too limited with his C.O.D. quickness to maintain a role as a full-time starter.


    RSP Boiler Room: Phases of Movement



    L.J. Scott Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Scott will be a patience play as a mid-to-late pick. He’ll likely produce when called upon, but like many backs whose athletic gifts are just a hair shy of starter quality, he will tease those expecting a permanent emergence.


  13. Jon Hilliman, Rutgers (6-0, 222)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.8 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Hilliman is a skilled cutback runner—especially when he’s running plays that stretch to tackle or end. He spots cutbacks early against penetration and he has the footwork to weave around defenders and find the open path.


    Hilliman is a smart runner who recognizes the difference between his capabilities and the realities of a situation. For instance, when he sees a crease closing, he’ll leave his feet and dive for it if it’s the best path to earn a modest total for a first down or he would have lost yards taking an alternate path.


    Hilliman accelerates well through cuts and can bend the downhill acceleration even further away from defenders in the hole after he makes the initial cut. He’s a patient runner that will press tight to the line of scrimmage to read blocks and set up the cutback.


    Hilliman baits defenders effectively with his presses to the line. When cutting downhill from an East-West approach, he only needs 1-2 steps for the transition.


    Once Hilliman is in the open field, he sets up defenders for cutbacks. He works to get the most from every run.


    He has the acceleration to work past all three levels of the defense—even through tight creases. Hilliman executes effective jump stops and jump cuts at the edge of a crease to set up the cutback.


    He can reach the wide-side corner with his acceleration. He can re-accelerate past edge defenders whenforced to stop or change direction due to penetration. His acceleration is good enough that he can bait some defensive backs with a stutter and earn the angle with the help of a stiff-arm.


    Hilliman hits creases hard and pushes front-seven defenders to generate scrums. When facing an opponent one-on-one, he can extend his body through wraps and lean for extra yards. He can run over a linebacker.


    Hillman runs through reaches from all types of defenders. He uses his free arm to swat away attempts and he also

    has enough leverage and strength with the stiff-arm to ward off linebackers in close quarters.


    His ball security is lacking a tight elbow, but Hilliman uses the correct arm based on the location of his pursuit. His carriage is also high to his chest and he’ll switch the ball when he has an opportunity. His fumble rate is 1 per 102 touches—committee tier.


    Hilliman’s strong agility helps him mirror defenders effectively off the edge. He’s patient with lead blocking on sprints as well as identifying the line twists in the pocket. He delivers a hard uppercut punch when working as part of a double team.


    Hilliman’s cut blocks are effective on plays up the middle or sprints to the flat, but he’s better when he’s cutting defenders on interior blitzes. Sometimes, he’ll shoot too low. He’s a capable stalk blocker, earning position and generating good placement of his hands. Hilliman’s

    stand-up game is promising, but he must begin punching against larger defenders.


    He catches the ball with his back to the quarterback. He also handles high-velocity throws that get on top of a receiver earlier than expected. He’s used mostly as an outlet receiver.


    Hilliman began his career as a standout at Boston College. He missed the 2015 season with a foot fracture after 4 games. After surgery and a long rehab, he returned in 2016 and played through more injuries.


    He transferred to Rutgers for one more year of eligibility after graduating with his communications degree at Boston College.


    Jon Hilliman vs. Virginia Tech



    Jon Hilliman vs. Notre Dame

    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Hilliman could be a significant sleeper in this class. If his pass protection or ball security were one tier better—and both are easy fixes—he’d be a ranked in the RSP’s top 10 at the position.


  14. Justice Hill, Oklahoma State (5-10, 198)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.8 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Hill’s style and talent fit along the narrow spectrum of Theo Riddick and Reggie Bush. Bush was a more versatile player between the tackles, but both offered great skill in open space as receivers who could work from the backfield and the slot.


    Hill is a dynamic speed back who can dip or cut at a high rate of movement, doing so efficiently with a single step to change direction. Whether it’s the short corner or the long corner, Hill accelerates past front-seven pursuit and extends runs into the secondary, presenting a stiff challenge to their angles of pursuit.


    Hill will flip an offense’s field position 40-60 yards with a single run. He’s an electric player who runs with a wiggle.

    This helps him work around interior defenders as an inside zone runner. It’s also a nightmare for safeties watching him work clean through an interior crease and heading towards them at top speed, because one false move will lead to a losing chase rather than a winning tackle.


    Hill reads the leverage of the defenders as he takes the exchange with his quarterback and has a good understanding of when to work inside or outside. He needs to be a little more patient at pressing creases on Duo plays (a man blocking scheme featuring a pair of double teams by the line). He doesn’t press as deeply as he should.


    Due to the free-flowing nature of the blocking that creates an open-field look, Hill thrives on draw plays. Even with a lead blocker on the play, he’ll set up creases with effective stride adjustments.


    Although it won’t happen with the same amount of success in the NFL due to the superior athletic ability of defenders, Hill will still earn success when the conditions are ripe to reverse field. More often, you’ll see him execute strong cutbacks while in the second level of the defense. These moves turn gains of 8-12 yards into plays of 30 or more.


    As sometimes happens with players with Hill’s talents, he’ll have occasional lapses of discipline and maturity and try too hard to bounce plays outside when there’s really no angle to take. This also leads to indecisive work on subsequent plays where he begins layering moves to create space when he should be taking what’s immediately in front of him—even when what he’s taking is minimal.


    Hill has light feet and gets in and out of cuts with ease. He’ll drop his weight and transition from East-West to North-South with no extra steps. Jump, slalom, parallel cuts, jump stops, and spins are all common words in his running back vocabulary, and he’ll combine them to generate some exciting statements for his offense.


    He’s quick and creative enough to attack creases aggressively, earning 3-5 yards before he’s wrapped. He doesn’t need dramatic movement to earn space. He’ll vary his stride and pacing to get the job done as well.


    It’s an important indication of his budding maturity as a runner that he doesn’t have to stop-start and cut to manipulate defenses. The fact that he can use his stride and pacing to set up a crease and hit it hard adds versatility to his style and makes him capable of handling gap and zone schemes.


    Still, his dynamic movements will earn him angles where defenders can only reach for his frame rather than hit and wrap it. Hill has an explosive spin move that will turn hits into reaches that he can run through. When he has accelerated into a crease, he can run through reaches to his lower legs and bounce off hits at the second and

    third-level of a defense.


    He’s only a challenge to tackle when he faces defensive backs in direct collisions. However, he can use his momentum and strength to pull a defensive lineman a few yards when wrapped in the hole.

    Just don’t expect him to drop his pads into the chest of defensive tackles and linebackers and generate pushes of 4-6 yards—even when he hits the crease hard. The fact that Hill only earns a slight push against a linebacker that is tackling from a position where his knees are on the ground and at a leverage disadvantage is all you need to know about Hill’s power.


    Hill has an effective stiff-arm to ward off reaches. He gauges pursuit angles well enough to slow down and use the stiff-arm as a proactive maneuver so he can earn more ground than he would trying to outrun a good pursuit angle.


    Hill has work to do as a pass protector, and while he’ll never be stoning defensive linemen and linebackers, he will prove capable once he addresses specific technical and conceptual flaws. The first is not overextending at the point of attack.


    He must develop more control as he works towards his assignment or else the opponent will make quick work of Hill on the way to the quarterback. The aggression to get deep into the line of scrimmage, but sacrificing depth for control is a better choice.


    He’ll miss delayed blitzes because he will look back to the quarterback to determine if the ball is out a few beats after the snap. As a result, linebackers or defenders executing twists can work past him.


    Every game I've seen of Hill, he "attempts" to chip a defender. I place the word in quotes because it appears he’s executing with great effort, but a closer look reveals it’s more show than substance. He misses his angle on chips too often and it’s carried out like an inexperienced pro wrestler who tries to sell a move too dramatically.


    All too often, Hill’s stand-up game against edge defenders begins with a good square, a quick touch of the defender and little technique to sustain the effort. It’s like a harmless peck on the cheek to a spouse before he or she walks out the front door.


    When Hill sets his feet and his hands early, he can shield defenders and move with them on edge rushes. He’ll extend his arms into all sizes of defenders pressuring from the edge. He also works inside-out from the pocket to earn good position as part of a double-team effort with a tackle.


    However, he must learn to punch. Delivering his shoulder or elbow may occasionally work and blow up the opponent’s path, but it’s a low-percentage technique that often fails a lot bigger than getting pushed back into the pocket.


    Getting pushed back into the pocket will happen to Hill even when he’s square and delivers a punch because he’s a size mismatch. That would be an acceptable outcome.


    He can throw the uppercut punch, but he did this as a route runner converting to a blocker and not from the pocket. Once he begins throwing a punch, he can at least temporarily freeze his opponent. This will help him maintain good position, mirror the defender, and transition to an angle where he can push with leverage.

    Hill earns appropriate height and position across the body of opponents when he cut blocks. He can improve the speed of his execution. He must shoot with violence rather than lean into the effort.


    Although Hill has ball security flaws, his fumble rate is 1 per 136 touches over the course of a career where he handled the ball 681 times. This is starter work.


    Hill carries the ball high and tight through traffic, but the carriage gets loose at the elbow as he sees more open space. By the time he’s in the open field, the carriage can also become too low.


    Hill carries the ball with either arm and bases it on the pursuit of his opponents. He’s good at switching the ball to the appropriate arm during a carry.


    Hill catches the ball with the appropriate hands techniques for the location of the target. He can high- point the ball with full extension of his frame.

    With his speed and quickness, he has potential as a vertical route runner as well as developing his routes as a slot receiver.


    Hill’s production potential has greater variation than some of the players in his tier, because he’s a scat back and he’ll have to prove he can handle a bigger workload between the tackles. It took Reggie Bush a couple of teams and a several years before he earned this opportunity.


    Hill could be an exciting fit for the 49ers’ outside zone scheme. His capability as a gap runner could make him a developmental option for the Eagles who could still earn a role in sub-packages.


    Will Bruce Arians give Ronald Jones a second chance to show something in Tampa Bay? Does he even want a back like Jones? If he does, he might bring in Hill as competition.


    RSP Film Room: Justice Hill


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Hill’s upside is Reggie Bush’s past production, but his downside is the frustration that fantasy managers have with Duke Johnson’s situation. He’s a talented player with the ball in his hands that’s best considered a long-term patience play. Hill will be overvalued this spring, because the excitement for a game-breaker will likely exceed the volume he earns during his first contract.


  15. Benny Snell, Kentucky (5-10, 224)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.8 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Snell is not nearly as exciting an option as Henderson or Hill, but he’s the Jordan Howard “type” of this running back class. Although a powerful inside runner who lacks game-breaking skills, he can move the chains and handle a heavy workload.


    Unlike Howard, Snell catches the ball well. Like Howard, teams will question if Snell is worth using in the passing

    game because what he does well may be too predictable to opponents.


    An efficient inside zone runner, Snell spots the potential opening and sets up the crease with his pacing, stride length, and overall patience. He can work inside-out as he reads zone blocks and he’ll reach the edge on well- blocked plays. He times creases well behind a fullback, but there aren’t a lot of teams in the NFL that still use fullbacks on a frequent basis.


    Snell has good footwork. He steps over reaches for his lower legs as he works through the crease and he can sequence various moves to weave around defenders, especially off-tackle.


    When a crease isn’t opening, Snell will find the soft spot and push to create space. He’s also adept at finding small creases and attacking them with aggression, maximizing yardage. He knows he’s a contact runner and isn’t afraid to rely on a strength of his game.


    Knowing who you are is half the battle. Physicality can only get a runner so far in the NFL, and Snell has the requisite quickness to take the short corner against pursuit when bouncing outside. When he reaches the edge, he has an effective jump cut to work outside-in against edge containment and get downhill.


    Whether it is between the tackles or in the open field, Snell adjusts his stride and finds cutback lanes. He also has the peripheral vision to spot cutback lanes well at the far end of the line of scrimmage and avoid penetration into the backfield.


    He can outrun enough linebackers if there isn’t a safety playing over top to the side of the field where Snell is running; he’ll earn 30-40 yards. At the same time, Snell must be wiser in the open field when he’s near the first- down marker. Instead of trying to avoid pursuit for a bigger run and lose the first down because he gives up yardage, he should engage defenders to earn the necessary gain to move the chains.


    In short: When Snell runs between the tackles, he knows who he is and how to leverage his strengths. When he’s outside his environment and in the open field, he forgets who he is and fails to use his talents appropriately. This is a minor maturity issue that he should correct.


    Atlhough he can outrun a lot of linebackers at the college level, top athletes at the position could track Snell down on perimeter runs—even when lacking a great angle of pursuit. Forget about him outrunning defensive backs unless he breaks though the line up the middle and the safeties and corners are washed out at the line of scrimmage.


    Although none of this analysis seems like a glowing review of Snell’s acceleration and quickness, remember that he faced a steady diet of SEC defenders. Manyof them may lack NFL-caliber skills, but are NFL-quality athletes. Leonard Fournette told reporters during his rookie camp that the NFL felt like he was facing top SEC teams every week.


    While not a precisely accurate piece of analysis from Fournette, it’s a reflection of the athletic ability of the

    conference. Snell has starter-tier metrics with his acceleration and quickness. Based on the tape and the data, he should continue to be an effective chain-mover who can occasionally earn longer gains.


    Snell’s movement is good for his style of play. He opens his hips easily enough to turn outside. He freezes pursuit with a head fake and he has skillful jump-stops to set up plays at the corner. He’s a slashing runner who usually maintains his discipline with the tenets of the blocking scheme he’s executing.


    The strength of Snell’s game is contact. He has an aggressive, first-contact mentality in the crease when he spots angle to exploit on a linebacker or defensive back. Snell will lower the pads into these opponents and drop them in the hole. Even when facing defensive linemen, Snell will bounce off and move forward.


    Second-, third-, and fourth-effort is the name of his game and he’ll finish with good extension through wraps. He also sports an effective stiff-arm to ward off pursuit or pry a defender loose from his frame.


    Snell is on the cusp of the committee and starter tier with his ball security, averaging a fumble every 118 touches. He often uses the appropriate arm away from the pursuit and he’ll take a hit to the ball without it budging.


    He must become more consistent using the correct arm for the path of the run and tighten his elbow. Loose elbows make runners more susceptible to punches from behind or defenders prying the arm away when in a scrum. Both scenarios are likely with the rugged but slower Snell.


    Snell has one big flaw as a pass protector that is correctable: He drops his head into the collision point with the opponent. This minimizes the impact of his punch, causes him to lose sight of his assignment, and allows the opponent to work around him or use that lapse in leverage to his advantage.


    If Snell corrects this issue, he can excel. He displays excellent diagnosis and execution of cut blocks—even between the tackles on defensive linemen running twists. His cuts have good height, placement, and initial violence with the shoot. Even when Snell misses the cut block, his consistently good angles of approach widen defenders from their path to the quarterback.


    Snell works across the formation with enough quickness to square and deliver a proper punch with an uppercut motion. This is promising work, but until he curtails his habit of dropping his head, he’ll get pushed back into the pocket with ease and lose opportunities to control the confrontation.


    Snell highpoints the ball and makes receptions, despite taking contact during the act of the catch. He adjusts well to targets that force him to turn away from the break path. He also finds open space for his quarterback when the play breaks down.


    If the RSP’s ranking was weighted more heavily towards overall upside for these running back prospects, Snell wouldn’t be as high on this list. However, when you ground analysis in the reality of what a player can and

    can’t do right now and use upside as differentiators within tiers, Snell earns high marks.


    He may not earn a first- or second-day pick in the NFL Draft but he could earn a contributing role as a rookie and work his way into a lead position. He has the style that would befit most of the teams in the AFC North. If the Chiefs want third power-back for the depth chart that will be available on Day 3 and can give them Spencer Ware’s physicality—and Andy Reid has a history with favoring backs with this style—Snell fits.


    RSP Boiler Room: Hip Mobility and Unanswered Questions RSP Boiler Room: Attacking in Tight Quarters


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Snell is a mid-round pick because of the talent glut in the NFL, but he has the talent to outperform his draft status. He’s a solid investment at a bargain price—even if he winds up with career that mimics Carlos Hyde as an on-again, off-again starter or contributor.


  16. Devin Singletary, FAU (5-7, 203)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.6 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    If Singletary succeeds as a starter or contributor with starter production, it’s because he’ll have proven that his game is better than the sum of its parts. As is the case with many of the backs this year, he’s an unusual and difficult evaluation.


    Singletary has the best peripheral vision and timing in this class. Combined with his balance to bounce off glancing blows from every level of defender, his creative footwork, and his diehard style (his nickname is “Motor”), and he bleeds every ounce of production from his talent.


    He’s slow, not nearly as quick as his moves make him appear, and unlikely to get any sturdier with a frame that’s likely maxed-out.


    Singletary’s combination of traits makes him a borderline starter, unless you have some thresholds for athletic ability that will automatically knock him out of contention. I do not.


    I believe there are several archetypes for running backs because of the wide range of athlete types we’ve seen have success at the position. What I’m not sure I’ve seen before is a runner with his extremes of positive traits that may or may not compensate for other traits that would be deal-breaking limitations for morst other runners.


    Singletary might be the riskiest choice at the running back position in this class and there are several of them. The difference between him being No.8 and No.15 on my board comes down to one grade that could have gone either way: Acceleration.


    His 4.4-second 20-Shuttle is the cut-off point between starter and committee tier acceleration. Based on what I analyzed below after deconstructing and reconstructing his game from tape analysis, I went back and forth whether to award him the starter tier.

    Ultimately, I didn’t and it’s why he doesn’t have a borderline starter score (79.6) for Depth of Talent and the No.8 ranking on this list.


    He’s a contributor level player rather than a player with borderline starter upside. Knowing how close it is, I encourage you to examine his acceleration within the first 20 yards and decide for yourself whether Singletary is worth selecting ahead of the backs ranked 9-14 on this list.


    He may get there, but he’s already maximized a lot of traits to get where he is.


    Singletary is a mature runner who knows when to attack and when to wait. When there’s a reason to attack, he’ll split defenders or double teams, making one cut downhill and working under them with good pad level.


    He finds quick solutions to penetration into the backfield. His movement is a library of ducks, spins, head fakes, shakes, dead legs, jukes, jump cuts, and jump stops. He combines these moves in a wide variety of ways to eliminate direct contact from pursuing defenders.


    He needs 1-2 steps to transition from a path to the sideline to one heading downhill. He opens his hips well for sudden turns. He reaccelerates well.


    There are occasional plays where Singletary would do better to adjust his stride, rather than use the moves listed above. His inside-out decisions when reading the line can get too rash. He bounces outside when he should have remained inside. Against disciplined and athletic defenses, Singletary can push too hard and lose his patience.


    He’s a decent blocker for his size. He delivers his hands with a punch while keeping his feet moving to mirror linebackers off the edge one-on-one and defensive ends as part of a double-team effort with a tackle. Against larger opponents one-on-one, he overextends his position.


    Singletary has an uppercut punch but used it more often when chipping rather than one-on-one assignments. He must improve his punch and its frequency of use. Right now, he drops his head and pads as a windup to the motion and it inhibits his ability to strike.


    Singletary prefers to shield or push defenders, or launch into defenders with a shoulder. Although a shoulder to the chest can put a defender on the ground, the attempt more often results in a bad angle or the inability to sustain when Singletary fails to achieve the desired effect.


    He earns the proper height and angle across the frame of linebackers when cut blocking. He has taken bad angles on cut blocks, but still did enough to widen the edge rusher from the pocket.


    Singletary is a capable receiver and working in open space. He’s used most often on outlet routes and screens. A team skeptical of Singletary’s ability may elect to use him in these situations first.

    Singletary catches the ball with his hands and uses the correct position for the location of the target. He tracks the ball over his head in stride and he high-points the ball. He’ll come down with the ball when hit from behind at the catch point.


    He’ll have to work on routes and reading the defense to be on the same page as his quarterback. However, his athletic ability doesn’t give him great upside in this area.


    His ball security rate is starter quality (1 fumble per 158 touches), even if his technique isn’t perfect. He uses the correct arm based on the pursuit and he’ll switch as necessary. However, Singletary carries the ball loose from frame and low. If he doesn’t clean this up and his rate of fumbles climbs during his first year in the league, it won’t be a surprise.


    Singletary has adequate burst just below the RSP’s starter threshold. He often gets into the secondary or to the corner when he has an open runway. He can decelerate at the boundary and cut inside.


    From shorter runways, he can reach the corner and then make a one-step cut downhill. Despite good burst, he’s not beating most defensive backs or many linebackers. Gains of 35-40 yards will be unusual for him relative to other backs.


    Despite average acceleration and below-average quickness, Singletary has created enough space with his movement to set up reversals of field, cutbacks, and bounce-outs for chain-moving gains and the occasional field-flipping play.


    Anyone nicknamed “Motor” rarely goes down upon first contact. He must be wrapped or he’ll bounce off multiple hits, reaches, and wraps until he’s brought to the ground. With his athletic profile, it doesn’t appear this should work out for Singletary as well as it does.


    There are several underlying factors for his success. His short stature and deep press of creases makes it difficult for defenders to locate him at the line of scrimmage. He’s easy to lose and this gives him an added step of acceleration time that his workout data cannot contextualize.


    When he can get lost in traffic and gain an extra step, his pad level and low center of gravity make it difficult to bring Singletary down with a hit or wrap. His combination of moves freezes defenders and he’s especially sneaky with varying his pace to set up false rhythms of movement that bait defenders into bad angles.


    Singletary has a stiff-arm effective at warding of reaches. He’ll lower his pads into direct collisions with defensive backs in the hole or at the edge of the formation. He’ll get a push on these defenders for extra yards.


    Singletary bounces off hits at indirect angles from every type of defender on the field. It doesn’t happen every time, but he does it frequently enough to routinely earn at least 2-3 yards after contact. He’s wise about dropping his pads to earn these yards in situations where bouncing outside would result in a net loss.

    Singletary pulls through a lot of wraps aimed high or low on his frame. This skill and his contact balance are heightened by his stamina.


    As broached in Darrell Henderson’s profile (see above), some runners are explosive but lack stamina while others have average-to-below average speed or burst but maintain a pace that others cannot sustain over the same course of a play. This is one of Singletary’s special talents and it heightens the value of his peripheral vision, his low center of gravity, burst, change of direction, and contact balance.


    We’ll learn how valuable those qualities are when he suits up on Sundays.


    RSP Boiler Room: Anatomy of a Stiff-Arm RSP Boiler Room: Motor

    Devin Singletary Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Singletary is the most dangerous back on this board—in terms of predicting when he’ll be drafted and how good he’ll be. I doubt I will be drafting Singletary because as much of a proponent I am of excellent vision, I don’t believe a player can produce without other quality skills.


    While I understand how Singletary could succeed, I’m not projecting it. It’s why I’ll need on-field proof from Sunday football before I’m sold on his ability.


  17. Alex Barnes, Kansas State (6-0, 226)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.5 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope


    Gauging on-field speed and acceleration can be difficult. Marrying it to NFL Combine data can help, but there are times metrics aren’t an accurate reflection of on-field performance because the athlete’s processing of information slows him down. Or, in a milder case, the player is dealing with an injury that isn’t widely known.


    It was easy to see Dexter Williams’ acceleration and quickness on the field. He posted an impressive 4.16- second, 20 Shuttle and a 7-second, Three-Cone. These were among the top performances in these drills at the combine.


    Barnes exceeded Williams’ marks with a 4.10-second, 20 Shuttle and a 6.95-second, Three-Cone. Gauging whether Barnes’ athletic attributes in these areas translate to the field of play has been more difficult.


    Somewhere along the line, an analyst must side with the times, the tape, or find a middle ground. When it comes to Barnes, what I see is a back with excellent acceleration and quick lateral movement whose ability to sustain this speed drops considerably after 20 yards of movement.


    After all, speed comes in many forms. Some individuals have great build-up speed. They start slow, but once they establish their stride, look out.

    Others start fast, but can’t sustain the initial rate of acceleration or build on it. This is where I think Barnes is with his game.


    There are also individuals that aren’t the fastest at the beginning or the end of a run, but they have terrific stamina. This doesn’t show well in a lot of sprint events in track and field, but in football, it has value. In his prime, Marshawn Lynch’s rate of movement and intensity was as strong after he carved an “S” over the course of 90 yards on a run where he’s left fallen defenders in his wake as it was at the line of scrimmage.


    It’s important to note this distinction about Barnes’ game, because when a runner’s athletic prowess in testing doesn’t match his on-field play, there’s potential to overestimate the value of the player. Compounding the difficulty of this evaluation is how closely grouped these backs are.


    Give Barnes full credit for his acceleration metrics and he’s the No.5 back on the board. Give Barnes no credit and base it solely on his film and he’s the No.18 runner.


    I’ve split the difference with partial credit, awarding him the bonus value in the lower tier that indicates potential to unlock his base athletic ability. It places Barnes here at No.18.


    Based on athletic talent, Barnes belongs in the same tier as the five backs listed ahead of him. However, good football is about how players express that talent on the field. This is where Barnes’ game doesn’t match his metrics.


    Conceptually, Barnes has a handle on the basic plays that are in most NFL offenses. He runs power and zone competently. He reads the line of scrimmage, anticipates penetration well, and if nothing disrupts the process he’ll set up blocks according to the tenets of the scheme.


    If he has to run up the back of his teammates to generate a push, he’ll do so. Like any back, Barnes can lose some patience during the game if the run blocking isn’t opening creases but it doesn’t happen often.


    Barnes has the stride and pace variation to set up blocks and the decisiveness and physicality to drop the pads and hammer a soft spot in the line. This makes him a good short-yardage runner.


    The natural body lean of Barnes’ gait is a positive of his game. When he anticipates penetration into the backfield, his pads are usually low while he slides laterally to the nearest escape lane.


    His patience lends itself to skill with cutback running. Barnes displays enough acceleration on the field that when he can get first- and second-level defenders drawn inside, he can hit the backside crease and earn 10-20 yards untouched. This is a fitting display of his 20-shuttle acceleration.


    His acceleration is best highlighted on gap plays like power, trap, and counter. Although he sets up these pulling blocks with patient manipulation of his stride and pacing, the inherent nature of the play requires less of it to access the crease. When Barnes can hit the crease

    hard, he’s tough to bring down and his burst will get him into the secondary.


    When he reaches the linebackers, Barnes will press an opponent to set up an open angle with an economical move. When a run calls for dramatic changes of direction, Barnes can transition from an East-West track to a North- South track with two small steps.


    In addition to effective presses of gap creases, Barnes also has a combination move where he stutter-steps to a side and then cuts downhill. When he encounters oncoming defenders, Barnes spins through reaches or jump cuts with enough range that he begins outside his opponent’s shoulder and ends the cut well outside the other.


    A big back with upper-body strength, Barnes pulls defenders for extra yards. This includes defensive tackles wrapping his legs. His body lean and pad level lends itself to forceful collisions with defenders in the secondary and generates 3-4 yards post-contact.


    If he needs to use a forearm shiver to claim space—be it a defender or teammate in the way—he can knock a larger man deep into the hole. Barnes has a stiff-arm, but he doesn’t land it with the power and leverage it deserves. Right now, it’s more of a fade away tool while splitting defenders in the open field.


    Barnes can run over safeties at the entrance of a crease. He’ll stalemate linebackers head-on and he has enough strength to pull through the reaches of defensive tackles and linebackers. When the defense disrupts Barnes’ gait, he can balance-touch to regain it.


    Barnes drops his weight well enough to make changes of direction that he often beats defensive linemen downfield. Once Barnes reaches the secondary, his speed tapers off quickly enough that pursuit can catch and wrap him. This is where evaluating Barnes is most problematic.


    Arian Foster was markedly slower than Barnes when measuring long speed. However, he anticipated well and executed efficiently and it helped him play fast. Barnes has games on his tape where he couldn’t gain angles on pursuit that one would expect based on his NFL Combine performance in the acceleration and change of direction drills.


    In two games that I charted, I wrote down that Barnes, “Lacks notable acceleration and speed on the runs I’ve seen today. [He] lacks the suddenness to make that first man miss in the open field once through the crease.”


    I could be misjudging the plays. However, I’ve been doing this for nearly 15 years and I usually assess speed and quickness correctly, once I can pair the metrics and the film.


    Barnes has difficulty outrunning safeties and cornerbacks with decent angles of pursuit. He also lacks a sudden accelerator and after contact, he doesn’t reaccelerate as well as other backs that pull away from pursuit after a winning collision.

    In contrast, I studied Foster at Tennessee and he had no problems generating big runs that challenged opposing secondary defenders—in the SEC, no less.


    In addition, there are significant plays on tape where he has the angle to attack the secondary, but when he sees the pursuit bearing down, he anticipates he’s going to be tackled. It’s almost like watching a receiver drop to the ground after catching a dig route over the middle. It’s a subtler behavior, but it’s notable.


    This area of his game could be the difference-making attribute of Barnes’ career. If he makes improvements here, he can become a starter—maybe even a highly productive talent in an offense filled with strong surrounding talent.


    If not, teams will regard Barnes as a contributor who can spell an injured starter, or maybe serve as the de facto starter while a team adds a high-round pick in the future. However, Barnes will repeatedly experience the fallout of teams desiring a more explosive runner who finishes with greater violence on a consistent basis.


    Barnes’ receiving game has promise. He makes flexible extension on low targets working away from the quarterback. He has a strong catch radius on high and low targets and makes adjustments without losing his balance.


    Barnes tracks and catches awkward targets arriving into his frame or behind his break points. When featured in the intermediate and deep games, he high-points the football above his head. He also tracks the ball over his shoulder at a full sprint and executes a one-handed grab. He can finish the catch despite earning hard contact immediately after the reception.


    Barnes should develop into a competent blocker. He squares his assignments, meets rushers deep enough at the line of scrimmage, and moves his feet with the opponent. Barnes can push blitzing middle linebackers to the edge of the pocket.


    He’s effective when shielding defenders, but he can also cut block up the middle and at the edges of the pocket. Barnes delivers cuts with excellent height and across the opponent’s body at the hips. When he fails, Barnes is cutting too low because he dropped his head before the shot.


    Barnes also has lapses with his head level in his stand-up game. He’ll drop his head, overextend, and either get pushed into the pocket or shed aside quickly.


    Barnes is a willing and able lead blocker for running plays. He shields defensive linemen with good angles and if he misses an assignment, he’ll double-back to a different one to help his teammate.


    Barnes carries the ball too loose at the elbow, which opens him up to defenders punching at the ball either from backside pursuit or over top. His fumble rate is 5 out of 484 career touches—4 of them happened during the 2018 season.


    Barnes has really impressive flashes with movement, receiving, balance, and power. If he can tie it together

    with consistent quickness, he’ll be a productive starter. Based on what I’ve seen, it’s a bigger than average gamble.


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: If Barnes earns a second- or third-day pick for a team with a demand for a starter, he’s worth the gamble in the second or third round. If not, I’d rather wait to see if he falls beyond the third round of fantasy drafts.


    I can see how he could become a good player. I don’t see enough on the field to give him the upside that his timed acceleration and change of direction metrics suggest.


  18. Jordan Scarlett, Florida (5-11, 208)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.5 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Scarlett is a fascinating player because he has an odd combination of athletic strengths and weaknesses. It makes for a challenging projection of his talents.


    Scarlett is a patient runner who identifies splits of double teams. He will alter his stride length to set up creases and can deliver a head fake or juke to freeze the opponent and run past.


    Decisiveness is a significant strength of Scarlett’s game and it’s a good match for the gap plays in the Florida offense. Regardless of the size of the crease, if Scarlett identified it, he hit it hard and bled it dry. If a crease didn’t open, he’d at least find the softest spot and push his teammates forward.


    Duo, trap, and power are three of his bread-and-butter schemes. With these plays, he doesn’t need dynamic movement relative to zone runners. He’s quick, shifty, and has a good slalom cut and a small jump cut.


    However, it’s helpful when plays break down to have an arsenal of dynamic movement and it’s lacking in his game. He lacks a wide range of lateral movement and has difficulty dropping his weight into cuts.


    When his pad level is high, a common occurrence with his upright running style, he’s pushed backwards. However, this is due more often to a lapse of good pad level than the norm.


    Scarlett consistently works his pads under the pads of defenders and he can drop linebackers with his attack–or at least knock them backwards at the exit of a hole. He’s strong enough to stalemate linebackers with direct collisions at the entrance of creases. He’ll keep his legs moving until his teammates and arrive and create a scrum.


    He frequently breaks multiple tackles on a single run. Scarlett runs hard. He pulls through reaches high or low to his frame, bounces off indirect contact, and breaks wraps. Linebackers can have difficulty bringing Scarlett to the ground.


    In addition to his balance and pulling strength, Scarlett has a capable stiff-arm that he uses to ward off reaches

    and pry loose of wraps. He twists and turns through contact while maintaining a downhill path.


    In addition to the curiously good tackle-breaking skill for his average size, Scarlett has good top-end speed.

    Unfortunately, he is slow to accelerate and has even slower change of direction quickness. Will he be quick and strong enough to do similar work in the NFL?


    I’m not counting on him performing with the same consistency, but I’m confident he can deliver as a situational talent in short-yardage or on first and second downs.


    Even if his athletic ability translates at a higher level of play than anticipated, Scarlett must improve his hands. He can catch with his hands—even make back-shoulder turns or track the ball with his back to the quarterback. However, he needs to extend his arms further from his frame rather than inviting the target into his body where it can rebound off him. He also has drops in his portfolio that aren’t rooted in technical or focus issues.


    Scarlett should become a good blocker. He slides to the spot of the assignment and delivers from a square position and with an uppercut punch. He’ll roll through his hips as he punches.


    Whether working in pass protection or the run game, Scarlett sets his angles well and can move with the opponent as he maintains contact. His uppercuts aren’t forceful, but they are quick and precise.


    He has to work on blitz assignments to understand the line’s adjustments when the unit alters the call due to the defense presenting an unexpected pre-snap look.


    Scarlett carries the ball with either arm and his carriage is high and tight to his chest. The elbow could be tighter to his frame. Despite this minor flaw, Scarlett only fumbled at a rate of 1 per 179.5 touches. This is on the cusp of the star-caliber tier.


    Scarlett is good enough to earn a late-round pick and find a fit in a scheme that maximizes his talents in a gap scheme. Place him behind the Colts’ or Eagles line and let him run duo, power, trap, and toss, and many of the concerns about his game will melt away as he accumulates yardage.


    Of course, this can be said about many backs fighting for roster spots. The running back market has a glut of capable talent, which makes it a buyer’s market seeking special talents. Scarlett is a tough runner but there aren’t enough special traits.


    Jordan Scarlett Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Scarlett earned a year- long suspension during his career, which will be another reason that he’ll have a low draft capital. He’s a late- round fantasy pick and will need multiple things to happen to surrounding talent for him to earn an early opportunity.

  19. James Williams, Washington State (5-9, 197)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.15 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Williams will most likely earn a contributing role as a passing down back. He reminds me of James White in terms of what he can accomplish on the field, but the way he does it is unconventional.


    Williams understands how to create space while working with a quarterback buying time to find an outlet.

    Although I studied Williams in-depth, I didn’t see him earn extensive opportunities as an intermediate and vertical route runner. His neighborhood is the shallow zones.


    Williams catches the ball easily and tucks the ball efficiently. Whether he’s extending for the ball away from his frame or handling a target thrown into his frame and behind his break path, Williams has consistent and active hands. He also demonstrates the proper technique for the target location.


    When he works downfield, it’s usually a corner route or an out. When targeted near the boundary, he can adjust to back-shoulder placements as well as drag or tap his feet inside the boundary while fully extending his arms or his body.


    When used as a pass protector, Williams has the quickness to work across the pocket and set at 45 degrees to square edge pressure. Although he has occasional misses, Williams diagnoses interior and edge blitzes well.


    When cut blocking, he will work across the body of an opponent. Williams is often too low with his cut-blocking technique and his stand-up technique is missing a sound punch.


    Williams’ value will come in the receiving game and running the ball in open space. He’s a light-footed runner with fascinating control of his footwork. Williams appears as if he’s on the edge of losing control of his gait when in fact, he’s precise with his movements.


    He transitions from East-West to North-South with a single quick cutting step. His jump cuts are dynamic and if he needs to set up an opponent with a long jab step, he can come to a sudden stop to set up another change of direction.


    Williams employs start-stop moves, choppy feet, slalom cuts, stutter steps, jukes, spins and jump cuts in a variety of sequences. His stutter steps consistently freeze opponents in the open field and he has an excellently timed spin move at the exit of a crease.


    In addition to the footwork, he layers shoulder fakes, shake moves, and head fakes into his efforts. He’s the most creative mover in the class and one of the most dynamic.


    As a runner between the tackles, Williams reads the line and finds backdoor cuts or bounce-outs. He sets up creases between the tackles with his movement and

    when necessary, he will work up the middle and attack unblocked defenders entering the crease.


    Williams doesn’t earn much of a push on linebackers or defensive backs, but can spin off direct contact for positive gains. When facing down a lineman, the best- case scenario at the point of contact is a stalemate against a defensive end.


    His vision is borderline star caliber—especially in space. He routinely creates space in scenarios where it appeared there wasn’t a likely solution. His acceleration is strong enough to beat safeties up the sideline when he reaches open space.


    One of the things he does better than all but one other back in this class (Darwin Thompson) is pull through wraps to his lower legs. Thompson’s work appears to be a product of strength and quickness whereas Williams has a finesse with his movements that looks like Houdini escaping chains and straitjackets.


    Williams earns consistent placement with the stiff-arm and he can ward off multiple defenders in succession on a single run. He also uses his forearm to frame a bubble of space so defenders hitting him can’t reshape his frame or ball security. This adds an extra layer of space to protect the ball.


    Williams uses his left or right arm based on the location and path of the pursuit. His elbow comes loose too often as he’s running. And he carries the ball under his left or right arm based on the location of the path and the pursuit.


    A sudden, creative space player with versatility and unconventional movement, Williams will be a productive asset for a team that runs a spread offense or uses its backs as receivers from a variety of positions.


    RSP Boiler Room: Slippery Is An Advanced Quality RSP Boiler Room: Check-Down Alchemy


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: If Williams lands in an offense where the fit makes sense for a legitimate early impact without creative speculation, he could earn a pick in the third round of fantasy drafts. Otherwise, he’ll be a nice PPR bargain in round 5-7.


  20. Nico Evans, Wyoming (5-9, 211)


    Depth of Talent Score: 78.1 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    One of my favorite prospects with a likely late-round or UDFA grade, Evans is an underrated back with power, burst, agility, and underused receiving skill. He also can block.


    Evans presses rushing lanes well and spots the cutback quickly. He’ll set up creases with alteration of stride and pace and then cut downhill with a jump-stop or drop of the hips.


    He has notable burst and enough long speed to challenge cornerbacks in a footrace. An effective one-cut runner, he

    can press deep into the crease and take away a linebacker’s angle at the last second.


    His footwork helps him stay in rhythm with the blocking scheme and sets up bounces to the edge and backdoor cuts. Once in the hole, Evans can make a second cut to avoid linebackers and safeties.


    There are a number of run designs he can execute. He is good at cutting back on the stretch play and has the speed and burst to execute it as designed. He’s a decisive ISO runner, who gets his knees high to work over arms and legs on the ground in the hole, avoiding reaches as he clears the crease. Trap, power, inside zone, counter, and toss are all within Evans’ wheelhouse.


    Evans can cut efficiently downhill when transitioning from an East-West approach. He loses some of that precision on longer routes or perimeter runs to the long side of the field where he’s built up a decent clip of speed.


    Short and quick, Evans has athletic heft at a stout, 211 pounds. This includes his work against defensive linemen in the crease. Evans can drop his pads and bounce off indirect hits from linemen as well as pull through their wraps to his shoulders or waist. He made this work against the first level of the defense appear routine.


    Evans can spin off hits from linebackers or lean through their contact. He’ll push a middle linebacker 2-3 yards after making direct contact in the hole. Hard hits to the hips and legs by safeties don’t automatically force him to the ground. Evans often regroups and changes direction after taking hard hits of this type and he fights for every yard after contact.


    Evans has 3 fumbles in 266 touches, which is close to 1 per 90 touches, squarely in the middle of the committee tier. He’ll carry the ball under the appropriate arm and to his chest. He also uses high and tight technique.


    Evans is a promising blocker and if he plays to his skill level in this area, he’ll make a team. He squares his targets well and earns good position on blitzes so he can shoot his hands.


    He anchors well enough against linebacker blitzes and linemen twists that the initial collision only costs him 1-2 steps backwards. He keeps his feet moving and will mirror the defender before walling him off from the pocket. The underlying skill that helps him with these various positives is that Evans gets deep into the pocket.


    He’s an excellent cut blocker, who can work waist-high to an opponent and shoot through the body. Whether Evans works to the edge of the pocket or is the lead block on sprints, he can take down a linebacker with his technique.


    Evans has an uppercut motion but hasn’t mastered the process of rolling his hips to generate force. He’ll extend his arms through the contact point, but the pop is missing. Although he has shown effort to block defensive tackle, including a square approach and a punch a tackle can push Evans back quickly.

    He can also be slow to react to edge pressure and it can put teammates in a bind when expecting his help. This includes missing opportunities to chip a pass rusher.


    Evans’ blocking is good enough that he could get on the field early enough as a change of pace back and his receiving skills will help that cause. Although not targeted often at Wyoming, he has shown good tracking on intermediate and deep targets, correct hands positions for the target locations, and full extension adjustments.
