Evans also has the hand-eye coordination to track the ball over his head or handle a poorly throw pass that has too much velocity for the target type.


    Evans reminds me of a Devonta Freeman in build and style of play. If he can’t make a team in the NFL, he’ll be a productive starter in another league. However, I think he’ll make a team and surprise with his all-around ability.


    RSP Boiler Room: Using the OL as Ballast RSP Boiler Room: Ball Security

    Nico Evans Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: While unlikely Evans will get drafted, he is a more talented choice than some of the high-profile players lower on this list that’ve captured the imagination of the general public. Monitor from afar but be prepared to add him this summer in deeper leagues when he impresses. He’ll be a practice squad stash who can make good when an extended opportunity arises.


    Tier V: The next 10 players are tightly grouped in this tier despite offering a variety of strengths. All of them have potential with time to earn usage in a tightly packaged role. Some of them have the upside to develop into bigger contributors, if not starters, as their careers progress.


  21. Trayveon Williams, Texas A&M (5-8, 206)


    Depth of Talent Score: 77.25 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Williams is mainly used in pistol and shotgun, but he also earned time in the I-formation. He’s patient with lead blockers and will use stride and pacing adjustments to set up creases. He favors the spin move as a dynamic tactic to create space and he executes the move so it is tight enough to avoid wraps in the hole.


    Williams makes sharp lateral cuts and has just enough quickness to find backside creases when he’s playing in a spread formation against nickel looks. He opens the hips fast and can turn sharply. He only needs 1-2 steps to get downhill from an East-West approach when working to the near side; 2-3 steps when he must work a little farther and build up more speed.


    He can eye the cutback lane a little too much. He also try going airborne against edge containment when the angle is not wise.


    Williams is a high-effort player, but he lacks anything more than functional power—sometimes less than that. Defenders at the line frequently pull Williams backwards with a wrap.


    Williams is seeking glancing blows to work under, spin off, or work over top. Direct contact is not his strength. He can get a running start and drop his pads into a cornerback or safety that is standing still and get stalemated.


    Williams’ acceleration and long speed will get him into the secondary and depending on the position of safeties and cornerbacks, significant chunks of yardage beyond. However, he’s about two steps slower than the true breakaway threats. He’s knocking on the door but no one is going to answer.


    There’s no shame in this for Williams. He will use his cutback ability intelligently to create larger swaths of open grass he can exploit until the pursuit catches up. He either bleeds the yardage after contact or finds another cutback opportunity for more.


    Inside zone and outside zone are two of his better plays. He moves a little like Devonta Freeman and can spot creases like the Falcons’ runner, but he’s missing the vital power and balance that makes Freeman more than a scat back.


    He’s also a solid gap runner when it comes to running trap and counter but his lack of size may get him blown up more often at the other end of a crease when he’s committed to ramming the ball downhill with no little manipulation.


    Williams has grown immensely as a pass protector. Earlier in his career, he was always looking for the kill shot when he was chipping opponents. Williams would lead with a shoulder or elbow and deliver a huge shot.


    Sometimes the shot knocked the defender to the ground. Almost as often, the shot did the defender a favor by knocking him loose from the tackle’s block and into an open rushing lane to the quarterback.


    Williams’ stand up blocks didn’t have a proper punch where he could deliver with force and control. He either had to load up and throw shots from off-balanced positions and risk missing wildly, or he extended his arms and took first contact that would drive him into the pocket.


    Williams became a better puncher this year. His position and punch allowed him to remain in control of opponents. Although he doesn’t throw the hardest punch, he’s getting some pop with the contact and able to mirror and redirect with a second or third punch against the opponent. He’s doing this well against linebackers and safeties and moving his feet quicker with each punch.


    Due to his size, Williams still gets shoved back. He also can get beaten to the punch and controlled easier.


    His cut blocks remain inconsistent based on the trajectory of his shot into the opponent. He must work across the body rather than a straight forward shot that can land Williams between the opponent’s legs. He also shoots too low.

    Williams catches the ball with good tracking over the shoulder. He has the hand-eye coordination to make a one-handed grab.


    Williams uses active hands techniques based on the location of the targets. He has to be more boundary- aware when working with his quarterback after the initial play breaks down because he’s taken himself out of plays by stepping out of bounds. He also must get his head around faster to spot the ball on underneath routes.


    Williams carries the ball loose and low in space or when making dynamic movements. He uses the appropriate arm away from pursuit. Williams fumbled the ball 1 per 97 times—committee work. When he’s in traffic, the ball is tighter to his chest. He needs to make it a steady habit.


    This is probably the lowest opinion you’ll see someone publicly have on Williams. After performing my analysis, I cross-checked my thoughts with Lance Zierlein’s report at NFL.com and he’s a little more optimistic that Williams can become a starter—but you can see that he’s well aware of why that’s far from a guarantee.

    What really caught my eye was a quote from an NFC area scout:


    “The road scouts weren’t really feeling him but I just take that kind of production seriously with SEC backs. And it’s not just this year; he’s had three years at it.”


    Production is valuable but only if the process reveals physical, technical, and conceptual skills.


    The speed and acceleration are enough. The vision is good for the scheme. If Williams lands on a team with a similar scheme, then that would be in his favor—as would his change of direction talents.


    However, he still lacks the kind of balance that a vast majority of the starting running backs in the NFL possess (see Overrated).


    I’m with the road scouts on this one.


    RSP Boiler Room: Footwork-Vision-Speed



    Trayveon Williams Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: He’s not worth a second-round pick in dynasty leagues—if you agree with me and the road scouts I referenced. If not, let’s hope Williams proves he’s more than a contributor.


    He’ll need to be made the centerpiece of a spread offense with a strong offensive line and great surrounding talent for me to even begin rethinking this one.


  22. Wesley Fields, Georgia Southern (6-0, 205)


    Depth of Talent Score: 77.25 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Fields follows Jerick McKinnon and Matt Breida as the third compelling athlete from Georgia Southern’s backfield to earn a shot in the NFL. He’s an explosive runner with developmental upside.

    Fields has the speed and acceleration to challenge a secondary for breakaway runs as well as beat outside linebackers, and some safeties, to the far side of the field on perimeter runs.


    Fields is a decisive runner. He reads the leverage of defenders at the line and sets up creases with stride and pace variation. He’ll find an alternate hole with a cutback, bounce, or slide to the next gap over. He’ll take what’s available when defenders contain the play early.


    He’s quick to side-step penetration entering the crease or parallel cut from penetration into the backfield. He’s skilled at transitioning downhill on runs to the perimeter with a single step.


    There were plays where Fields was 1-2 steps late with his recognition of penetration, though, and it prevented him from doing something productive in response.


    Like Breida, Fields is powerful for his size and reaches don’t bring him to the ground. Linebackers have a difficult time wrapping him or even knocking him to the ground with a hit. If a defensive lineman wraps Fields high, the runner will often pull through that as well—even penetration that meets him in the backfield.


    Fields maintains a low pad level through contact and drives forward, using his free arm to ward off contact. He bounces off indirect contact by linebackers and safeties, sometimes multiple times in a play.


    Fields is a promising receiver with big-play skills. He makes receptions with his hands, tracks the ball over his shoulder, and uses correct techniques for the target location. He’s split from the formation and sent on deep seam routes, fades, and post routes. He tracks the ball well at a full sprint. He displays a good set up of the angle route over the middle, using a stutter to freeze coverage.


    Fields reads line twists accurately and squares the oncoming lineman with good position. He’ll punch with an uppercut. Too often, he’ll opt to throw an elbow or shoulder rather than set and punch.


    As a cut blocker, he shoots across the legs of his targets with violence and proper height. He’s skilled at the cut block as a lead man on a sprint play where the passer is rolling to the flat.


    Fields improved his ball security dramatically between 2017 and 2018. Before 2018, he only used his right arm and the carriage was too low and loose from his frame. He fumbled the ball ever 61 touches before correcting his technique. With a better understanding of ball security, Fields only fumbled 1 in 210 touches—a star-caliber effort for the season.


    An ankle injury limited Fields for the 2016 season, but he’s been healthy for the remainder of his college career.


    The Packers and Vikings were at Fields’ Pro Day but the results of the drills weren’t published in the media.


    RSP Twitter Analysis: Big-Play Receiving And Balance RSP Twitter Analysis: Deep Receiving and Downhill Cuts RSP Boiler Room: Anatomy of a Block

    RSP Boiler Room: East-West to North South


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Fields will be a late pick or a free agent addition after the draft. Monitor this summer and determine if he’s worth on spot on your practice squad.


  23. Ryquell Armstead, Temple (5-11, 220)


    Depth of Talent Score: 77.2 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Armstead would be a good addition to the Jacksonville Jaguars at a decent value because he will offer some redundancy to Leonard Fournette in terms of style and talent. He’s a bigger back with good strength and speed who runs hard and fits best in the gap-heavy scheme that the Jaguars like to use.


    He’s at his best when he can set up creases with small stutters, dips, or plants to freeze defenders and then hit the gap hard. He has notable burst and he can work through lanes and use his stiff-arm to ward off contact.


    When he’s in the gap, he can step over shots to his legs. He also uses his small manipulative tricks in the open field to freeze a safety and then run past him.


    Within the limits of his vision and footwork, Armstead shows potential for consistent maturity about not automatically bouncing runs outside when the first interior gap doesn’t come open. This is also true of designed runs to the outside. He’s quick enough to run the sweep as well as cut back to the inside.


    When he makes a cut downhill, Armstead will split defenders. He’s quick enough to reverse field or take the run to the corner and work around a safety—even to the far side of the field.


    Armstead reads the angles of defenders working free of blocks and makes decisions off that information. He will vary his stride and pace to set up blocks and has the peripheral vision to spot outside pursuit and dip away as he cuts downhill through an adjacent crease.


    If nothing comes open, Armstead drops the pads and pushes for what he can earn. While in the crease he can use the backs of his linemen to remain upright while opponents strike him in the crease. If the defender hitting Armstead can’t wrap up, Armstead’s use of his linemen as ballast helps him regain his footing and work to the open field.


    He has the balance to get under linebackers in the crease and send them backwards. He’ll pull through reaches and wraps and drag defenders. He’s a strong, physical runner.


    When he hits a clean crease, Armstead slides to an open lane through the secondary. He runs with a palpable energy—not as frenetic as Elijah Holyfield or as sudden as Darrell Henderson—but there’s intensity with his movement. He’s also blessed with deep speed to take runs the distance.

    Armstead wins when he drops his pads into contact or spins off hits. He can run with a wiggle and set up opponents with a shake move or head fake. His footwork is underrated because he’s quick and sequences economical moves together effectively.


    He’ll squeeze through small creases and tear through reaches if the defense can’t wrap up. He’s at his best as a blunt object rather than a surgical tool, which is why he’s not an ideal zone runner. Armstead runs well through reaches or spinning away from contact. He’ll fight for every yard and keep his feet moving through contact. He runs with high enough knees to pull through wraps in the hole.


    One prominent flaw with Armstead’s game is that he doesn’t consistently find simple solutions. Armstead makes the occasional odd decision in the open field, veering away from a receiver’s block and into an unblocked safety that was well within normal peripheral vision. Like many gap runners, Armstead is not great at avoiding backfield penetration and the only move he has to combat it is a spin.


    He can bring his head too far down when attacking a defender in the crease. Although he’ll bring it back up as he makes contact, and he can keep his feet moving, there’s reason for concern he’ll hurt himself or lose balance too fast with collisions at the next level.


    If he’s going to run plays other than gap style blocking, Armstead would fare better with stretch or outside zone. He has skills at transitioning from East-West paths to North-South with one sharp step.


    If the defense frustrates Armstead early on, he will lose discipline and attempt cutbacks on plays where he was in position to earn the first down before he chose to change direction. When he stops his feet, he’s in trouble.


    As suggested earlier, Armstead’s maturity is not consistent. His decisions become the most tentative when there are not initial creases. Instead of bouncing immediately or pushing downhill, he’ll become tentative and get wrapped behind the line. He’ll also get himself strung out on off-tackle and perimeter runs where he had a cutback to the inside that he passed over.


    When he drops his head into contact and doesn’t bring it back up in time, he’s knocked backwards. If he maintains his footing, he’s forced to restart his footing and he loses the momentum-based power that’s a big part of his game. Sometimes, Armstead runs so hard that he will lose his balance when forced to cut back or reverse field.


    Armstead carries the ball high and tight with either arm, but the elbow is loose at his size. The ball will swing a bit more when he’s in the open field, at least until Armstead spots pursuit and he’ll make the conscious effort to tighten his carriage. He has starter upside with his security, perhaps star-caliber upside after improving his technique and fumbling only 1 time per 218 touches last year. His career rate is 1 per 100, which is in the upper third of the committee caliber tier.


    Armstead is lower on this list, because he’s much better at running behind one blocking scheme than another and because he fights the football as receiver. He can catch

    the ball with his arms extended from his frame. He’ll adjust back shoulder or track the ball with his back to the quarterback.


    Even his technique based on the locations of targets is sound. The issue is consistency with tracking the ball. He has difficulty gauging the ball and leaps when there’s no need or hesitates with his hands and lets the ball get into his body. The ball often bounces off Armstead’s hands when it appears he looks it in.


    When running routes, Armstead must refine his breaks. He hops into hitches and stop routes. The lack of precision allows defenders to recover and make plays on the receiver and the ball.


    Armstead has good techniques as a blocker that he can refine in skill and consistency. He diagnoses the A-gap blitz effectively. He will cover the tackle and handle defenders who get inside or outside the lineman.


    He gets square and has an uppercut technique for a punch. His depth of setup in the pocket and stance are good enough to force edge rushers wide of their path. He can send an outside linebacker outside the pocket with his stance and position.


    Armstead mirrors defender movements well. He also earns good depth in the pocket and can turn with edge defenders.


    There are times he can open his frame too early and edge defenders will work inside of him. His punches also lack the force they could with a better roll of the hips.


    When Armstead cut blocks, his location across the legs is sound, but he doesn’t earn enough height. He can become too focused on cutting opponents on the outside when the better tactic is the stand-up game.


    It’s possible that Armstead could develop into a productive starter. Right now, he’s a high-functioning reserve if the specific scheme is a fit. If it isn’t, he may have to bounce around until he finds one that is.


    RSP Boiler Room: Art of the Bounce



    Ryquell Armstead Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: An athletic pickup for the end of deeper rosters with practice squads.

    Otherwise, monitor from afar.


  24. Kerrith Whyte, Jr. (5-10, 197)


    Depth of Talent Score: 76.85 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    A speedy back with angular cutting ability, Whyte’s physical skills make him a better NFL fit than his teammate Devin Singletary. His style of running has similarities to Dion Lewis.


    Whyte only needs 1-2 steps to transition downhill from an East-West heading. He often sets up downhill cuts with a stutter and a juke. He also possesses enough stop-start quickness to avoid a defensive back’s run blitz

    in the backfield and bounce the play for a significant gain.


    White has the speed on curvilinear tracks to bend runs to the perimeter without losing his pace. However, he’s not limited to this style of direction changes. He can execute sharp jump stops to get downhill.


    When he works through creases, he has effective reach with his stiff-arm and enough leverage to hold off defensive ends, linebackers, and safeties. He pulls through reaches and wraps to his lower legs on a regular basis.


    Whyte’s balance is good enough to bounce off indirect contact to his hips from outside linebackers and direct hits to his lower legs from safeties. He’ll often extend through the contact for extra yards, finishing strong.


    In addition to spotting bounce-out and cutback opportunities, Whyte sets up runs with patience and hits creases decisively. When penetration reaches the backfield, he gives his team a fighting chance to turn potential losses into strong gains.


    Whyte carries the ball high and tight to his frame. However, he’s inconsistent with the effort. On some plays he doesn’t lose that carriage frequently—even when he’s changing direction. Other plays, White’s carriage is low and loose. He’s conscientious with using the arm that’s away from the pursuit.


    One of the speediest backs in the NFL Draft, he can beat all three levels of defenders in the open field for long plays. Even something as mundane as a swing pass can turn into a long gain.


    Whey catches the ball over his shoulder in stride. He can have some minor tracking issues that lead to juggled targets but he will secure the ball.


    He squares and punches effectively on defenders that he seals inside as a lead blocker for outside runs. He moves his feet well to stay with the opponent. Whyte is effective as part of a double team of defensive linemen.


    He also squares and meets blitzing linebackers in the A- gaps with good hand position. However, he must keep his head up at the point of confrontation or he forfeits his leverage or gives the linebacker time to work around the block. Whyte must develop an uppercut punch with proper leverage and force.


    If Whyte can prove a reliable receiver and improve his pass protection, he could become a strong change-of- pace runner with big-play upside.


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: An athletic pickup for the end of deeper rosters with practice squads, Whyte has less every-down upside than a few of the backs below him on the list. However, his immediate upside is as strong, if not stronger, because of his big-play ability.

  25. Devine Ozigbo, Nebraska (5-11, 222)


    Depth of Talent Score: 76.1 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    At first glance, Ozigbo looks like Falcons and Chargers running back Michael “The Burner” Turner. He has a low center of gravity with well-developed thighs, glutes, and calves. However, Ozigbo is nearly 25 pounds lighter than Turner’s NFL listed weight. A good memory (or a little research) confirms that Turner played at 225 pounds at NIU.


    Ozigbo is a capable zone runner with initial burst and enough long speed to start in the NFL. His acceleration can get him the short corner on designed plays to the perimeter as well as unplanned bounce-outs. He’s quick enough to beat some safeties around the corner. He runs through reaches and he has enough cutback quickness to avoid the first man plugging an outside crease, but not quite enough to always hit that crease without pursuit catching him and forcing a scrum.


    He consistently presses creases when a lane opens early or penetration is making its way towards him. This allows him to maximize his cutbacks, which he does well. At the same time, he’ll also hit a crease immediately when it’s a short-yardage situation so he doesn’t waste time. He accounts for game situations with good decision-making.


    Ozigbo employs stutter steps and other stride variations to set up creases or work around penetration. His hips are flexible enough to open quickly with the point of a toe at 90 degrees and it helps him execute sharp turns. He can sequence bounces inside and cutbacks outside in succession and get skinny through a crease.


    Ozigbo’s stop-start moves are good enough to dip inside or outside penetration coming down the line. He needs 2- 3 steps to transition from an outside approach to a downhill run. He’s also improved his efficiency with avoiding penetration by turning the hips towards the sideline rather than taking a step into the penetration before attempting an evasive maneuver.


    A strong back, Ozigbo drags defenders easily and he’ll bounce off defenders with good pad level, too. He’ll easily push piles 2-3 yards without a lot of momentum.

    Defensive ends are sent backwards from indirect contact.


    Ozigbo carries the ball with either arm but his elbow isn’t tight enough. He has been susceptible to defenders pulling his arm loose of his frame and freeing the ball while he’s fighting for yardage in the scrum. His ball security rate is 1 per 117, on the cusp of the starter tier but just a committee-caliber rating.


    A sure-handed receiver, Ozigbo can make catches with full extension of his frame for targets arriving over his shoulder and with a defender coming down hill for the hit. He’s reliable with his hands and against contact that hits him in the front of the waist or in the back.


    Ozigbo will work tight into defenders on double teams to generate a push on a larger defensive lineman. His punches are well-timed and he can slide outside to

    square a defensive back blitz and force the defender to a standstill.


    He still has to develop a punch and he can misjudge blitzes—and at difficult moments. He misjudged a double-blitz off the left side late in the game on a red zone play and his quarterback didn’t have time to throw the ball away to preserve time on the clock. The sack ended the game.


    He’s flexible enough to deliver cut blocks. He can get a little higher and deeper with his shot on linebackers but the work was competent. Ozigbo is an adept decision maker as a lead blocker on sprint-outs, knowing when to double-back and the angle to take on a pursuing defensive end.


    Ozigbo’s profile began to rise this year. Coaches attribute it to an increased maturity with how he sees the game on the field. He also played through an ankle injury in 2016, which probably limited his development. Despite the injury, he’s played at least 11 games every year.


    RSP Boiler Room: Hips, Footwork, and Acceleration Devine Ozigbo Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Monitor from afar until there’s good reason to consider him for a roster spot. He can probably be had as a priority waiver claim after your rookie drafts.


  26. Damarea Crockett, Missouri (5-11, 225)


    Depth of Talent Score: 76.7 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Crockett is an intriguing boom-bust play. If his acceleration and speed translate to starter thresholds and he plays to the best of his ability, he’s no worse than a rotational starter. However, Crockett’s energy level—and sometimes his effort—dwindled when forced to share time with another back. And, I think it had more to do with Crockett’s relationship to offensive coordinator Derek Dooley rather than working with a second back.


    Crockett ran gap and zone plays at Missouri. He executes well on off-tackle zone and counter. He can be patient, but he must make better reads against penetration at the entrance of the crease.


    Ne needs better footwork choices like dips instead of spins when getting attacked while working towards the sideline or run to the end.


    Crockett also can try to veer from the path of a play with the hope of creating a bigger play and winds up with less than the original plan.


    In terms of physical and technical tools, Crockett has the ability to chop his stride in half and has good ankle flexion to make sharp parallel cuts, jump stops, and jump cuts. His agility isn’t bad at his current weight but he needs extra steps to make a transition downhill while working towards the edge of a defense.


    He’s strong enough to push linebackers downhill when he can deliver pads at an angle in the hole. He has enough

    burst to beat backside pursuit and the deep speed to challenge some defensive backs—including corners for long runs.


    Crockett is strong enough to pull through the wrap of defensive tackles penetrating up the middle. He can pull most defenders 3-4 yards after contact. He’ll push a pile as well. He extends through wraps and leans for extra yardage. He also has an effective stiff arm. When he’s motivated he can knock over defensive tackles and linebackers with his size, explosion, and intensity.


    He can turn and catch the ball with his hands away from his body and at helmet level in the flat. He can alo track the ball over his shoulder.


    Crockett uses either arm based on the location of the ball. He also carries the ball high to his chest and tight. Still, he fumbled the ball every 68 touches, which is the low end of the committee tier for ball security.


    He can do better as a blocker. He will ignore or behave as if he missed a blitz and then watch that defender sack his quarterback. This happens with play action when he acts out the fake, sees the pressure, and then carries out the rest of the fake anyhow. He’ll overextend and lower his head into assignments. And he’ll fail to move his feet with a defender’s movement.


    When Crockett cut blocks, he doesn’t explode through the defender and he leads too low. When he’s trying, he has the quickness to mirror and the hands to punch.

    Instead, he’s hugging defenders with poor placement.


    Crockett was a big-time recruit who was lighter and quicker prior to 2018. In 2017, a shoulder injury limited him to six games as a sophomore and he needed surgery.


    Effort is a real question with him. He seemed to lose his edge and motivation when forced to share time with another back and maybe more importantly, work with a new coach in Derek Dooley.


    Damarea Crockett Higlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: He’s worth a late-round pick (after the fourth-round in most rookie drafts).

    Otherwise, monitor. If he earns positive early reviews, add him to rosters in deeper leagues.


  27. Travis Homer, Miami (5-10, 201)


    Depth of Talent Score: 76.6 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Homer plays with physical intensity. He has to play smarter and develop greater technical skill if he wants to be an impactful offensive player. He’s an average-sized runner with starter speed and enough acceleration and quickness to develop into a productive back.


    The intensity versus contact is good. He takes his pads to defenders when he finishes runs. He can get low in a collision with a defender and drag even larger defenders at the line of scrimmage for 2-3 yards.

    His balance with this technique isn’t as strong in the open field. He’ll lose speed and power and fails to pull through the wrap despite having more space to build momentum.


    Homer’s fundamental effort versus contact is good. He’ll keep his feet moving when a defender stalemates him and it gives his teammates time to start a scrum.


    Homer can pull through reaches to his upper body when dealing with penetration in the backfield and he can work through and wraps to his knees.


    He uses his stiff-arm as a tool to ward off defenders in traffic. He’ll even load up the Bolo Punch with his forearm to make first contact in a collision. He also uses the balance-touch technique in the open field when collisions with defensive backs knock him off his stride.


    Homer’s pad level is good enough to float over top or slide to the side of direct collisions against defensive backs as he propels himself forward for extra yards. He runs over safeties routinely when he has momentum into a direct collision. He also has some success with bouncing off indirect contact of linebackers and remaining on his feet when his pads are right.


    Despite his finishing style, he's not a highly powerful back. When he attacks in short-yardage situations, he often lacks the built-up momentum to generate the necessary push for the first down.


    He’ll earn a small push on middle linebackers and defensive tackles when he has to engage head-on. He has potential for greater power, but he drops his head too far into contact. This will be tough for him to fix because pad level is an ingrained behavior when isolating it to this part of the collision.


    Homer ran zone and gap plays at Miami. He displays good patience with outside zone and can work inside-out or outside-in based on his reads of the line. He’ll take what the defense gives him without trying too hard to bounce or cut back.


    He has the burst to dip outside multiple points of penetration and the footwork to adjust his stride and find creases in a slower fashion. He spotted penetration well as a shotgun runner and adjusted his stride to step over the trash of fallen bodies on his way to an open crease.


    He often side-steps defenders, spins off incidental contact, and uses his free arm to swat past reaches as he makes his way through a hole. He can transition from an East-West path to North-South with one step at a good rate of speed.


    Although Homer works effectively as a zone runner, he would be at his best running gap. His eyes-feet connection isn’t great against obstacles at the line and in the backfield as other zone runners. It also matches his ability to split smaller creases between pulling linemen with less manipulation and greater intensity. He’s adept at running the counter play as well as toss and draw plays.


    Homer has the burst to reach the perimeter and bend around the pursuit without losing a lot of speed. He has deep speed, but it’s not special enough to outrun

    cornerbacks with angles over the longest stretches of the field.


    Homer has excellent potential as a receiving back. Miami used him as a receiver from multiple spots on the field, splitting him as a wide receiver, in the slot, and out of the backfield.


    He didn’t run “wide receiver” routes as much as he stretched the field with wheel routes and seam throws, or caught quick throw-outs.


    Homer has the hand-eye coordination to track the ball like a receiver. He catches targets thrown behind his break point that require digging out of the turf with one hand. He also showed the ability to track the ball over his shoulder near the boundary of the end zone with a defender trailing him tight and wrapping as he made the catch.


    Homer is consistent with using the correct hand technique for the location of the target. Although he made occasional errors that resulted in drops and tipped balls, such as not getting his head around fast on a break to the flat or dropping a ball after taking hard contact, Homer has the upside of a star receiving back.


    He must develop as a route runner for it to happen. This includes learning how to adjust for his quarterback when running routes against man-to-man coverage versus zone coverage.


    Homer has the quickness and lateral movement to make effective blocks as an edge protector. He maintains good angles on outside linebackers blitzing off the edge, moving side to side effectively. However, he doesn’t always trust his lateral movement when required to slide across a gap to handle a delayed blitz or pressure that breaks through. He’ll panic and lean rather than slide over with a balanced stance.


    When Homer trusts his movement, he can work outside- in to address a cross blitz with square position on the linebacker. He also has the mobility to work from the backfield to the edge and square the edge pressure.


    Homer earns deep position in the pocket to attack A- and B-gap pressure. He’s patient with how the pressure develops—often choosing the unblocked defender who is the most immediate threat or can’t be picked up by a teammate or avoided by the quarterback. He’s quick enough that he can often address multiple defenders breaking through the pocket.


    The biggest issue with Homer’s pass protection is his punch. He must learn to deliver a punch with his feet on the ground. Too often, he’ll launch into the defender as he punches. These efforts lack control and prevent him from maintaining a position to follow up and remain in the defender’s path.


    When he punches with some level of control, it’s a jab and not an uppercut. The uppercut allows him to redirect his hands more quickly into the defender’s body while maintaining a balanced position. The jab leaves a blocker prone to overextension of his frame and he loses opportunities to latch onto the opponent. Homer also dips his head when he punches.


    At this point, Homer’s protection covers two extremes. He either delivers a hard punch from an off-balanced position with the risk of missing wildly, or he squares the opponent and delivers a weak jab with his head dipped and the defender makes first contact that bulls Homer back into the pocket.


    Because the punch is the foundation for everything that follows, Homer is only effective when he can use his sub- par punch in the quick game when the ball is out fast or when he doesn’t have to punch at all as a chip blocker.


    Ball security is a real problem for Homer. Although he will use the correct arm based on his path and the angles of the pursuit, he often swings it looser in the open field and his elbow is always too loose form his side—even when the ball is high to Homer’s chest. He fumbled the ball once every 62 touches during his career—the bottom-end of the committee tier.


    Homer’s game looked sharper in 2017 than the games I studied in 2018. Still, those games didn’t have enough differences to view him as more than a low-end contributor at this point of his career.


    RSP Boiler Room: Travis Homer Travis Homer Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Even if I decided to be too generous with my grading, Homer would only be higher in the contributor tier. He’ll be drafted late in fantasy leagues because he’s a known quantity from a big program.


    There’s nothing wrong with that tactic. It only takes improvement in a couple of areas for these players to earn relevant playing time.


  28. Qadree Ollison, Pittsburgh (6-1, 228)


    Depth of Talent Score: 76 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Pitt running backs coach Andre Powell has called Ollison one of the smartest players he’s coached in his nearly 30-year career.


    “He’ll make a fine coach one day if he chooses to go that route,” Powell told the Pittsburgh Tribune-Review. “Whenever the air goes out of the ball for him, if I had a chance, I’d hire him in a second.”


    “He’s not only a tailback but he plays a lot of special teams for us. He’s our protector on punt team. He’s very detailed in a lot of things in his work. And we’re fortunate to have Qadree Ollison as part of this program and a Pitt grad.”


    When you watch Ollison play, you can see the intelligence and passion for the game that Powell discussed. He’s a capable runner of zone and gap plays. He has the control of his steps, dropping his weight into downhill transitions and only needing 1-2 steps. Unlike a lot of bigger backs, Ollison runs through wraps to his ankles when working sideline-to-sideline.

    Ollison chops his steps through the exchange to read the line and drops his weight accordingly to bounce or cut back. He’s patient on some ISO plays with a fullback although sometimes he wasn’t as patient behind a lead blocker on perimeter runs—working too fast to landmarks.


    Ollison flips his hips well enough to bounce outside penetration on various gap plays and then flip them back downhill when he avoided the opponent. In addition to his stride and hips, Ollison can jump cut to access the backside crease. His head fakes also freeze opponents as an added setup for his downhill cuts. He had success dipping inside-out to freeze containment at the hash and then use a stiff-arm to work around the man for gains of 30 yards or more.


    He displayed speed to beat a defensive ends, linebackers, and cornerbacks up the sideline for long touchdowns multiple times this year. His 4.58-second, 40-yard speed is good enough to hold maintain separation for gains of 30-50 yards. His hips are flexible and his lateral cuts are strong.


    Has the moves and mobility to work into a crease, jump cut away from penetration find the cutback to the long side of the field and take the corner. He had enough speed and stamina to work the defensive back over with a stiff-arm so he could turn up the field.


    A powerful back, Ollison breaks arm tackles and extends through wraps and falls forward. He has the pad level to work under direct collisions with defensive ends for an extra yard or two. In short-yardage situations, Ollison can pick his way to an open crease or leap over the top of the line.


    Ollison is a second-effort runner. He performs a balance- touch well enough to work through contact against linebackers and defensive ends and earn another 5-6 yards. He also spins off hits.


    He secures the ball high, but the elbow can come a little loose as he makes dramatic moves or accelerates into the open field. He uses the sideline arm to carry the ball. Despite the minor flaws with security, Ollison has only fumbled 2 times in 580 touches at Pitt—a star-caliber rate of 1 per 290 touches.


    Ollison diagnosis blitzes well. He has the footwork to slide across the formation to handle delayed blitzes or late pressure. He also spots twists and takes the correct opponent. He squares his body well and delivers an uppercut punch. When cut blocking, he earns the desired height as he shoots through the opponent’s body.


    He handles interior pressure with a good push, leading with low pads but he loses some collisions because of a pads-first hit. He gets knocked into the pocket for catching that contact rather than greeting it with a punch. He drops his head too often into collisions with larger defenders rather than punching.


    Ollison can catch the ball with contact looming. He uses his hands to make the plays and extends well for targets away from his frame in the flats.

    If Ollison succeeds as more than a backup in the NFL it’s because his movement is quicker and more precise than his performances at the NFL Combine. Stylistically he moves with the grace, power, and perhaps the underrated quickness of a big back like Arian Foster.

    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: A priority free agent in deep dynasty leagues. Monitor from afar.


    ***Jalen Hurd, Baylor (6-4, 240)


    Depth of Talent Score: 75.75 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    ***Note: This player will not be counted officially in my rankings as a running back. However, this is where would be placed (No.30) based on his tape as a runner—and this is based on is tape before converting to wide receiver. The listed weight is what he was when he played the position.


    Hurd has improved his quickness and footwork since the position change. It’s likely he’d be 7-10 spots higher if he returned to running back and played at his lighter weight.


    Hurd was a top recruit to Tennessee as a running back. He started for the Vols at the position, but requested to switch to receiver. After two years, Hurd left the program and sat out a year as a transfer to Baylor where he was promised he could transition to receiver.


    Hurd still took snaps as a situational running back during games—often in the red zone, short-yardage situations, or as a change of pace runner. He’s no longer 240 pounds, but I listed his playing weight at Tennessee. His wide receiver weight is listed in his profile for that chapter.


    Hurd can push the pile with his size and stand-up defensive ends as an edge protector. He is a capable blocker who can deliver his hands and roll his hips into contact. He often earned a push and turned edge rushers with his size and technique. Hurd can refine his blocking by getting better initial position and not setting up too early. He also can deliver his hands with an even fuller uppercut motion that will maximize his power when he rolls his hips into contact.


    That force also worked well with his stiff-arm. He used it frequently with perimeter runs.


    Hurd had enough burst at 240 pounds to reach linebackers and work around the corner when earning the ball on outside runs. Despite his burst, Hurd has to be more patient with gap runs, especially to the edge. He can outrun or outpace his lead blocks and wind up giving linebackers and safeties time to adjust their angles to avoid the blocks and tackle the runner.


    Hurd lacks true breakaway speed. He’s fast enough to flip the field 35-40 yards. Anything longer and cornerbacks have a greater shot of recovering and overtaking him.


    When he gets low with his pads, he pushes a pile and leans through contact to his legs. Hurd reads the linebackers and safeties effectively, but his feet didn’t consistently respond to what he was mentally processing. He doesn’t alter his stride length well at all and it

    compounds issues with changing direction, timing his acceleration, and finishing with leverage.


    If he can improve his feet, he could be a much better runner. In fact, Hurd’s transition to receiver has helped him become a better runner. He’s lighter on his feet, executes good cuts, drops his weight quicker and deeper, and accelerates more effectively through contact.


    If he’s a complete failure as a wide receiver, which I don’t think will happen, there would be reason to ask him if he’d like to return to his old position.


  29. Myles Gaskin, Washington (5-9, 205)


    Depth of Talent Score: 75.05 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.


    Gaskin had an excellent career at Washington and he’s a terrific college running back. He’s smart enough, savvy enough, athletic enough, and technically sound enough to make the NFL. However, there are few qualities about his game that are starter-caliber when examining his depth of talent.


    Two of the exceptions are his ball security and burst. Gaskin has started 4 seasons at UW and he’s only fumbled 1 time per 254 touches. His high-and-tight technique with either arm is a reflection of that skill.


    Reliability is half the battle. The majority of his game is mostly contributor and reserve quality level skill. Gaskin will help a team—and on occasion, he may even have impact moments on the field—but he projects as a passing-down or two-minute player. And before he can fulfill that promise, there’s work to do.


    Gaskin has flexible ankles and good bend with his knees to drop his weight and execute cuts and turns. He jump- cuts well enough to make a defender miss in the backfield, in the hole, or past the line of scrimmage. His burst gets him around the long corner, beating pursuit down the line and around the corner. Although his acceleration is excellent, he lacks the control to transition downhill without taking at least 3-4 steps to make the adjustment.


    This also showed up with his 7.19-second Three Cone time, which is one-hundredth of a second fast than a reserve-caliber effort. It’s still good enough to be in the league when examined in a vacuum, but it’s doubtful that a staff will want to build offensive sub packages of perimeter runs or give him Cole Beasley’s route packages to feature Gaskin’s quickness on a weekly basis. He often gets caught from behind by linebackers after changing direction and getting downhill.


    Gaskin’s change of direction is good enough for selected work outside and between the tackles. His slalom cuts are effective against penetrating defensive tackles. He has enough stop-start ability to navigate creases and he can cut well off either foot.


    He has the right balance of patience and decisiveness on pin-and-pull sweeps and other zone plays. He reads second-level blocks and makes good decisions based on his reads. However, he also can become too tentative

    because he’ll bypass an opportunity to seek a better one and the defense closes on him.


    He’s a better zone runner than gap runner at this point because he’ll try for cutbacks on gap plays, working away from his lead blocker into no-man’s land. He must learn to cultivate the designed gap with patience and shorter steps rather than abandon it to seek a bigger play.


    Gaskin pulls through reaches to his legs, waist, and upper body. He can break these attempts against all three levels of defenders and he doesn’t require momentum to generate this power. His body lean and ability to pull defenders who wrap him is competent.


    He often works under linebackers for an extra yard or two and can push safeties and most defensive backs for extra yards—against direct and indirect contact. He has some isolated instances of bouncing off indirect contact against defensive linemen, but it’s not consistent enough to award him for it in the evaluation.


    Gaskin twists and turns through wraps and extends his frame for extra yards. He’s more difficult to tackle in the open field. This is where he runs through the majority of wraps and gets his best pushes thanks to the momentum he’s built. His contact balance against direct hits isn’t as strong of an asset. Defensive backs can stalemate him even with momentum built up. Linebackers can often knock Gaskin backwards.


    Gaskin projects well as a potential space player because of his ball security, acceleration, balance against linebackers and defensive backs, and his receiving skill. He extends and adjusts well to the ball with sound hands techniques for the location of the target. This includes high-pointing targets and tracking the ball over his shoulder. Gaskin also works with his quarterback after the initial route fails to break open and finds an open zone.


    Gaskin must cultivate a punch as a blocker. He leans and offers his shoulder, but that will get his quarterback sacked. His best asset is cut blocking. He earns good position on blitzing linebackers and defensive backs.


    While there may be runners with more promising athletic skills, technical skills, or upside in different areas of the game than Gaskin, if a team selects him for his potential as a receiver in space, it’s a sound decision.

    Myles Gaskin Highlights


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Monitor from afar.


    Tier VI: These seven players have talent to play in the NFL. They project as reserves, but scheme fit, specific skills, or unusually quick development could propel them to greater heights.

  30. Karan Higdon, Michigan (5-9, 206)


    Depth of Talent Score: 73.9 = Reserve: Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.


    Higdon displays patience for setting up cutbacks, pressing close to the line of scrimmage. He has patient stride adjustments to set up creases on zone and gap plays. He cuts well, transitioning downhill from a well- paced East-West approach with only 1-2 steps.


    He also displays good patience behind his fullback to set up linebackers and safeties into the wrong holes as he cuts back into the open area. Higdon reads the helmets of the line play well enough to find the open creases. He displays discipline with prioritizing the smaller down-and- distance need over the potential of bounce-out that would gain more yards.


    On gap plays, which are mostly what Michigan ran, Higdon hits creases hard. However, there are times where he could chop his steps a bit more to set up his lead blocker and not run into the man’s back.


    Higdon has starter speed and enough acceleration to pull away from linebackers and some safeties. If Higdon earns good angles, he can beat cornerbacks. He times his burst well into the crease. He can earn the short corner with his burst and he makes crisp, downhill cuts with acceleration through the hole.


    Higdon can be reticent to maintain an outside track on runs designed for the perimeter and will try to cut back to the inside to a fault. He has the speed to maintain early separation he achieved versus a stacked box.


    Higdon keeps his feet moving and runs with a low pad level. He can win a head-on collision with a safety and knock the defender backwards as he continues forward for a short gain. He’s capable of pulling through multiple lower body wraps on carries where he has built up speed through the crease and into the secondary.


    However, Higdon is not a pile pushing back. He can run through wraps and bounce off hits, but unless he’s one- on-one with a defensive back, he’s not pushing anyone else backwards.


    If a linebacker hits Higdon from the side, Higdon is likely going sideways and to the ground. If the linebacker hits him straight-on, Higdon’s progress will be stalemated. A defensive lineman’s hit likely stands up Higdon.


    Occasionally, Higdon will combine his agility and balance to bounce off an indirect hit to his shoulder by a defensive lineman. His power is mostly about running through wraps, earning short gains through contact, and attacking defensive backs in the secondary when he has the momentum to bounce off their glancing contact.


    While skeptical about the idea of a player having a “nose for the end zone,” some of Higdon’s more determined finishes come in that area of the field.


    Higdon can slide laterally to square edge rushers. He has an uppercut punch that he rolls his hips through and delivers with good hands position. He’ll reset his feet

    after a punch to anchor his position and deliver a second punch.


    Despite his work as a puncher, he has a tendency to lean into larger pass rushers while punching. This leads to Higdon overextending.


    Higdon has some good diagnostic skill. He reads dual blitzes and picks the correct man based on his and his teammates’ assignments. When he has to face two unblocked rushers, he knows the one to take so his quarterback has the best chance of safety.


    For his size, showed skill to square and hold up a defensive tackle from collapsing the pocket into the quarterback. He couldn’t anchor, but he slowed the progress of the much larger defender.


    He catches the ball with his hands and in the two-minute drill he displayed awareness to get out of bounds early. Although not used extensively in the passing game, Higdon has a good catch radius to extend low for the ball. He also makes plays with his back to the passer.


    His ball security is sound and he uses either arm based on the pursuit. His security rate is 1 fumble per 162 touches—a starter rate with the RSP’s thresholds.


    Higdon will be working for a shot as the third back on a depth chart.


    RSP Boiler Room: Quality over Quantity



    Karan Higdon Highlights

  31. Ty Johnson, Maryland (5-10, 208) Depth of Talent Score: 73.85 = Reserve:

    Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.


    Johnson is a breakaway threat. He has strong stop-start quickness and he can make dynamic movements side-to- side. When he bounces a play away from downhill penetration, he often has the acceleration and speed to reach his goal.


    Johnson’s long speed is probably the best in the class. He outruns good angles by cornerbacks. He’s a skilled return specialist and this is likely where he’ll thrive in the NFL.


    Johnson’s acceleration is notable. He can run through reaches—especially to his lower legs—because of his rate of speed. His transitions downhill are sudden and efficient. He can reverse field from the short side of the field to the long side and take the run up the sideline. He was able to pull away from a defensive end’s reach and bounce off minimal contact from him to reverse field.


    Johnson’s deceleration is nearly as impressive as his acceleration. This gives him potential as a route runner. His talents as a return specialist with running back and receiver experience, remind me of former Lions return specialist Jeremy Ross.


    Johnson uses his pacing to set up creases with good timing. His stop-start quickness allows him to dip away from pursuit.

    Johnson finishes with good pad level and carries the ball under the appropriate arm away from pursuit. His pads and lean get him very low in the hole. He can collide head-on with safeties and push his way forward for 3-4 yards. He can drag a defensive end a few yards when wrapped high and in backside pursuit.


    His pad level is good enough to work under defenders’ hits. However, his head goes down as he initiates contact and it limits his ability to maintain his footing and earn yards through contact. He also slows down at the point of contact with his pads rather than accelerating into the contact where he has a greater chance to win and stay upright.


    He has some facility with inside and outside zone, but he needs to adjust his stride to set up blocks a little better. As a receiver, Johnson can catch over his shoulder with his arms extended from his frame.


    I didn’t see Johnson block in the games I studied. I also didn’t see him fumble and according to multiple stats resources, there wasn’t a fumble on his record in 430 touches.


    Depending how he performs, Johnson’s overall depth of talent grade could realistically be 1-3 points higher if I saw him pass protect. Even so, the added value wouldn’t propel him inside the RSP’s top 20.


    He’s an exciting player, but his game isn’t well-rounded enough as a runner to earn significant playing time. He should become a productive return specialist immediately.


    RSP Boiler Room: Footwork to Maximize Acceleration



    Ty Johnson Highlights

  32. Travon McMillian, Colorado (5-11, 203)


    Depth of Talent Score: 73.4 = Reserve: Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.


    McMillian transferred to Colorado after attending Virginia Tech. He’s a hard-running scat back with starter-caliber speed. His style is reminiscent of former UCLA star Johnathan Franklin, but he’s not as refined of talent.


    McMillian is a one-cut runner who maintains good pad level and sustains intensity to finish strong. He drops his pads low enough to knife through direct contact against linebackers. He’ll consistently stalemate or defeat linebackers and safeties at the end of runs with direct collisions.


    He’ll earn 1-2 yards when taking defensive linemen in direction collision. If the defender wraps McMillian high, McMillian pull the opponent for 2-3 yards.


    McMillian extends his frame at the end of collision for extra yards. He can bounce off contact and maintain his feet when he lands the forearm.

    He can also pull through reaches to his frame. He’ll often break multiple reaches in a single carry when working in traffic. He also wards them off with his stiff-arm.


    McMillian maintains a high-and-tight carriage of the ball and will even cover it like an old-school fullback when facing collisions in traffic. His elbow can be too wide from his frame, but the overall technique is good enough that he earned a starter grade despite his security rate of 1 fumble per 119 carries being on the cusp of starter and committee tiers.


    McMillian is an effective gap scheme runner. He has a feel for setting up creases with small pace and stride alterations before hitting the crease hard. He also anticipates creases opening and accelerates towards the point of the opening before it actually happens. He shows good knowledge of the play call and understands the timing of his teammates.


    He will even leave his feet to reach the small hole to get into creases and then drive for a push.


    He also has the footwork to run zone plays. He works deep to the line to press a lane and then cut to the open crease. He does this well pressing inside or outside of the crease.


    McMillian has a slashing style. He drops his weight into hard cuts. He often uses jump cuts after his initial presses of the line of scrimmage. He can set up gap and zone plays with this movement as well as avoid penetration.


    Against defenses that overmatched McMillian’s offensive line, he repeatedly found ways to avoid penetration with creative footwork solutions or a spin move, turning big losses into smaller losses or short gains. He’ll also weave around penetration and then back onto the path toward the open crease. McMillian can open his hips with a toe- point and bounce outside an obstacle.


    His footwork isn’t as refined when trying to set up cutbacks on toss plays. He’ll have touches where his stride length is too long and it prevents him from reading his blocks efficiently. He has to work on taking shorter steps through his exchange with the quarterback so he can avoid penetration as well as give himself a little more time to read pulling blocks.


    McMillian squares his opponents after sliding to the assignment point in the pocket. He picks up interior blitzes, looping defenders, and twists. He’s most effective as a shield blocker, chip blocker, or part of a double team with a tackle.


    McMillian has an uppercut punch in his arsenal, but the punch is inconsistent and needs to be quicker and more forceful. He allows opponents to get the first strike too often and he often loses the confrontation because of it. When he’s using his punch, he can stop linebackers blitzing the interior gaps and turn them away from the pocket.


    He has to work on stalk blocking so he's set up in a square position, or he winds up off-balance and out of control throughout the entire interaction. When he’s

    using the uppercut technique, he’s hitting first and controlling interactions, but there’s too much variation with his efforts to count on him in this facet of the game. Still, there’s potential for McMillian to become a much better blocker in the NFL than he was in college.


    McMillian uses his hands to catch the ball. He can turn to his back shoulder on the flat route and secure the ball with under hand technique near his chest while working away from the quarterback. He tracks the ball over his shoulder and displays active hands on throws over the middle. The drops he had were difficult targets that require awkward turns and longer extensions of his frame that he was capable.


    McMillian makes quick transitions from receiver to runner—even when the target requires an awkward or difficult turn to make the reception. He runs flat breaks on routes breaking to the sideline.


    McMillian has experience as a return specialist. He’ll have to draw upon this skill and more special team work to begin his career.

    Travon McMillian vs. USC

  33. Mike Weber, Ohio State (5-10, 211) Depth of Talent Score: 73.45 = Reserve:

    Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.


    Weber displays enough patience and awareness to read the line and adjust to penetration as he’s taking the exchange. He can make quick adjustments during the exchange to avoid defenders already deep into the backfield. His feet are quick enough to work across the back of his blockers and avoid backside pursuit and shoot the gap downhill.


    Inside zone and gap plays are his bread and butter— especially gap plays where he has a knack for finding solutions to problems that he’s not as consistent at when running zone. Weber will read and react to linebackers as he approaches the line and he can string moves together with quick enough feet to have a fighting chance at working past a linebacker and perhaps a safety.


    He has a bad habit of being tied to the jump-cut and other footwork maneuvers more complicated than he’s capable of executing in a given situation. He winds up slipping and getting stuffed. This includes situations where he anticipates penetration, but doesn’t use the simplest and most elegant solutions and the play fails.


    Weber also loses discipline and tries reversing field when edge contain foils his work outside. He tries too much for a big play when getting the hard yards is part of being a highly productive running back. He does this on other runs, ceding ground when the necessary yardage is in his grasp because he’s going for the big play. He often loses the yardage he easily had. Although gap plays are his best format, Weber isn’t patient enough with pulling blocks to the edge.

    Weber’s game isn’t the sum of its parts. He’s quick- footed, but he doesn’t know how to draw on it well enough to consistently make advanced decisions required of a top college player and NFL starter. He has speed, but his acceleration isn’t as notable. Because his footwork and decision-making has flaws with refinement and maturity, he’s not maximizing his skills consistently enough in situations where he should.


    He uses his hip mobility to transition downhill from an East-West approach within 1-2 small steps. His speed is good enough to reach the sideline and pull away from many defensive backs. He has cutback ability to the edge that will challenge linebackers and defensive ends.


    Weber has decent, but not top-drawer power and balance. He drops the pads and gets a push on defensive backs and linebackers. Occasionally he can move a defensive lineman when that lineman is in a disadvantageous position and has no leverage.


    Weber wins collisions against linebackers and safeties but he’s often stopped and, at best, forced into a scrum when attacking linemen in the hole. He can spin away from contact and run through reaches and wraps, but hits take him to the ground easier than his frame would suggest they should.


    Ball security is a limiting factor of his game. He can use the correct arm versus pursuit and his carriage his high in traffic. However, he favors his left arm too much and his elbow is generally loose from his frame.


    Weber fumbles the ball way too much—1 per 60 touches. This rate is at the bottom end of the RSP’s reserve tier and on the cusp of rampantly bad work. Correcting this issue will go a long way towards Weber becoming a viable backup rather than a third back on a depth chart.


    Weber catches the ball well. He turns and reaches over his outside shoulder for the ball and can make the one- handed snare with good hand-eye coordination. Most of his work is in the short range of the field, so he has to show more in workouts that he can catch with a variety of hands techniques based on different target locations.


    The best part of Weber’s game might be pass protection. He has a strong punch where he rolls his hips through the contact. He often earns strong position in the pocket to attack assignments. His sets are at good angles and he’s deep into the line to give his quarterback a good buffer.


    He picks up line twists effectively. He also slides across the pocket to take on blitzing edge defenders and defensive backs. His timing and angles are excellent. His chips are violent.


    Weber transitions from receiver to blocker well. He will use a one-arm technique on a defender if needed. His cut blocks are across the body and high enough on the opponent’s frame.


    Weber’s technique is good enough for him to do work in the NFL now, but he’ll need to stop overextending against larger defenders in the middle of the pocket. He catches contact in these situations and gets pushed.

    Expect Weber to make a roster this year. Weber earning anything more than the No.3 spot on a running back depth chart will be a surprise.


    Mike Weber Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Monitor from afar.


  34. Jalin Moore, Appalachian State (5-10, 212)


    Depth of Talent Score: 73.1 = Reserve: Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.


    Moore suffered an ankle fracture and dislocation in October that required surgery. Fortunately for Moore, dislocations of the ankle don’t have a strong risk of recurring the way shoulders with past dislocations do.


    Moore has enough skill to challenge for an NFL roster spot. He possesses strong timing with his acceleration and using a lead blocker. He’s an effective runner on off- tackle zone, using the fullback to set up creases.


    Moore has effective stride alteration, quick stop-start movement, and good re-acceleration to reach creases. When the defense blows up the play design, Moore finds alternate cutback lanes. Appalachian State’s offensive line was leaky enough that Moore often couldn’t take advantage of the numerous cut back lanes he spotted but couldn’t reach due to penetration.


    When Moore can access a crease, he gets downhill fast, hitting the hole hard. His straight-arm is a sound tool for pushing off defenders reaching for him in the crease and it helps him when he’s bouncing a run to the edge.


    Moore has the hip mobility to open up and turn with one sharp step. He can set up this change of direction with a stutter and dip to bait a defensive back.


    When his teammates can scramble to provide a little support after giving up initial penetration, Moore is quick enough to reverse field and work to the far edge of the field, turning a certain loss into a strong gain. His spin move is sudden. He keeps his knees high in traffic to lift his feet away from reaches and wraps in the hole.

    Whenever Moore has room to stop-start, he’ll find a secondary crease and accelerate through it to open field. He’s not averse to hitting a crease that's tight or occupied if nothing else is there and will decisively attack it with pads low, earning a healthy push.


    Moore breaks wraps to his legs. He’ll push through contact—even a defensive lineman—and extend his body forward. He can attack a safety head-on and spin off or bounce off for additional yards. High reaches and low wraps do not bring Moore to the ground.


    One of the greatest strengths of Moore’s game is his ability to get square to a defender and slide into position fast for a block—even when the assignment requires a quick change of direction. He’s good at reading blitzes coming from linebackers and safeties behind the line of scrimmage. He considers primary and secondary assignments and transitions well from one to the other.


    Moore earns good placement with his hands when attacking an opponent and can generate a push or

    moving the defender away from the pocket. He must make an uppercut punch part of his repertoire. He allows too much first-contact from defenders and gets pushed backwards or discarded. Even when he’s in a position to deliver a punch, he doesn’t.


    Moore catches the ball with proper techniques for the location of the target. He extends fully for passes away from his frame. He struggles with targets into his body and behind his break path. He can lose concentration when there’s impending contact. Most of his work was done as an outlet receiver.


    Moore carries the ball with either arm based on the pursuit angles. His carriage is high to his chest and he’s only fumbled at a rate of 1 per 205 touches—squarely in the star tier for the RSP’s security efficiency.


    RSP Boiler Room: Yards Through Contact And Agility



    Jalin Moore Higlights

  35. Jeremy Cox, Old Dominion (6-0, 235)


    Depth of Talent Score: 72.5 = Reserve: Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.


    Cox is intriguing as a late-round guy because he’s a big back with the flexible hips and awareness of a productive runner. He’s built like former Denver Broncos running back Mike Anderson and his game has some commonalities with the former Utah back.


    Cox has the hip mobility to make wide parallel cuts away from defenders pursuing him from over top. He adjusts his stride length at the entrance of creases and he can drop his weight to make sharp cuts.


    He finds bounce-out and cutback opportunities in the zone scheme. When he crams the ball up the middle, he has the acceleration to reach the secondary if he moves through the hole untouched.


    Cox also spots the cutback lane and can make dips in succession to work away from the front side of a play. He has enough quickness to do it but needs the room with his cuts to execute.


    Although he has good mobility with his hips, he needs 2- 3 steps to transition from an East-West approach to a North-South run. If he’s making the transition after running across the width of the field, he’ll need 3-4.


    Cox can lose balance and momentum trying to cut downhill in these situations and it costs him balance, momentum, and power. He does a better job of opening his hips to make sharp turns early in a run when he’s facing penetration into the backfield.


    Once up to speed, he doesn’t have great control over attempts at curvilinear movement, so bending runs around the edge isn’t as good of a solution as cutting. Cox has a spin move, but it’s more of a tool for pulling through wraps than making opponents completely miss. He’s fast enough to beat angles of some safeties.

    Cox uses his size well as a power runner, but not to its greatest potential. He can drop his pads and bounce off all three levels of a defense—including the linemen— when colliding against indirect contact.


    His hips need to be angled a little more behind his pads when he engages in direct confrontations. He must keep his feet moving through contact longer than he does.

    When he does, he can push piles 3-5 yards. The power is there. Cox must unlock it with better technique.


    Cox has a stiff-arm and he’ll use it against larger defenders effectively. He can switch the ball to the opposite arm while running. He also needs to tighten the elbow or risk losing he ball.


    Cox has good hands. He’ll extend for the ball away from his frame and he can make receptions to his back- shoulder and back hip.


    He diagnoses the safety blitz looping inside after the snap. He slides his feet quickly. He can turn a defender outside with good footwork. He picks up the cross blitz effectively.


    He missed the final three games with a season-ending ankle injury in 2018. He also missed multiple weeks in 2017 with a fractured collarbone.


    Jeremy Cox Highlights

    Gap-X--

    Zone


    RB Third-Down Table

    Note: PPR leagues have become the standard scoring system in many corners of the fantasy industry. This development and the spreading out of NFL offenses mean that there can be enhanced value for backs with significant receiving roles. The RSP will always remain a football-first publication that caters to the fantasy community. In the spirit of football-first, the default ranking will continue placing significant weight on a runner’s vision and power. However, the Third-Down Table provides a PPR-weighted score decreases the weight of vision and power and distributes it to receiving, blocking, and traits valuable in the open field.

    RB Comparisons Table

    Note: In theory, player comparisons are a reader-friendly way to get a clearer mental picture of a player’s physical build, athleticism, technical skills, and potential. In practice, this is a hit-or-miss process that, at the very least, is an entertaining exercise. Each “-“ is an approximate level of separation between one player’s talent and the next. A “/” between two names means those players have closely matched talents. The key word is “talent,” because there are some players with lesser careers listed ahead of more famous or productive peers. This is my subjective interpretation of skill, not success. For example, I have LaMont Jordan ahead of Chester Taylor on a spectrum of comparison for a runner on this list. Taylor has arguably had the better career, but I believe Jordan had star caliber potential that Taylor lacked.

    Gap-X--Zone


    RB (Depth of Talent) Rankings 2017-2019

    This list of 64 running prospects from the past three years is sorted by Depth of Talent score. It is not an updated ranking, but rather, a look at how I would have seen these players from the same starting point as prospects without a team prior to the draft. Think of the list as one solely about grading talent and not landing spot, scheme, or how the player performed in the NFL.


    Please Note: Due to adjustments made with the RSP’s grading of Ball Handling this year, the 2017 class is operating on stricter standards than the previous two classes. It means the Depth of Talent for previous year’s projects will be inflated by as much as 2-10 points, depending on the severity of those players’ fumble rates. I placed specific players in bold type in the top 10-20 spots whose overall scores would be lower if graded to the 2017 standard.


    The long-term, aspirational goal of this combined list will be to develop a workable score that has some value across draft classes. Because the RSP’s process is built on continuous improvement, adjustments to the scoring criteria will make this aspirational goal difficult to attain over the course of the next few years.


    The realistic goal of this combined list is entertainment value and a starting point for the reader to conduct research on his own that may proof helpful for fantasy leagues. Here are possible ways this list may help:


    • A combined present and short-term historical perspective on the value of players and draft picks at the position.

    • Perspective on emerging, unproven, or declining players (helpful for formulating trade value).

    • A short-term historical perspective with physical and athletic measurements.


      An updated three-year ranking based on how I see these players heading into the 2017 season will be available in the RSP Post-Draft Publication.

      Note: I suggest beginning your examination using tiers by Depth of Talent Score and demarcate the tiers by 10 points:


    • Tier 1: 90-100

    • Tier 2: 80-89

    • Tier 3: 70-79

    • Tier 4: 60-69

Focus more on the range these players fall rather than the linear order. Remember, players with a specific fit in a system may score lower than their actual potential of impact will indicate, which is why the RSP is implementing Scheme-Based analysis for additional perspective and clarity about prospects and their short-term and long-term potential. Players names in bold would have Depth scores 2-10 points lower than they did at the time of publication.


Those who wish to calculate these collegiate fumble rates for past players and make a more refined adjustment of the information can access the game logs for each player in question on Fox Sports (For example, Google “Ameer Abdullah Nebraska Stats Fox Sports”). The site provides stats on fumbles and divides those career totals by total touches (runs, receptions, and returns).


Once determining the fumble rate, refer to the Ball Handling Tier in this chapter, and match the fumble rate to the corresponding score. Then refer to the past the Ball Handling Tiers in previous publications to determine the difference in points between the two for the necessary adjustments.


Most don’t care that much to find this information, but those who even care to ask will be motivated to do the work.
