Wide Receivers


Overview and Fantasy Impact of the Position Skill Breakdowns

Overrated and Underrated Projects

Scheme Based Fits Fantasy Top 52

Top 52 Rankings Table Top 24 Big Board Rankings Top 20 Slot Board Rankings Ranking and Comparisons

2017-2019 Pre-Draft Rankings Scouting Checklists and Profiles

Overview and Fantasy Impact of the WR Position


I described the past four wide receiver classes as talented groups unlikely to knock down the NFL’s front door with its rookie performances. However, each class has had multiple talents capable of long, productive careers.


I warned readers for the past four years that counting on nine rookies to deliver high-end production every year—the curve- breaking impact of 2014’s rookie class—was unrealistic. In any given season, expecting any more than 3-4 productive rookies is unlikely. It wasn’t that long ago that the expected total was only 1-2.


Last year, Calvin Ridley and D.J. Moore ended their rookie seasons as the Nos. 18 and 35 fantasy receivers overall—20th and 36th in PPR, respectively. Two years ago, JuJu Smith-Schuster and Cooper Kupp were the Nos. 17 and 27 overall—22nd and 25th in PPR, respectively. Three years ago, Michael Thomas, Tyreek Hill and Sterling Shepard were the Nos. 9, 15, and 37 overall. And four years ago, Amari Cooper, the No. 32 fantasy receiver overall, was the only viable starter of the bunch.


The 2019 class has the talent to meet the high-end expectation of 3-4 productive rookies. The overall volume of talent is not as deep as last year’s crop, but the talent at the top of the board is more promising. If placed in the right situation, this year’s class has 40 percent more players in its top 10 capable of immediate starter production than the 2018 class. It also has seven players with higher Depth of Talent Scores than 2018’s fifth-rated prospect—including three with higher grades than 2018’s No.1 prospect.


Wide receiver is the ultimate scheme-based position. Fit is a vital part of the equation, because NFL teams, like fantasy owners, are generally all over the board in rating receiver prospects.


The reasons have to do with the application of talent and skill. There are receivers in the NFL that only do a select number of things, but they do them so well that defenses have trouble stopping them.


These talents differ from player to player. In addition to the normal variances of talent evaluation, how these players fit with the scheme and current talents of teammates can mean one organization will have a second-round grade on a prospect that another will rate as a free agent.


Regardless of height, weight, or style of skill set, it’s a good idea to balance optimism with a healthy dose of realism. Don’t count on top-tier production from rookie wide receivers. Yet, remain open to the possibility that three or four might reach the summit based on the boost of quality surrounding talent.


There were 33 receivers selected in 2014 NFL Draft. Nine reached a 500-yard, 5-touchdown threshold in their rookie seasons. Three more were close. In 2015, teams selected 35 receivers. Only 5 earned at least 500 yards. Only 2 earned the 500/5 threshold. The 2016 NFL Draft had 31 receivers among its draft picks, and only 3 met the threshold with 7 earning at least 500 yards.


Two years ago, the NFL selected 32 wide outs. Smith-Schuster, Kupp, Chris Godwin, and undrafted free agent Keelan Cole were the only rookie receivers to earn at least 500 yards. Only Smith-Schuster and Kupp reached 500 yards and 5 touchdowns. Trent Taylor (430) and Kenny Golladay (477) were close to the yardage mark. Four of these six players did a lot of their work from the slot.


Last year, the league drafted 33 receivers. Calvin Ridley was the only receiver to earn at least 500 yards and 5 touchdowns. However, 8 rookies—Ridley, Moore, Courtland Sutton, Antonio Callaway, Christian Kirk, Marques Valdes-Scantling, Robert Foster, and Michael Gallup—earned 500 yards. Ridley, Callaway, Anthony Miller, Dante Pettis, and Tre’Quan Smith earned at least 5 touchdowns.


I have believed, and continue to believe, that 2014 was a super-talented exception among recent receiver classes due to its depth and the unusual opportunity for many of them to see the field early. Injuries (Jaguars and Giants) and veterans getting older or shipped out of town (Pittsburgh, Philadelphia, Buffalo, Arizona, and Carolina) facilitated these rookie opportunities. Because of these past rookie successes, I mentioned that, at some point, there would be too many young receivers occupying meaningful roles for a similar number of rookies from 2016-18 to earn a similar volume of opportunities.


The top producers at the position in the NFL are in the prime of their careers—31 of the 36 top-scoring receivers (using fantasy PPR totals as the gauge) won’t be older than 29 when they begin the 2019 season. Of those 36 options, 21 are no older than 26 and have at most 5 years of pro experience.

There will still be opportunities thanks to injuries, retirements, suspensions, underwhelming veteran play, and rookie talent. As has been the case, count on no more than 3-4 rookie receivers making an instant impact. Be prepared to patiently stash wide receiver talent from this class.


If you don’t anticipate having enough roster space to stash rookies, trade this year’s picks. If you have roster space but your receiver corps is loaded with talent, stockpile at running back and tight end.


With the exception of tight ends in premium scoring (1.5 PPR) leagues, running back and receiver provide dynasty owners the best trade currency. If you view the draft as a mechanism for acquiring resources that mature into playable or tradable talent, you won’t make the mistake of seeking instant bull’s eyes with every selection.


Consider instant impact a bonus rather than an expectation. Many receivers still have a difficult transition to the NFL. The gap in physical talent between them and defenders narrows, passing windows shrink, and the physical and mental complexity of the game heightens.


Many of these young players have to master a broader array of skills than were required in college. Other than the slant or go route, few receivers faced tight man coverage on a consistent basis. Few were expected to have mastery of a broad range of routes, much less the entire route tree. There’s also a difference between running this tree against press coverage and off-man or zone coverage. Also, there is a wealth of adjustments at the line of scrimmage that the rookie has to learn to be in simpatico with his quarterback.


Considering these factors, it’s no surprise that it’s still rare to see rookie receivers posting starting-caliber fantasy production. However, offensive schemes are changing. Some coordinators are simplifying concepts or molding the scheme to the talent more than ever. The “noted exceptions” are gradually becoming more common.


If the past 3-4 years is any indication, the NFL is gradually embracing the college passing game, spreading the field, and relying more on slot receivers as offensive focal points. While the draft media has been lamenting the lack of dynamic perimeter prospects for the past four years, Ridley, Moore, Thomas, Hill, Smith-Schuster, and Kupp have become offensive focal points as versatile slot receivers who did a significant amount of work.

Receivers drafted after 1995 comprise 58 percent of this list. Expand this list to the top-30 first-year receiver performances and receivers picked after 1995 comprise 56 percent of the sample. One-third of these performances have come since I began writing the Rookie Scouting Portfolio in 2006. Michael Thomas, displaced Amari Cooper on this list who displaced Mike Evans the year before, who displaced Keenan Allen the year before that.


Kupp and Tyreek Hill (counting Hill’s combined rushing and receiving totals) placed them within shouting distance of Green’s spot and Smith-Schuster was even closer. While not every team will find the next Hill, Smith-Schuster, or Kupp, if the 2018

class is any indication, it’s what the college game is serving up. The organizations that embrace these slot-perimeter tweeners will be the organizations with successful offenses.


Even as the league expands its profile of the successful receiver to include tweeners, it remains unlikely for us to see 6-8 rookies become fantasy starters every year, unless there’s a slew of injuries to veterans across the league. However, expecting two players to play like starters and two more to provide strong support for NFL teams and fantasy rosters is reasonable. Last year’s class featured two top-36 PPR starters.


The 2019 class with the strength pooled at the top of the board has an enhanced opportunity of proving excecptional.


Despite my overall caution about rookie production, there are 15-18 receivers capable of earning top-25 PPR fantasy production this year if they land in favorable enough environments. I wouldn’t count on more than two players from this class displacing a receiver from the top 25—and, for the past two years, it didn’t happen.

The totals remain steady even if the distribution at the top half of the draft has some recent variance. Based on the talent of the 2019 class and the early returns of the past five classes, I’ll estimate this will be a top-heavy class. Expect 10-12 receivers to earn a first- or second-round pick but only 25-27 will earn a draft pick.


Dynasty and Redraft League Advice


Fantasy owners in dynasty leagues need to be patient with young receivers. Even if that player has the skill to make an instant impact, those skills may not match what the team needs him to do. It’s not uncommon for a talented rookie to join a team with quality players ahead of him.


Remember that veteran contracts are often 1-3 years in length, which means many teams draft with the hopes of developing a rookie without having to pay more money for the veteran. For this reason, it often takes a rookie receiver two- to-three years to earn NFL starter production.


In most situations, re-draft owners would be best advised to use caution when it comes to rookie receivers. That’s why, in re-draft leagues, my general advice is to wait until late if you pick one at all. Some of the better options will be available on

the waiver wire. Odell Beckham didn’t see a lick of training camp or the first month of the regular season. Most fantasy owners wrote him off in 2014 as an injury scratch.


Beckham was my No. 2 receiver six years ago. Tyler Lockett and Stefon Diggs were the Nos.32 and Nos.33 fantasy options after Week 4 in 2015. Tyreek Hill was not considered a fantasy option until the season was well under way. Cooper Kupp was a slow receiver on a bad team with a bust at quarterback (well, not here). Learning enough about a player’s potential in this publication should put you in position to strike when the iron is hot.


It is no surprise that the Rookie Scouting Portfolio’s evaluation method often yields lower scores for wide receivers across the board than running backs, due to the challenges I’ve outlined. There are a number of receivers with grades in the 60’s on my 100-point scale that can develop into quality contributors at the next level.


My checklist evaluations are a reflection of how broad the player’s athleticism and fundamentals are. My talent stacking is where I show depth of talent. If an NFL team knows how to apply that depth of talent productively, a player can have a narrower scope of athleticism and fundamentals (Kelvin Benjamin) and still produce in a system that maximizes what he does best and minimizes what he doesn’t.


At the same time, the best receivers often have the highest scores of any position. The safest way to build dynasty teams through the draft is at wide receiver. The best wide receivers often have careers with 8-12 years of starter production. A running back with 4-6 years of similar production is an unqualified success by comparison. This year’s receiver crop is strong at the top and deep enough that should offer the best long-range return on investment.


This Class: The 10,000-Ft. View


Last year, I thought there were 45-50 receivers with the talent to make a roster, 25 with starter potential in the next 3-4 years, and 24 players with 1,000-yard potential. Divide each number by three—my unscientific Attrition Factor—and you have a realistic projection of what will happen when potential no longer matters: 7-8 starter prospects with 1,000-yard potential.


This year’s 10,000-ft. view is similar but more top-heavy. I think there are 45-50 receivers with the talent to make a roster; 27 with starter potential in the next 3-4 years; and 17 players with 1000-yard potential. Considering the depth of talent already stocked from previous years, it’s safe to change my incredibly unscientific Attrition Factor to four as the number to divide these totals by. This will yeild a good estimate of what’s likely to happen when potential no longer matters: 11-12 receivers with potential to make a roster and 6-7 of those players with starter potential.


There are more players this year (12) than last (8) who I believe can become reliable starters—60-80 catches, 800-1,100 yards, and 6-8 scores—regardless of quarterback talent. This year, ten have the potential to develop into perennial Pro-Bowl players. Regardless of the potential to start, there are an abundance of wide receivers this year with potential to play a decade in the NFL.


As with every class, there will be players who don’t play to expectation and players who will wildly exceed them. My job is to give you an idea of who can be good and why. At this early vantage point, 2019 is an excellent class for drafting receivers if you’re patient and realistic about the overview of the position. There are 10 players with legitimate talent to develop into the leading receiver for its team within the next 2-3 years.


This class also has a healthy number of complementary starters—possession receivers, deep threats, and YAC specialists— with production potential. Of the top 25 receivers on the RSP’s board, 15 players fit this complementary description.


How to Best Use My Rankings for Fantasy Drafts


There are two sets of rankings at your disposal when you purchase the RSP: The April Pre-NFL Draft rankings that weigh heavily towards talent and the May Post-Draft RSP update that factors both talent and team fit.


The pre-NFL draft rankings in this publication are based on how I perceive the player’s technique, talent, athleticism, and potential for growth. I do this with a variety of analysis methods—none of them have to do with where I think a player might be drafted.


Evaluating talent and evaluating where in the draft, if at all, to invest in that talent, are two different processes. This pre- draft publication was created to consider the long-term value of player regardless of where he is drafted, the perception of his character, or his place on a depth chart. These factors may shape the initial opportunities that a player will earn, but they aren’t meaningful statements about his on-field skill. Players mature, teammates move on, and opportunities arise that once didn’t seem feasible. It’s why the RSP has a shelf life of at least 3-5 years.

If your rookie draft takes place before the NFL Draft, I will note when I believe I have ranked a player higher than consensus, so you can make informed decisions about how to adjust my rankings into a draft board that suits your needs. If I have a player ranked sixth at his position, but he’s considered a fifth-round value, I recommend you consider that player “undervalued” for fantasy purposes. You can wait to acquire him later. In some leagues, it might be prudent not to draft the player at all because he’ll be available as a free agent, and you can track his progress without using a roster spot.


In some situations, you’ll have to decide whether or not you agree with my assessment of the player’s talent or value him according to his draft position and opportunity with his new team. This year, I have also filtered my overall rankings into a draft board for slot candidates and big receivers. This should prove helpful to many risk-averse fantasy owners when it comes to avoiding smaller receivers—although this strategy is appearing too conservative in recent years.


Rookie Productivity—A Historical Perspective


The difference in rookie production between receivers drafted by round over the past 13 years is small. The samples are still too small for more than an anecdotal observation, but the idea that the scheme fit drives variation in draft grades across the league makes sense for this position.

About 2019’s Wide Receiver Rankings

The RSP now has two grading scales: Depth of Talent and Breadth of Talent. The traditional checklist that has been around since the RSP began remains in place. What it measures is the number of things that a player can do at his position.


The RSP’s Skill Breakdowns have evolved into a measure of how well a player can perform those skills according to defined tiers of performance expectations. Weights have been assigned to the tiers and like the checklist, there is a total score.


The Checklist Score is the Breadth of Talent Score, while the Skill Breakdowns generate the Depth of Talent Score. The RSP will be using the Depth of Talent Score to build its player rankings.


Because the Depth of Talent Score awards small bonuses to players who show particular potential for development in specific areas, the RSP will also provide a table that ranks players without the projection bonuses. This third table will provide readers additional context about where I see these players now and what I foresee from them in the future.


This analysis is performed with a grading system with defined criteria (see the Glossary), play-by-play observation, a player’s realistic development potential, and measurement of his physical skills.


The Difference Between Pre-Draft And Post-Draft Rankings

In addition to its utility for fantasy football, rankings are a helpful exercise for any evaluator or draftnik. Describing my rankings process should also provide additional insight and usefulness to the fantasy owner. I want my readers to see some of the nuance behind the ranking of a player.


Rankings Creation


The first step is watching football. I watch hundreds of games each year—recorded broadcasts, cutups produced by DraftBreakdown.com, and individual cutups produced on YouTube—and grade players one session at a time.


I try to grade a player at least twice, but what’s more important to me than the number of games is the amount of touches, attempts, or targets that I can see in a game. I’m seeking the greatest variety of scenarios that the player has experienced.


While it will always remain a work in progress—that’s the nature of process improvement—there are years of work behind the RSP grading system. I don’t have to think as hard about how I grade a player, because the process is defined well enough for me to follow it without questioning it all the time. The questions I do have come about as an organic part of the process and they’re helpful in making the RSP a better publication.

I used to take notes on close to 100 percent of the plays that feature the prospect or where he has a contributing role. This often included down-and-distance information, time on the clock, offense and defense formation, and pre-snap adjustments on both sides of the ball. I then note the actions of the player within the context of this information: technique, physical skill, and decision-making, including what could have been done better.


While a fantastic exercise for anyone who wants to learn more about the game, it has reached the point of diminishing returns for me. I’ll continue transcribing games for future publications, because it’s a worthwhile exercise in maintaining a disciplined eye for the details of the grading system. However, I have decreased the frequency of transcriptions over the past two years and their appearance in the supplementary materials will be rare.


Even so, I continue taking notes and scoring the game study checklists that I use for the player profiles in each chapter. The overall grade on this checklist is what I call a Breadth of Talent Score.


The Breadth of Talent Score is an assessment of a player’s physical, mental, and technical skills that meet the baseline requirements of an NFL player at his position. The higher the score, the less fundamental work he has to do to meet the broad standards of the position’s requirements.


The Breadth of Talent Score has a “Yes/No” grade. The score does not indicate how well the player performs the criteria on the checklist. This is where the Skill Breakdown comes into play (see the next section for more information).


I place each player in tiers for each category of the Skill Breakdown report. All tiers are defined in a manner to differentiate levels of skill. I also note the ease and/or difficulty required to improve each facet of that player’s game. This exercise gives me insight into whether the player’s current depth of skill is at, above, or below the acceptable NFL baseline.


Each tier has a weight number and the sum of these tiers is the Depth of Talent Score. This grade is a reflection of how good that player is—and with a conservative, short-term projection of reasonable development—can become.


A player with a high Breadth of Talent Score is versatile in the sense that he performs a broad enough range of tasks at a fundamentally-sound level to appeal to a wide range of ways that teams define the position. A player with a high Depth of Talent Score at least does a subset of things at a high enough level that with the right team fit, he can become an asset. Rankings are based on Depth of Talent, because I’d prefer the idea that teams understand themselves enough to pick players capable of fitting into their scheme. This is not always the case, though, and, throughout the history of the league, there are glaring errors in judgment where the team overestimated the player’s breadth of talent because they admired his depth of talent in a specific subset of areas.


It’s difficult to assess how well a prospect will handle the transition to a professional environment without a formal interview, visit, and background investigation. In addition to the differences in competition, scrutiny, and pressure, the level of football strategy also jumps a notch and these players have a lot to learn.


Some players view this transition to the NFL as an opportunity to have fewer distractions from their development plan. Others find even more opportunities for distraction now that they are free from the constraints of the hourly schedule that universities impose on them.


Then there’s the unofficial mental disorder of fame, which can wreak havoc on an individual’s sense of self, his accountability, his routine, and his expectations of others. Many of these players mature through this transition as professionals with a craftsman’s approach to development, but others get swept away in a fast, outsized lifestyle and don’t figure out their responsibilities until its too late. And a few walk to the edge of the cliff, look Career Death in the eye, and turn around with enough time to make the most of their opportunity. Even the NFL hasn’t figured it out.


The Difference Between Pre-Draft And Post-Draft Rankings


In most cases, I prefer the pre-draft rankings. They may lack the context of the NFL Draft, but they are the most pure assessment of talent I provide.


A player I rank in my top-12 at a position can go undrafted, earn limited reps at the rear of the depth chart, get cut, and bounce around the league for two years before he lands on a team that recognizes his talent and gives him a real shot. The players I just described were Lions running back Joique Bell and the Chiefs’ Spencer Ware.


The Pre-Draft RSP rankings do not account for character or projected round. Ware fell in the draft due to character concerns, but this did not change his talent ranking in the RSP. The NFL Draft is as much an exercise of risk management and investing as it is a talent assessment.


The pre-draft rankings are free of those biases and makes this publication a worthwhile reference in future seasons. Players don’t figure it all out on the same timeline and they often find new homes, better scheme fits, and gain maturity on the second or third team they join.

As much as I favor the pre-draft process, post-draft rankings provide the clearest picture of the way teams see these players and the immediate opportunities they will earn. The post-draft rankings will account for the largest percentage of prospects and how their careers will play out.


However, the pre-draft rankings provide a safety net when the NFL over- or underestimates talent and fit. Not only does this happen more than you’d think, but it also gives the reader opportunity to capitalize on these exceptional cases.


Conventionality may prevent colossal failure, but exceptionality is the key to massive success. The rankings and information in each publication are designed to account for both dynamics as they unfold in football.


2019 RSP Skill Breakdowns and Stack Rankings for Wide Receivers


The Rookie Scouting Portfolio checklists are designed to assess whether a player possesses a baseline physical skill or technique as defined in the glossary of the publication. What it does not do is differentiate how much or little of that technique each player has. Paul Richardson and Dede Westbrook can both catch the ball, but the checklist “yes/no” doesn’t capture the degree of ability.


The skill breakdown reports are an avenue to explore these comparisons. The defining criteria for these breakdowns are in the glossary.


Improvement Spectrum or “Ease of Fix” for Wide Receiver Skill Sets

I include my thoughts on a player’s potential to improve his skills within each category. It’s important to remember that athletes often enter their prime in their mid-to-late twenties, which is attributable to a combination of increased physical, technical, and conceptual skill.

“Ease of Fix”

The style of type that I used for each name in these categories indicates a prospect’s potential to improve within these skill sets:


  • Normal Type: Little to no change projected as this player transitions to the NFL.

  • Easy Fix: These skills can improve with at least moderate ease if the player makes the effort.

  • Hard Fix: These skills typically take great effort to address, if possible to address at all.

  • Bad Habits: These players have bad habits they need to unlearn—a difficult transition, at best.

  • Underrated/High Ceiling: Aspect of player’s game with high-end potential with room to improve.

    For additional information on the details, refer to the glossary.


    Skill Category Subheadings

    The subheadings under each skill should be reasonably self-explanatory, but here’s a quick break-down:


  • Star Caliber: Rivals the best in the game at his position.

  • Starter Caliber: Commensurate with a full-time starter at his position.

  • Committee Caliber: A baseline level of skill for a player to contribute productively in an offense.

  • Reserve Caliber: Lacking something to consistently be productive, but good enough to contribute.

  • Free Agent: Lacking the minimum skill to make a team if evaluated strictly by this single component.

  • Deficient: Skill set is so lacking that it must improve to earn consideration if judging strictly by this component.


    Weighted values are located at the bottom of each tier. Bonus points are 10 percent of the highest possible score. For example, if the highest possible weighted score for Separation is 9 points, the bonus allotment is 0.9 points. If a player’s performance in the separation category falls under “Reserve Caliber” he earns 3.6 points from the tier. If the player is noted as both an “easy fix” and “underrated-can improve,” the player will earn 1.8 bonus points.


    Keep in mind that players can earn a Star-Caliber rating and still have flaws that they can address.


    Note: I did not see enough of Tyron Johnson’s game to get a great feel for his skills. However, I am listing what I have thus far. I will study more of his game before releasing the RSP Post-Draft.


    Separation


    The key component to getting open against tight coverage is the receiver creating space between himself and the defender. The concept of separation from the defender in college football differs considerably from that in the NFL. The saying “If you’re even, you’re leavin’,” describes the fact that successful plays are executed in tight spaces in the pros.


    If an NFL receiver has more than a step on his coverage, this is considered a grand opportunity for the quarterback to complete a pass for a big play, if not a score. Creating separation involves speed, quickness, physical play, and savvy. Hall of Fame receiver Steve Largent had the speed of a receiver that belonged on the bench, but he was a master at gaining separation on any kind of route—short, intermediate, or long—and this made him difficult for defenses to stop.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

    Note: Every player is listed as an “easy fix.” Their speed and acceleration may not improve significantly enough to jump multiple tiers but if a receiver earns a roster spot, he will have the time and resources to improve his technical prowess in this area.


    (Separation) The Best: The conventional methods of earning separation involve a combination of speed and acceleration and to a lesser extent, change of direction quickness and strength. D.K. Metcalf and Marquise Brown are among the largest and smallest receivers in this class. Both have deficiencies that normally wouldn’t earn a receiver a top-tier rating in this category. However, players with exceptional skills are often exceptional cases.


    Metcalf’s acceleration and change of direction quickness is below average, but he has exceptional strength. He’s difficult to move off course and, when he performs release maneuvers with his hands, his work is the most sudden and violent of this class.


    Brown is 25-40 pounds lighter than most cornerbacks he’ll face, and he lacks a strong library of maneuvers with his hands. His speed and quickness are enough of a threat, though, that opponents rarely play him tight at the line of scrimmage.

    When they do, his footwork and change of direction quickness make it difficult for opponents to get a hand on him. He also plays enough in the slot that he won’t see a significant amount of press coverage.


    Because of their deficiencies, there is a heightened boom-bust element to their ability to separate against cornerbacks with the NFL’s level of speed and physicality. However, it’s not enough of a concern to limit recognition that they deserve.


    Miles Boykin and Hakeem Butler are among the best all-around performers in this area. Both possess great size, long speed, excellent short-area quickness, and a variety of moves off the line of scrimmage.


    (Separation) Monitor: N’Keal Harry must develop a wider range of maneuvers and prove that his acceleration will be good enough to get on top of man-to-man coverage. Harry is fast enough to maintain separation but his ability to win early will determine if he’s a big slot receiver for most of his career or a true perimeter threat.


    Deebo Samuel has excellent footwork and strong speed and quickness. He also lacks the range of hand usage that would place him in the Starter Tier. As with Brown, Samuel might prove quick enough that he may not need a lot of handiwork, but it’s less likely because he’ll spend more time outside and he’s not as sudden as Brown. Samuel also proved more adept than his peers at the Senior Bowl when handling press coverage during practice. If his maneuvers translate to the field, he’ll enjoy early success.


    Tyre Brady makes excellent plays downfield against tight coverage. He added muscle to his frame this offseason to prepare for more physical coverage. Did the addition weight cost him speed or was he always slow? Does he have the acceleration to comnpensate?


    (Separation) Needs Improvement: DaMarkus Lodge wins the ball in the vertical and deep game. However, his timing with his hands at the line of scrimmage must improve or he’ll have nothing to compensate for his lack of acceleration and change of direction speed. Jalen Hurd has the athletic ability but must learn the release maneuvers. When he does, he’ll be one step closer to becoming a starting NFL receiver.


    (Separation) Concerns: Jaylen Smith is a big and fast receiver, but he doesn’t play with the violence of Metcalf and he has a similar lack of acceleration and change of direction skill. However, Smith’s deficiencies show up on the field. Tony Pollard has speed and quickness, but he didn’t perform in an offense where he had to face tight coverage at the line. He must prove he has the skills to get the job done.

    Routes


    If the concept of gaining separation is about how to run and turn in order to get open, route running is more about the awareness of where and when to run and turn. Running effective pass patterns takes precision and timing. It also takes awareness of how the defense and offense are reacting to each other before the snap.


    A great route runner with great awareness (Steve Largent, Jerry Rice, Cris Carter, and Larry Fitzgerald) can have a very long career at the receiver position, because he relies on speed less than his peers to get the job done.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

    (Routes) The Best: Butler is gifted with height, quickness, and mobility. He can drop his weight into hard breaks with the mobility of a slot receiver and a properly run whip route requires excellent mobility to drop and flip the hips.


    Although the likes of Travis Kelce can execute the whip route well, it’s a sign of his elite athletic ability because the route is a staple of small slot receivers. Butler has the athletic ability and route acumen to play outside and in the slot. Against Iowa, Butler ran this route well enough to force his coverage to commit a defensive pass interference foul in order to prevent the receiver from earning the catch with a clean lane up the sideline for a long score.


    Marquise Brown doesn’t run the cleanest routes, but his change of direction is so quick and sharp that he generates separation in ways most receivers cannot.


    Much is made about D.K. Metcalf’s NFL Combine performance, but Boykin’s overall workout was far more impressive. Just as Metcalf’s subpar performances in drills show up on the field with specific routes and coverage situations, Boykin’s explosive athletic ability shows up in his drills and his routes during games. If he played with an elite college quarterback, Boykin’s production would have been even greater.


    (Routes) Needs Improvement: Jakobi Meyers, Parris Campbell, Tyre Brady, and Emmanuel Butler need to expand their route trees. DaMarkus Lodge will need to improve the sharpness and flatness of his breaks to earn separation against NFL defenders.


    (Routes) Concerns: Reggie White, Jr. and Jazz Ferguson impress with size and ability to win above the rim. Both must develop greater quickness and sharpness with every phase of route running.


    Receiving


    There are many skills to lump under the category of receiving. For the sake of establishing clear criteria, the checklist format considers:


    • The act of catching the football.

    • The adjustments a player makes with the ball in the air.

    • How consistently the player makes a reception given their immediate environment.


      Wide receivers and tight ends generally run more intricate routes and encounter more complex coverage than runners, so their checklists split out routes from receiving skills. Runners, on the other hand, simply have a more generic route-running category grouped with their overall skill as a receiver.


      Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

      Trevon Brown





      26 20.8 15.6 10.4 5.2 0


      (Receiving) The Best: This class has a strong collection of receivers with great hand-eye coordination, athletic ability and toughness to win the football productively and consistently. Ideally, we want receivers to have equal parts production and consistency. However, some of the best in the game thrive on higher volumes with slightly lower consistency.


      Metcalf and Hakeem Butler are known for their athletic gifts and their higher-than-average drop rates. In the world of evaluation, all drops aren’t equal.


      The more benign type is focus-related—when a receiver becomes preoccupied with his next task before finishing the first. Most of Butler’s drops are focus issues where he’s diverted his attention upfield before he’s completely secured the football. Chad Johnson, Brandon Marshall, and Terrell Owens were great examples of top NFL receivers who had high rates of focus- related drops.


      Most of Metcalf’s drops are focus-related, but he also has a significant number of technique issues. This cause of dropped passes is fixable but requires more intensive practice so he’s reacting to the trajectory of the target with the optimal technique. You’ll see plays on Metcalf’s tape where he’s dropping fade routes and other tight-coverage targets because he wasn’t using the best hands position to attack and secure the ball.

      Despite these issues, both Metcalf and Butler have excellent hands, skill to win the ball against contact, and the coordination, range, and athletic ability to make some of the most difficult adjustments to targets in this class.


      Boykin, Lil’ Jordan Humphrey, Reggie White, Jr., and A.J. Brown also make athletic and creative adjustments to the football and can do so in tight, physical quarters. Tyre Brady makes some of the most difficult tight-quarter catches you’ll see, but there are legitimate questions about his technique that may limit his potential to do so in the NFL. His size and speed doesn’t inspire the confidence to target him in tight-coverage situations as it does for those already mentioned.


      This is probably true of Felton Davis III, who makes J.J. Arcega-Whiteside’s skill for boxing out and rebounding appear semi-pro quality by comparison, but he lacks Arcega-Whiteside’s frame. Davis is a ball magnet when healthy. Hopefully his treatment for a torn Achilles’ tendon will be as successful as Michael Crabtree’s.


      The most impressive pass catcher in terms of productivity, consistency, and creativity might be N’Keal Harry. He has the size to inspire trust in 50-50 targets and the tracking, body control, and hand-eye coordination to make catches that Davis, Butler, and Metcalf make but with greater efficiency.


      (Receiving) Needs Improvement: Arcega-Whiteside is known for having the good hands required of the box-out game that has become a specialty of his overall work. He has had some issues catching the football with his palms rather than his fingertips.


      This creates scenarios where the ball ricochets more violently in his hands because he’s not stopping the spin as efficiently as he would if he used his fingertips and their 7-10 points of surgical precision to brake the ball’s motion. Arcega-Whiteside made improvements in this area between 2017 and 2018 but it will be an issue he’ll constantly have to practice since it wasn’t a technique he learned early in his career and it isn’t as ingrained in his muscle memory


      Lodge has some minor hand position issues, but another potential concern is confidence. There are games where once he drops a target, he drops another, and gets into a minor slump that will cost him in the NFL.


      Dillon Mitchell should be a much better player than he is. While capable of big plays, he drops a lot of passes and NFL.com’s Lance Zierlien has spoken with a scout who has learned that Dillon hasn’t worked on this issue on his own time in the way most college stars of note do when faced with a glaring issue.


      Penny Hart is an exciting slot receiver with potential to be more versatile. For that to happen, he must get better at catching targets over his head and limit his focus drops. He’s a short receiver and if a quarterback doesn’t feel comfortable about a shorter receiver being able to go up and get the ball, it will limit his opportunities.


      Terry McLaurin doesn’t apply the correct technique for the trajectory of the target and it limits his viability as a target against tight coverage. The same is true of David Sills V, who has excellent tracking of the football but his reliance on bucket-catching in tight quarters may cost him in the NFL against more skilled coverage than he faced at West Virginia.


      Elusiveness


      An elusive runner avoids contact. If a runner has sufficient agility to change direction and drive the opposing defender off balance or avoid a direct hit, he possesses an adequate amount of elusiveness to his running style. There are several techniques ball carriers use to avoid hits. Some runners have all the techniques in their arsenal and can keep defenders off- balance with an endless variety of moves, while others may only have a few effective moves in certain situations.


      Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

      5 4 3 2 1 0


      (Elusiveness) The Best: Marquise Brown has great change-of-direction quickness and uses it as a weapon to attack defenders at the line of scrimmage, in his routes, and in the open field. Renfrow isn’t as explosive, but he’s precise with his feet and quick enough that you’d probably win money in Vegas taking the over on the percentage of catches in a game where he’d make the first man miss.


      In the open field, Mitchell comes to a stop and reaccelerates as well as anyone in this class. If he caught the ball as well as he moved, the Odell Beckham, Jr. comparison would be on the mark.


      Boykin looks like a young Terrell Owens. He runs with quickness, power, and speed. His cuts may not be as dynamic in range as the slot receivers on this list, but they are sharp enough at a high speed to turn potentially direct collisions into glancing blows.


      Hart’s suddenness and precisions puts opponents on their heels. Although some of you will be that “What about?” guy and mention Andy Isabella, who almost deserves mentioning here, Hart is far more economical and downhill-oriented with his movement, and it makes him more dangerous because defenders are always on their heels.

      (Elusiveness) Needs Improvement: Olabisi Johnson has excellent workout metrics but appears as a far more plodding, linear mover on tape. It leads one to wonder if he’s thinking a lot on the field.


      Metcalf does not drop his weight well in and out of breaks and it limits his range of motion as a route runner and ball carrier. But here’s the thing: Would you ask a bull to be a butterfly? Just as there are a variety of running back archetypes based on physical dimensions, movement style, and on-field role, the same applies to receivers.


      Metcalf may never do the same things that Antonio Brown can on the field and it may limit his versatility, but ask him to reprise some of Dez Bryant’s work with some of Ted Ginn’s field-stretching thrown in and there will be a lot of good defensive backs who can’t wait for their “play amnesia” of their failures to come fast enough.


      The same applies to Jazz Ferguson—a big, fast rebounder who’s agility is good enough to make parallel cuts and side-steps of pursuit. But asking him to change direction like Antonio Brown is unrealistic. However, he must get quicker with his first step.


      (Elusiveness) Concerns: Lodge isn’t big or fast, so he must compensate with better change of direction so he’s precise. His workouts and on-field play suggest that he’s a good college player whose game won’t translate as well to Sundays.


      Johnnie Dixon has excellent speed but his acceleration and change of direction appear sluggish on the field. Dixon has dealt with arthritis and tendonitis in his knees, nearly forcing him to quit football. The extent of these health issues may determine how skilled he can actually become as a route runner and open-field runner.


      Ball Handling

      The category of ball handling incorporates a number of skills ranging from the most fundamental to the highly advanced. A superb offensive skill player not only demonstrates the ability to protect the ball while he is the target of 11 defenders in pursuit, but he also can use good technique to avoid taking a hit to the ball in the first place.


      Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

      (Ball Handling) The Best: None of the players in the starter tier stand out as practitioners of ball security. They’re in this tier because they have fewer lapses than their peers.


      (Ball Handling) Needs Improvement: All of the receivers in the committee tier have at least one of the following issues:


  • Carrying the ball too low from the chest.

  • Carrying the ball with the elbow too loose from their frame.

  • Carrying the ball to one side only, regardless of the direction of the play and the pursuit.


The receivers with their names in bold and underlined type use the correct side to carry the ball, but their carriage is either too high or too loose. Those with their names only in bold tend to carry the ball too wide or too loose and fail to use the correct side.


(Ball Handling) Concerns: When transitioning from receiver to runner, Xavier Ubosi often carries the ball like a Steelers fan waiving a Terrible Towel.


Marquise Brown uses either arm, but doesn’t switch the ball away from the pursuit angles. His elbow is also too loose and low. He’s probably confident that he can tighten his security when opponents get close but he’ll learn that pursuit in the NFL is quicker, faster, and more precise at knocking the ball out of his diminutive frame.


The same applies even more to Andy Isabella. If a runner’s movement was akin to a person’s speech, Isabella would be an intelligent man with an occasional stammering problem—he’s processing information faster than he can communicate it. His size, ball security, and occasional on-field stammering could be a combination ripe for turnovers.

Balance


Balance is a core factor in effective ball carrying, denoting the combination of good foot and body placement, agility, and awareness of one’s physical space. A player with good balance can adjust to the force of a hard blow and not fall over.


Football players are trained to maintain their balance when facing most head-on collisions with a defender, but special players have the rare ability to keep their balance when the direction of the blow or placement of the blow to the body is unexpected, whether coming from an angle or particularly forceful.


Although an extreme example, Barry Sanders frequently demonstrated throughout his career that a low pad level, uncanny anticipation of defensive angles, and great balance could defeat the backfield penetration of a player with a significant height-weight advantage. As a receiver, Herman Moore possessed great balance in and out of routes adjusting to the ball and as a ball carrier after the catch. Percy Harvin is another receiver with average size but excellent balance.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

Blocking


Skill players block for the run and pass on a limited basis, but if the play is to have a high level of success, their assignments are as important to execute as those of their teammates on the offensive line. A skill player’s attitude towards blocking can also speak a lot to the way they approach the game overall:


  • Comfort level with hitting

  • Courage

  • Teamwork

  • Understanding of technique

  • Understanding of the offense


Blocking is generally one of the key skills where top prospects need the most refinement before they make the transition from college starter to NFL starter. A good blocker sees the field much earlier than his peers with a similar level of talent in other facets of their game.


Hines Ward is a receiver that understood how his blocks could turn 15 or 20-yard runs into 50 or 60-yard touchdowns. He also searched out ways to attack the defense after he had successfully completed his first assignment on the play.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

Vision


Two of the most important factors that separate a talented runner from a talented athlete are the level of comfort he has with physical contact (his heart), and his ability to anticipate and exploit the best places to run with the football (vision). Locating the best place to run requires a runner to vary his rate of speed, set up the blocks in front of him, and move in one direction to exploit daylight in another.


Vision requires a high level of intuition, and backs or receivers with great vision and strong fundamentals as a runner exhibit a style that is akin to a great improviser in music or the spoken word—instinctive, but in control of the moment. Vision is the common denominator among great ball carriers.


Even receivers need to show the heart to split defenders rather than always attempt to run around them. Emmanuel Sanders is a great example of a player who, despite his thin frame, consistently made the right decisions as a runner after the catch at SMU.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

(Vision) The Best: Deebo Samuel justifiably earns a lot of love for his ability to weave through a defense, and he applies his skills equally well as a return specialist and receiver in open space. The same is true for Brown and Hardman, but they won’t run through reaches and wraps as well as Samuel or Parris Campbell.

(Vision) Needs Improvement: Shun Brown is one of more than a dozen receivers who must learn to turn upfield immediately rather than take a wide loop and lose yardage in an attempt to gain more.


Diontae Johnson is dangerous after the catch, but he must practice greater efficiency with his transitions from receiver to runner. He also has moments where he turns the wrong way when it appears he should have gauged the defender’s movements correctly.


Isabella is a former high school running back with great physical movement skills. As described in the Elusiveness section, his movement has an occasional “stammering” quality to it.


This is often a sign of overthinking or missing subtle key indicators that he’s generated enough open space to get down-hill. This is similar to the quarterback that waits a beat too long to throw the ball when he has identified the leverage advantage, but isn’t confident to let the ball go. Isabella can make one too many moves trying to identify that clear confirmation.


It doesn’t make his vision bad, but it impedes it from being as good as his impressive movements suggest.

Power


Simply put, power is a football player’s ability to move forward when a defender is blocking his progress. The variety of methods a player can use to address the defender and his effectiveness at gaining yards after contact determines the player’s overall score within this category.


Walter Payton’s style of play epitomized the techniques of a power runner. Payton was not a big back, but power often stems as much from aggression, leverage, and determination as it does size and momentum. Julio Jones, Dez Bryant and Mike Evans are all powerful runners as receivers.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

Durability

The category for durability is designed to measure the player’s ability to play with pain, overcome injury, and determine if he has any chronic issues that may prevent him from reaching his full potential as a pro. Some injuries are more a test of the player’s work ethic than his body’s healing capacity.


Others test both recuperative powers and character. More players slide in the draft due to injury history than most any other factor about them.


This year, there are only 10 players with durability scores below the starter tier. To save space, I’m only showing those. The rest are in the starter tier.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers.

Major Injuries


Ahmmon Richards: He retired this year due to a neck injury. I kept his name in the Skill Breakdowns, but he will not be ranked or profiled.


Felton Davis III: A tear to his Achilles’ tendon sidelined Davis earlier this year. He is scheduled to resume running in April. If he makes a team, he’ll likely spend the year on the PUP list. He was never a dynamic mover or speedster before the injury. If he can make a complete recovery, he could deliver as big-slot receiver.


Johnnie Dixon: As mentioned earlier, Dixon has dealt with arthritis and tendonitis in both knees. It kept him out of a majority of football practices for two years. This has stalled his development and he nearly quit the game. He has excellent distance speed, but his change of direction quickness and acceleration isn’t as strong. It leads one to wonder if these issues rob him these qualities and will prevent him from developing as a professional.

Marquise Brown: Lisfranc surgery for a broken foot will sideline him this offseason.


Depth of Talent Score

The RSP compiles points in these tiers and the ease of fix bonuses into a Depth of Talent Score. Here is the grading scale:


    • 100-95 (Rare): Instant All-Pro upside; takes over games and changes teams.

    • 90-94 (Franchise): Immediate production and leadership anchor.

    • 85-89 (Starter): Starting immediately with large role and learning on the go.

    • 80-84 (Rotational Starter): Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths.

    • 75-79 (Contributor): Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.

    • 70-74 (Reserve): Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.

    • 60-69 (Developmental): Special Teams, end of bench, and practice squad players.

    • 0-59 (Street): Developmental talents with deficiencies in experience, technique, and/or athletic ability.


      The grades assigned to rookies are a portrait of their games based on their college performance and—depending on the nature of their flaws—a small-to-moderate projection of improvement. The grades given to rookies are not static; they are only a starting point of the player’s development.


      If a player with a contributor grade improves in 2-3 areas during training camp, his rookie year, or his first off-season, he could emerge as a talent 2-3 levels higher on the scale.


      While the players in the lowest four tiers have the greatest volume of issues, many of problems are easy fixes. This can lead to rapid improvement. As a player’s talent climbs the grading scale, the volume of flaws declines, but the difficulty level with addressing existing flaws increases.


      The on-field impact of these gains also differs based on talent level. Players in the lower tiers will make the largest gains, but they are often less impactful than the smallest gains by a player in the highest tiers.


      The Depth of Talent Score has little or no impact on the following:


    • A prospect’s competition for a spot on the depth chart.

    • Extended opportunity to prove his value.

    • Team politics and contract-driven decisions.

    • Injuries.

    • Scheme fit.

    • Supply and demand.


Supply and demand is vital factor. The RSP may grade 25 players with no worse than contributor values, but if the league’s depth charts are filled with reserves performing at an equal or higher level—or even a lower level with the other political and fiscal factors listed above—that “decent” or “good” grade may not matter.


I will list Depth of Talent Score for each player in the Rankings Profiles as well as the cheat sheet tables at the end of the chapter.



On-Field I.Q.


I believe the best players not only exhibit impressive skills but know how to integrate these individual components into their game and make unusual physical and conceptual adjustments as if it’s second nature. There is little-to-no hesitation with their decisions and movements. I like to use the term “fluidity” to describe this behavior. Here are receivers that have exhibited a noticeably higher-than-average on-field I.Q and who possess the fluidity to become quality NFL players:

Overrated: Talent, But Expectations Are Too High


The receivers in this section are good enough to contribute immediately. However, there are skills that they need to address if they want to come close to fulfilling their potential. If they don’t address them, the deficiencies will either limit their role or prevent them from seeing the field at the start of their careers.


Andy Isabella, UMass: A former running back and track star, Isabella earned the nation’s best 60-meter mark among high schoolers with a time of 6.72 seconds. He also bested Cleveland Browns cornerback Denzel Ward in the 100 meters at the Ohio State track championship.


He earned acclaim among football fans with his strong production against a top-rated University of Georgia team, including a long pass play. Senior Bowl practice observers lavished praise on Isabella for his excellent quickness and fancy footwork in one-on-one drills against defenders.


There’s no doubt Isabella has the skills to earn a starting opportunity in the slot at some point during his career. It’s far from a guarantee that Isabella will reach that point. What impresses some about his game has an uglier underside.


Isabella must prove he can defeat press coverage in a game. This is different than the pseudo-practice environment of a college all-star game that is far more like an audition.


Training, practices, auditions, and performances are four different environments for a performer. Training is the area where a performer expects to make mistakes. Be it a story, a dance routine, learning a song, or running a route, it’s about transforming raw material into refined but not yet finished content.


Practices simulate the performance as much as possible but with a more forgiving environment to experiment with certain choices—a risqué response in dialogue during an important scene you’ve written for a play, an alternate costume choice for a dance performance, an alternate tempo for a song’s bridge, or selling the post before breaking on the out route.


Practices have a time and place for experimentation and rudimentary learning as well as a rehearsal phase where the expectations for execution are closer to the actual performance.


Auditions are often segmented mini performances of material that’s often used as much in practice sessions as on stage. Audition judges have a wide range of expectations. Some may want the feel to be as formal as a real performance, others want it more relaxed like a practice, so they can get performers to feel more open and relaxed about trying things different from their scripted audition routines.


The difference between football auditions like all-star practices, Pro Days, and the NFL Combine and auditions for theater, movies, music ensembles, or even pitches for articles and books, is that, for football, there’s a much wider audience of influencers observing and judging the process. Regardless of what coaches and scouts might tell a prospect, media analysts and other forms of public opinion carry weight and will sway general managers and ownership. Decision makers have a history of overriding sound processes with decisions rooted in people-pleasing, pride, or personal vendetta.


This segment of the audience influences how players perform during the NFL’s audition process. All-star practices aren’t like normal practices and players can be rewarded for suboptimal behavior.


A converted quarterback, Braxton Miller earned accolades for his speed, hands, and movement skills. At the Senior Bowl audition week, he wowed onlookers with impressive movement that repeatedly faked out top prospects in drills. There was a significant amount of praise given to Miller for this specific ability—a behavior that is not optimal for most NFL routes because it takes too much time and throws off the timing in a passing game.


Miller went to the NFL Combine and ran an impressive 6.65-second, 3-Cone Drill and an explosive, 4.07-second, 20-Yard Shuttle. The Texans awarded Miller with a third-round selection and a four-year $3.11 million-dollar contract with a

$709,103 signing bonus in 2016.


Three years later, Miller is on the reserve list with a futures contract in Philadelphia after the Texans waived Miller in 2018. Injuries were a factor but the greatest issue was his difficulty getting open and running NFL-caliber routes.

Isabella isn’t as big or as explosive as Miller. He too impressed onlookers with his flashy movement during the drills of Senior Bowl auditions. Yet Isabella has a similar problem to Miller: Physical play stifles him and it influences him to perform more fancy footwork to avoid physical confrontation until he spots an opening.


It worked often enough for Isabella in the college game because he’s a top athlete. Sometimes it will work in the NFL—and in dramatic, crowd-pleasing fashion. However, if that’s the only way he can do the job, it will become one-dimensional.

When a player becomes one dimensional, opponents can take that strength away without fear of the player making them pay.


Isabella uses a variety of hands techniques against press coverage, but its window dressing for his quick feet and lateral movement necessary to force a defender to a side and enable him to attack down hill. Against top defensive backs, Isabella must learn to make more efficient moves that threaten the defender with downhill movement as he’s moving side-to-side.


This was the difference between Isabella and fellow slot receiver Penny Hart at the Senior Bowl auditions. When defenders tried to attack Hart, he was already working down hill and it allowed him to overcome the attempts at rerouting him, earn separation, and win the ball.


Isabella’s movement didn’t hold up as well to physical confrontation. It took him longer to overcome and either threw off his timing or he lost focus with the ball arriving and dropped the pass. This is what will happen in the NFL if opponents discover that he’s vulnerable to physical play.


Physical play notably disrupts Isabella’s process at this point in his career. As a slot receiver, who will work the middle of the field, often without tight coverage at the line, he still could produce at a high rate because the contact may not be as prevalent until after the catch.


However, he lacks the size, presence, and positioning to win the ball against tight, physical coverage. While the success against Georgia made Isabella a notable prospect, it’s also notable that he didn’t win significant gains against physical coverage—or even good coverage at all.


There’s reason to suspect Isabella will at least initially struggle in the NFL now that there’s much greater speed, quickness, intelligence, and physicality among the average starters he’ll be facing. He may author big plays for 4-6 weeks thanks to scheming that gets him open. However, when teams decide to focus on him and figure out that he’s jammable, disruptable in routes, and easier to tackle when defenders are in front of him, that’s when we’ll learn if Isabella has true starter potential.


Mecole Hardman, Georgia: Another small, fast, slot receiver with big-play capability after the catch and in the vertical game, Hardman is also an acclaimed return specialist. His popularity is riding the wave resulting from Tyreek Hill’s impact and the subsequent allure of Marquise Brown, Isabella, and others. Hill and Brown are vastly different players, but big-play speed and open-field ability have always gotten NFL evaluators to compulsively suck their thumbs over prospects.


Hardman has 4.3-speed and excelled as a slot receiver, space weapon, return specialist, and coverage player for the Bulldogs. Go to YouTube or watch national television when he’s drafted and you’ll see videos of him weaving around defenders and catching deep seam passes—often high-pointing the ball with a defender hanging off him. Watch these feats during cardio day at the gym or the rim’s-eye-view of a beer mug, and Hardman might look like a young Hill or Steve Smith to you.


He might get there but there’s a lot he doesn’t do well yet. It’s too much to presume that he’ll work at the game hard enough and absorb new skills fast enough to match Hill or Smith.


His route tree is limited, he has little experience facing press coverage, and even his work at the catch point is more limited than a first look may indicate. Hardman wins the ball when he can get a clean angle on a designed play with scripted adjustment to the target. Think of a back-shoulder fade or an underthrown deep ball where he can box out the defender, leap into the air with a square position to the oncoming target, and then turn away.


These are clean looks and he’ll succeed in these situations as long as he extends his arms fully to the ball. Where he falters is winning the ball in dirtier situations where opponents earn better position or disrupt Hardman’s position to the ball. He has difficulty making non-scripted adjustments to the football and this is the difference between him being an undersized receiver with speed and a true matchup nightmare.


Well, that and learning a more complete route tree and developing an extensive repertoire of press-release movements. With the right fit, he will not need any of these developed skills to become a significant weapon. Since the RSP evaluates 8- 10 times more receivers than the average NFL team, it’s operating on the possibility a player won’t automatically earn an

ideal scheme fit. Because of that perspective, Hardman is an exciting player who needs a specific fit to immediately deliver anything more than reserve and special teams production.


D.K. Metcalf, Mississippi: Seeking a big-play outside threat who will win on go routes, posts, screens, hitches, crossing routes, and the occasional slant? Metcalf is your man.


He’s capable of fantastic plays at the catch point and he’ll run by—or through opponents—with his impressive combination of size and speed. Include his 40.5-inch vertical and 27 reps on the bench press with his 4.33-second, 40-Yard Dash and there’s talk that he’s next Josh Gordon or Calvin Johnson.


On the field, Metcalf and Johnson can win deep and run away from defenders in open space when there’s a straight-line of turf ahead, break tackles, and rebound the hell out of the ball. That’s four really valuable traits.


However, that’s where the basis for comparison ends. Johnson could drop his weight in and out of breaks with the speed of a 190-pound slot receiver. He could run the entire route tree and his transitions between catching the ball and running were tight-angled turns that got him immediately downfield. He could also make dynamic cuts.


Metcalf doesn’t do these things well. He’s not his uncle Eric, who starred for the Browns and Falcons as a more fleet-footed and less powerful Alvin Kamara before Kamara was born. Metcalf is a rebounder with speed. Yes, he slipped during drills. Yes, slips are an indication of subpar mobility during these exercises—especially when they match the film of a route runner who works a limited route tree designed to maximize his straight-line excellence.


A better functional comparison—if you’re going to try a 1:1 comparison when most performers are an amalgamation of a variety of influences—might be Josh Gordon, if only looking at his routes in Cleveland and New England. He wasn’t asked to run routes with a lot of bend because they wanted to leverage the same skills we’ve seen from Metcalf.


However, Gordon could bend and change direction better than Metcalf. His playing history was so spotty, and his team was in such turmoil that he performed routes that were easiest for him and his new quarterback of the month to acclimate.

Gordon belongs in the comparison conversation, but only as one of several influences that only partially fit Metcalf’s game.


Demaryius Thomas – before Peyton Manning – also fits. He was a rebounder and speedster who won with straight-line skills—go routes, posts, fades, crossers, screens, and end-arounds. Another reasonable comparison is a big-and-tall-version of Dez Bryant with more speed and less dynamic change of direction skills.


The problem with comparing Metcalf directly to any of these players is that it inflates expectations of what he’s likely to do on the field. He’s a big-play receiver who scared college defenses into playing off him because, on the 1-3 occasions during a game where a corner playing man-to-man failed, Metcalf would earn a field-flipping play.


However, Alabama wasn’t afraid. Its corners failed at times in a big way—including a long score to Metcalf in the opening quarter—but the Crimson Tide won that game 62-7 and Metcalf earned 2 catches for 92 yards. LSU also played a lot of press coverage against Metcalf and he wasn’t productive in the game.


Arkansas beat Ole Miss 38-37 in 2017 and Metcalf earned 107 yards on 4 catches—mostly targets that were unchallenged. However, a guest poster on Gang Green Nation shows selected targets where Metcalf earned physical coverage and struggled, including one from Henre' Tolliver, a UDFA signed by the Colts now playing in the AAF. He has salient points about Metcalf against tight coverage even if he also explains that he expects Metcalf to be an excellent pro receiver.


Metcalf has the violent releases to defeat press and he can make physical cornerbacks pay dearly and often enough that he still earns a top tier in the separation category. However, counting on him to be used all over the field and earn 100-plus receptions is not a realistic expectation of his skills. It’s a subtle distinction for a player deserving of top-prospect status but a necessary one for those on the verge of overpaying for his services because they’re thinking of Calvin Johnson.

Underrated WR Prospects


Stanley Morgan, Jr., Nebraska: Lost in the hoopla of the athletic wunderkinds returning to the top tiers of this position after a five-year drought, is Morgan, an average-sized receiver who is likely characterized as “just a guy,” from a program that has been the antithesis of “Wide Receiver U.”


There isn’t as much program bias these days in scouting circles but if there’s one that may still linger, Nebraska as a desert for wide receiver play would be it. If we’re going to judge Nebraska’s receivers on the basis of consistent starter production in the NFL, the only name that earns a mention is Irving Fryar, whom the New England Patriots selected No.1 overall in 1984.


Fryar worked alongside a veteran receiver who would play 14 years in the league and earn 557 receptions, 10,716 yards, and 72 touchdowns in an era where passing was the equivalent of your grandparent walking to school barefoot and uphill both ways in a blinding snowstorm that didn’t end until they earned their high school diplomas. That receiver was Stanley Morgan—no relation to Stanley Morgan, Jr., but it’s an odd connection between Morgan, Jr. and the best receiver Nebraska’s football team fielded.


Morgan is a high-effort player with excellent quickness, promising routes, and consistent hands techniques. He is underrated open-field player with and without the ball in his hands. Morgan also stops fast. The ability to decelerate is of paramount importance to route running and Morgan does this as well as anyone in the class.


In my notes, I wrote that Morgan may stop faster than he runs. Morgan runs a 4.5-second, 40-Yard Dash, which is more than fast enough for a receiver with possession-plus skills. He also ran a 4.13-second, 20-Shuttle and 6.78-second, 3-Cone.


Deebo Samuel is only .05 seconds faster in the 40. Morgan topped Samuel in acceleration and change-of-direction metrics. Only Miles Boykin (barely) and Monmouth’s Reggie White, Jr. (again, no relation to who you’re thinking) had better performances in these two critical metrics of receiver movement.


This quickness and acceleration shows up in his routes and after the catch. Any route that features a stick with the front leg is in his wheelhouse and he’s a difficult player to cover on timing routes man-to-man. His fakes are violent and at the last possible moment before his breaks. He’s also skilled at stretching windows in zone coverage for his quarterback to find him.


Morgan is a boundary-aware and zone-aware route runner who takes and dishes out physical play at the catch point and as a runner and blocker. He takes hard hits and maintains possession of the ball and when he can make defenders miss in the open field—which he does often—he will run through wraps.


If Nebraska receivers are known for anything it is blocking, and Morgan doesn’t disappoint. His technique is consistently strong, and he excels at sustaining his hand position into an opponent—often getting under the skin of defensive backs that aren’t used to dealing with sustained physical play from a receiver.


Another affectionate term for a football player who loves the game and practices this way is a ‘dog.’ A 2018 article about the Washington receiving corps compared the attitudes of Josh Doctson and RSP favorite Paul Richardson. Players referred to Richardson as a dog who was all about football.


Morgan’s own mother has long referred to his son as a dog on the field.


Morgan reminds me of old-school AFC Central receivers like Hines Ward and Keenan McCardell—faster than you think, versatile play makers, and tough for days. I’m surprised he isn’t earning more attention but if I’m right, that day will come.


Jalen Hurd, Baylor: When I studied Hurd three years ago as a running back prospect at Tennessee, he was a 240-pound player with a gliding gait and the power to pull a pile behind him. He tripped over his feet a lot and lacked the caliber of footwork of a top-tier running back prospect. He was only a sophomore and there was still plenty of time for him to improve.


Two years later, I studied Hurd at Baylor. He’s still a big guy but notably lighter. When he runs routes from the slot or occasionally outside, he looks nothing like a former five-star running back. Watch Hurd drop his weight into hard breaks and execute smooth turns and speed breaks and you’d think he’s been playing the position since high school.

Despite resistance from Tennessee’s coaching staff for requesting a position change (and they had John Kelly and towards the end, Alvin Kamara) and later, a public spat between the Tennessee coaching staff and Hurd about Hurd’s commitment as a teammate. Hurd remained focused on the task of becoming a viable NFL receiver prospect and has achieved his goal.


Hurd is a big-bodied option who can win deep, earn the ball against tight coverage, and gain yards in the open field. He’s still learning the subtleties of playing the position, and it may take him a couple of years to master the differences with routes on the perimeter and life as a big slot receiver. He’s already shown the ability to learn fast and transfer his lessons to the field as if he’s been playing the position for a much longer period of time.


The irony of Hurd’s transition is that all of the practice with footwork to become a skilled route runner has made Hurd a more technically-skilled running back. Baylor used Hurd in the backfield in a variety of situations last year and his ability to cut and set up creases is much cleaner than when he was a full-time ball carrier.


Hurd runs with better balance and executes with greater control against unplanned obstacles. A smart NFL team will prize Hurd’s versatility and value his growth potential. He might be regarded as a project in some circles, but only in terms of how little experience he has playing the position. His quality of work makes him a viable contributor right away with the right fit.


Emmanuel Butler, Northern Arizona: There are a lot of receivers in this class with sticky mitts and a wide catch radius. Butler is among my faves. He’s a strong, tough receiver with the mentality that bracket coverage means there are now two defenders in his area who are not good enough to take the ball away from him.


Although he attended a small school that didn’t face top competition on a weekly basis, Butler had moments of excellence against PAC 12 programs. In addition to posting up defensive backs in the end zone and on deep fade routes, Butler displays excellent ball tracking with his back to the target and skill after the catch on quick-hitting routes where he can run at the opposition and make them miss with quick dips and cuts while pulling through reaches and wraps.


The greatest concern I had about Butler was his athletic ability relative to top competition. But his 4.22-second, 20-Shuttle and 36-inch vertical at the NFL Combine are a strong indication that what you see on film is what you get on the field.


He’ll likely have a long road to earning a roster spot. He may have to accept a UDFA contract or tryout and maybe endure a stint or two with other teams because he lacks draft capital. However, he’s arguably the most underrated player in this rich class.


Cody Thompson, Toledo: A special team’s ace who can block and cover punts as well as return them in a pinch. Thompson is a skilled receiver with the ball skills and shiftiness of former Titans’ receiver Damien Williams but a little more explosive. His skills lie somewhere between Williams and Julian Edelman who was just a little quicker at the start of his career.


Thompson wins the ball in the air, makes the first man miss, and runs with strong pad level. He suffered a broken leg during his career and there are concerns that he isn’t playing on the leg with the same athletic ability that he did prior to the injury.


His play was inconsistent. His tape shows tough, big-play NFL receptions and then intermittent games with multiple drops. Some routes against press appear refined and NFL-quick. Others appear tentative and lacking a great plan.


I’m banking on Thompson developing into a contributor. If he can continue working at his craft and building on his athletic baseline, he has the foundation to develop into a starting slot receiver who can also earn time on the perimeter and get open 25-35 yards downfield as a vertical threat.


At the very worst, he’ll latch on immediately as a special team’s performer and work his way up.

WR Projects


A “Project” isn’t necessarily a raw athlete.
