He could be a player with advanced skills but lacks the extensive playing time to gain experience, address his subsequent performance issues in practice, and put it all together as he accumulates those experiences. Practice creates great skills; game experience creates great players.


Not As Far Away As It Appears…


Reggie White, Jr., Monmouth: LockedOn Browns podcast host Jeff Lloyd told me about White—no relation to the Hall of Fame defensive end—in October. If it weren’t for the fact that Monmouth doesn’t face the caliber of athletes as consistently as bigger programs, he’d qualify more as a sleeper.


The first thing that jumps off the page with White is his fantastic tracking and catch radius. He makes plays on the ball that translate to any level of play. He wins with extreme adjustments to the ball that often appear effortless.


He’s skilled at vertical routes, and is especially successful at manipulating defenders with his stems. He can also run flat speed breaks and drop his weight into sudden hard breaks.


After the catch, White has sudden dips and cuts, and he can perform them in sequence as well as flip his hips for sharp pivots to open space.


White had a fantastic pro day: a 4.45-second, 40-Yard Dash; a 4.07-second, 20-Shuttle; a 6.77-second 3-Cone; and a 37.5-inch vertical. With the exception of the Starter Tier vertical, the rest are Star Tier performances.


According to a source I cannot divulge, there were four scouts from an NFC team in attendance. One of them—a respected veteran with over three decades of experience—says White might be the best prospect Monmouth has ever had.


Miles Austin is a Monmouth alum. If I felt more confident about White’s route running translating quickly to the NFL game, he’d be a top-12 receiver on the RSP’s board. However, the intricacies of route running are a game within a game that requires a lot of subtle adjustments and tweaking for a higher level of competition.


White also has to expand and refine his release skills. White reminds me of another 6-2, 200-ish-pound receiver with similar speed, acceleration, and change-of-direction quickness and vacuum hands—RSP favorite Marvin Jones. White is a better leaper but, Jones had more refined route skills as a collegian. Jones might also have more dog in him in the open field.


Still, it’s a favorable comparison and White is a player to know about.


Dillon Mitchell, Oregon: Here’s a player who needs to practice using his hands. Mitchell often uses them with the highest degree of skill during the game. However, he drops a lot of passes and his drops include all three of the main types: Focus issues, tracking issues, and technique issues.


Mitchell has targets where he attempts to clap his hands to the ball. His focus is also easily diverted by tight coverage or the prospect of turning upfield and using his excellent skills as a runner. He also has intermittent issues with adequately tracking the ball over his shoulder. He fails to extend his arms correctly on some of these throws.


Mitchell has tremendous skills in the open field and he has starter potential as a route runner. If he’ll work at his craft (see the Receiving tier in the Skills Category section of this chapter), he has the talent of an NFL starter. If he doesn’t, he’ll be a frustrating tease of a prospect.


Travis Fulgham, Old Dominion: Another prospect whose game is lost among the behemoth receivers roaming the 2019 draft landscape, Fulgham has a game reminiscent of Michael Crabtree. His dimensions, quicker-than-fast athletic ability, and skill at the catch-point with the ball in the air all strongly resemble Crabtree in his prime. And when Fulgham latches onto a defender as a blocker, he won’t let go until he’s planted that man on the hood of a car parked outside the stadium (or until the whistle blows, whichever happens first…).


He’s a big enough player to get physical with professional defensive backs. He has to learn to do so at the line of scrimmage against press coverage. If he can become as skilled with press coverage as he is blocking and refines his footwork heading into breaks, he could develop into a starter.

Juwann Winfree, Colorado: Another quicker-than-fast receiver, Winfree has good route skills that are getting better. He has become a student of his position and he is on his way to developing pro-level skills with releases and timing routes.


Although his 4.26-second, 20-Shuttle and 6.97-second 3-Cone Drill are an impressive combo highlighting his athletic ability, he also ran a 4.5-second 40-Yard Dash. Match it up with his tape and he can win most everywhere on the field.


His hands are also impressive. He has excellent hand-eye coordination, a wide catch radius, and he makes creative and difficult adjustments to the football. He has no problem handling contact, either.


He’s virtually invisible in terms of public knowledge of his game and it’s likely that he’ll be competing for a practice squad spot as a UDFA. Among players with this lack of draft capital, Winfree is one I’ll be monitoring closely.


Longer Path, But Could Be Worth the Journey


Shawn Poindexter, Arizona: A tall receiver with downfield ability and budding skill with timing routes, Poindexter needs to get stronger and technically more refined against tight coverage. He attacks the ball really well with strong technique. He should contend for a roster spot even if he’s not drafted.


Jamal Custis, Syracuse and Xavier Ubosi, UAB: Custis is two inches taller than the the 6’2” Ubosi but both are well-built receivers in the range of 215 pounds who can win the ball down field. Custis has moments of excellence as a pass catcher book-ended by inconsistent hands work. Ubosi must learn more routes. Both have the athletic ability and flashes of budding skill to become productive contributors one day.


Why Rankings Suck (And We All Want Them Anyway…)


I hate rankings. It’s a faulty categorization of talent. Every position in football has subcategories. Wide receivers and running backs have different roles based on the offensive system or their skill sets.


LeGarrette Blount’s role is much different from Darren Sproles’. DeSean Jackson is a vastly different receiver than Brandon Marshall. Russell Wilson might perform well in New England’s offense, but would you ask Tom Brady to run zone-read and scramble in Seattle? Is Brady a worse quarterback than Wilson because Wilson would fare well in a variety of systems because of his athletic ability?


You can have fun debating the question, but the point is that all the players mentioned above have value, and a linear ranking isn’t an accurate portrayal of their value. I prefer tiers because in most cases, there are groups of players that are so close in skill that a tier comes closer to recognizing talent value.


It shouldn’t matter to you whether Mitchell Trubisky, Patrick Mahomes and Deshaun Watson are Nos. 1, 2, and 3 on an analyst’s board, it’s more important to know if they’re all within the same tier.


Three years from now, you may argue that Trubisky significantly out-performed the other two, but organizational fit, system fit, health, and surrounding talent are just four of several variables that don’t make a one-to-one comparison of a player an accurate way of viewing talent. Nevertheless, I understand the desire for a linear order.


The rankings in each chapter of the Rookie Scouting Portfolio publication will also have headings that note the beginning of tiers where I would group these players. It satisfies my desire to dissuade readers from overreacting to a linear number (Why do you have [insert player’s name here] soooo lowwwww...) while giving you, the fantasy owner and draftnik, a beginning range to shift your boards around based on your teams’ needs and fit.



Scheme-Based Talents


Reader demand drives the inclusion of list-style rankings in the RSP. However, list-style rankings don’t provide the nuance that readers should have about the talent and fit (see above). Because the running back, tight end, and receiver positions have prospects with a wide variety of physical dimensions, athletic talents, and skill sets, even a scoring system with all the criteria of the RSP still has to prioritize which talents and skill sets are most important. In other words, every scoring system implicitly defines its standard of what’s ideal and grades every player to it.


Grading to a standard that awards prospects like Marshawn Lynch, Adrian Peterson, A.J. Green, Julio Jones and Rob Gronkowski top value is excellent when looking for the best all-around talents, and I will never stop doing so. Yet, list-style rankings make it harder for some readers to recognize the value of players I’ve assigned a lower number on the list, but I appreciate what is possible for them with a strong match of player to system.


This section will rank players who may not have the upside of a traditional every-down receiver but could become as productive as many workhorses with the right fit, even as role players. In fact, they have enough upside to produce like fantasy starters even if their skills aren’t as well rounded as the players that the RSP ranks above them.


Some of the players placed at the top of this fit-based section are ahead of higher-ranked players on the overall pre-draft list. That’s because a narrower range of skills are considered here.


Because a good fit can maximize a player’s talents while limiting on-field exposure to his weaknesses, the right pairing in May could elevate the post-draft rankings of several players, even if their pre-draft talent grades aren’t as well rounded as others.


Small Slot


Shorter receivers between 180-205 pounds are the usual dimensional range of the small slot receiver. Wes Welker and Jarvis Landry are both recent examples of the prototypes. The 5’9”, 186-pound Welker had significantly better acceleration and change of direction, but his long speed was a little slower than the 5’11”, 205-pound Landry.


  1. Marquise Brown, Oklahoma: Although characterized as a deep-route specialist who will be more Ted Ginn and DeSean Jackson than a slot specialist, I’m not convinced that’s all he offers. Brown’s light frame will be a concern in the middle of the field, but he displays a knack for finding open holes in these zones and making plays in traffic.

  2. Hunter Renfrow, Clemson: The classic small slot receiver and probably the best bet on this list to earn a high- volume opportunity in the footsteps of Wes Welker, Danny Amendola, Davone Bess, and Jarvis Landry. Renfrow has a fantastic feel for underneath coverage, and he’s a chore to cover within 15 yards of the line of scrimmage.

  3. Olamide Zaccheaus, Virginia: His route running hints at promise greater than a short-area slot receiver. He’s an explosive player who offers some potential to develop a route game that could occasionally hold up on the outside. He’s also capable of hybrid work from the backfield (see below).

  4. Penny Hart, Georgia State: Also a former running back, Hart has tremendous burst and quickness. He uses it as well as any slot receiver in this class to attack downhill and put defenders at an early disadvantage. Hart holds up well to physical play.

  5. Greg Dortch, Wake Forest: Another option in the Brown-Zaccheaus-Hart style of slot receiver with big-play YAC ability and skill to stretch the field. He’s a tough player in the middle of the field, but his light weight will be a concern.

  6. Andy Isabella, UMass: Another former running back with sprinter’s speed and dynamic movement. He’ll stretch the field and he’s bigger than Dortch, but his ability to produce against physical play is a question mark.

  7. Mecole Hardman, Georgia: An intermediate and vertical threat from the slot, Hardman must prove he can identify, communicate, and execute the subtleties of a more traditional slot role in the quick passing game. He’s a big-play option hailed for his athletic ability skill downfield at the catch point.

Big Slot


Marques Colston, Jordan Matthews, and Anquan Boldin are three excellent examples of big slot receivers in the NFL. Michael Crabtree has also functioned well in this capacity, despite also earning use on the perimeter. These players have the quickness and route skills to beat a wide range of defensive athletes with guile, but they can also use their size and strength as mismatches.


  1. Hakeem Butler, Iowa State: Not thought of as a slot receiver due to his size, Butler earned a lot of time in the slot with the Cyclones. He has the athletic ability to execute quick-breaking routes often exclusive to slot receivers, making him a tough matchup for underneath defenders. He could force opponents to place their best defender on an island, which can lead to coverage mismatches for other players.

  2. A.J. Brown, Ole Miss: An intuitive player who integrates his skills with what unfolds on the field to generate creative solutions, Brown processes information quickly and has the range of athletic ability to win with quickness or power. He will win inside or outside, but using him in the slot also gives an offense some flexibility to use certain plays that would otherwise require a tight end.

  3. Deebo Samuel, South Carolina: Stylistically and athletically, Samuel reminds me of a mix of Sammy Watkins and Packers great Sterling Sharpe. There might be teams that only see him as a split end, but I’d like to see him as a player who can be moved between the slot and flanker. Imagine Samuel replacing—and upgrading—Randall Cobb in Green Bay.

  4. N’Keal Harry, Arizona State: Of the three positions Harry could play, the slot is arguably his best spot. He’s quicker than fast and he could produce right away in a role where he can earn yards after the catch but, also paint the deeper zones with sail routes, seams, posts, and deep crossers. None of these routes require the same degree of refinement he’ll need as strictly a perimeter player. He’ll probably play multiple spots, but he’d be a tough draw in a role like Michael Thomas’ in New Orleans or interchangeable with D.J. Moore inside/outside in Carolina.

  5. Stanley Morgan, Jr.: While he’s best cast as a flanker, his game has similarities to Hines Ward, an excellent slot receiver with a big-play component.

  6. Parris Campbell, Ohio State: One of the popular comparisons for Campbell is Percy Harvin, but Harvin in his (short) prime was a way more physical player who probably could have converted to running back. Campbell is more like a raw Keenan Allen with gamebreaking speed.

  7. Emmanuel Butler, Northern Arizona: Likely seen as a perimeter and red-zone threat that will earn a steady diet of fade routes, Butler has the quickness to work the slot and he’d hold up physically.

  8. Lil’Jordan Humphrey, Texas: A gifted pass catcher, Humphrey lacks the speed to play any other spot than the big slot. He’s a powerful player with good acceleration to work past linebackers and safeties. He’s an intriguing option who could outplay his draft status quickly with a good fit.

  9. Felton Davis III, Michigan State: Although not nearly as flashy as his peers, pound-for-pound, he might be the best tight-coverage, ball-magnet on the list. When healthy, his athletic ability is not an optimal match for any other role than the slot.


Gadget, RB-WR Hybrid


Percy Harvin and Tyreek Hill are successful examples of receivers who can win deep, destroy a defense after the catch, or produce on end-arounds and traditional backfield runs.


  1. Jalen Hurd, Baylor: He’s actually a better runner after practicing wide receiver footwork. He’s a great match for a gap run scheme and still runs through hits and wraps by defenders at every level of the field. He’s skilled in short- yardage and toss plays.

  2. Lil’Jordan Humphrey, Texas: Humphrey also has the acceleration, strength, and pad level for the gap game. You don’t want him running to the perimeter that often but his ability to run inside and shift to the slot could be problematic for certain defensive looks.

  3. Olamide Zaccheaus, Virginia: A former scatback with some outside route skills. He can be an effective screen player and seam-beater and wheel-route option from the slot or the backfield.

  4. Penny Hart, Georgia State: A former high school running back, he can perform a similar set of tasks Zacchaeus but with more upside as a receiver and less upside as a runner.

  5. Andy Isabella, UMass: If Zaccheaus is on the runner-end of the slot spectrum and Hart is in the middle, Isabella is more of a receiver. He could be functional on some draws or screens, but there are questions about his balance and power.


The Top 52 Receiver Prospects for Dynasty Leagues


My rankings are based on my Depth of Talent Score with ties sorted by the highest Breadth of Talent Score. These two scores represent the combination of collected data in this analysis, my view of their potential fit within any offensive system, and their potential for growth.


Additional rankings tables are sorted by Breadth of Talent, Big Receivers, and Slot Receivers. The main rankings are the Combined Board: A list of every player regardless of size and role. This is my truest, unfiltered ranking of players based on talent.


Some of the players on the Combined Board are true slot receivers. Although the Rams, Steelers, Patriots, and Browns are recent examples of teams that have heightened the role of the slot receiver in their offenses, the majority of teams place greater emphasis on height and weight for a primary receiver. Many of the smaller talents ranked on my Combined Board won’t even earn a shot at a starting role, but I don’t want to generate rankings where I downgrade players based on height and weight.


The Big Board and the Slot Board provides another way of looking at these players. If you lean toward the conservative side of what works in football, then the Big Board is a ranking of receivers that are at least 6-0, 210 lbs. If the player’s frame looks like it could add 10-15 pounds of muscle, I will include them on the Big Board.


The Slot Board is a list of players of any height/weight dimension I believe are well-suited to a slot role. While many of them are smaller players, Michael Crabtree and Marques Colston are “big slot” receivers, and I have included prospects whose skills and athleticism fit into this category. I have not differentiated big slot receivers from other slot receivers.


The detailed profile summaries below are based on my Combined Board of the top 54 receivers I have studied. I will continue studying prospects from April through the NFL Draft, so there’s a good chance that there will be additional receivers in the RSP Post-Draft publication. The tables for the Combined Board, Big Board, and Slot Board are in the pages after the profiles.


In any dynasty league setting, I would be comfortable drafting the top 24 receivers from the Combined Board. In larger leagues with practice squad allocations and large rosters, there are 35-45 prospects I’d consider from this list below.


Note: Links to player highlights and/or interviews may break over time, because I did not create them. I am only providing them as a reference for as long as they are available on the Internet. The music in these videos is often not safe for work.


Tier I: The first two tiers have nine players in total. This year the top tier has three players with Franchise Starter Grades. They should be long-term pieces that teams build around.



  1. Hakeem Butler, Iowa State (6-5, 227)


    Depth of Talent Score: 93.9 = Franchise Starter: Immediate production and leadership anchor.


    This is the highest grade the RSP has ever awarded a receiver since it began using Depth of Talent Scoring. Based on the excitement surrounding D.K. Metcalf and the optics that Butler drops the ball too much, ranking Butler as the top-rated receiver may be a a polarizing pick. The logic behind the decision is based on the results of the RSP’s process.


    Before sharing more about Butler, there are layers of information about the wide receiver position, the NFL’s scouting process, and the RSP’s scouting process you need to understand. This will also help


    you understand the context of the rankings of other players at the RSP as well as other independent scouts, media, and the league.


    The wide receiver position has three different roles: split-end, flanker, and slot. Each role emphasizes specific skills and traits over others. When NFL teams build draft boards, it scouts by role and to current need.


    This initial decision filters the wide receiver pool to a manageable number for the scouts to study. There’s no point in studying 80 players that will not succeed in the slot if your team can instead better focus its resources on just 12 viable candidates. To complicate matters a bit, teams will also filter the receiver pool by players who can perform multiple roles.


    The first thing the 49ers told the media after drafting Dante Pettis is that it coveted him, because he could play multiple wide receiver roles. Some players, like Pettis can perform all three roles; others are only capable of one or two. Based on the offensive scheme and organizational philosophy, teams will also have preferences for specific player archetypes—body type, style of movement, and how that player expresses his play on the field (physical, finesse, aggressive, etc.).


    The NFL’s 32 teams consider many of these factors when they filter the wide receiver position pool into roles. This creates different grades for the same players—and for reasons beyond variation of what scouts see and understand about the game when watching film.


    Let’s continue this explanation with Dante Pettis—the 2018 RSP’s top-ranked receiver.


    A team looking for a split end would have included Pettis on theid draft board. When studying him as solely a split-end, however, he might have earned the No.5 spot on a team’s wide receiver board, earning a fourth-round grade.


    Pettis also would have been considered as a small slot receiver by some teams—a Wes Welker option. Pettis is bigger, and not as quick as the Welker prototype. As such, a hypothetical team looking for a small slot option may have had Pettis further down on its draft board, ranking him seventh among slot options and giving him a fifth-round grade.


    Yet another hypothetical team may have seen Pettis as a big slot receiver. This organization may value bigger, stronger slot options that can perform some of the blocking. The team doesn’t want to use a tight end in certain run situations from pass-down sets, so it can maintain personnel flexibility and unpredictability. Pettis is a decent blocker on the outside but manning him against an outside linebacker is a losing proposition. That team may have ranked Pettis eighth on its board with a fifth- round grade.


    You can see the variation in grades based on three different offensive schemes and three separate scouting departments evaluating the same player for a different skill set.


    In contrast, the 49ers may have been seeking a flanker but recognized the value of one that can play in the slot if needed. There believe six players in the pool can do both. Pettis also has the added benefit of skill at split-end. He earns a low-first-round grade.

    The organization has a feeling Pettis will fall to the second-round because he’s a bit of a tweener among multiple receiver roles and it projects that flanker isn’t a position of need for other teams in the early round.


    This is why wide receiver has the greatest variation of draft grades of any position in football. The RSP doesn’t filter positions this way.

    While it has been an intriguing possibility to go this route, its priority on the list of new or updated processes is not as high as other ideas. Although the publication has a significant football audience, the primary audience remains fantasy players who are seeking rankings based on production potential.

    Discussion of role has value, but specific pre-draft rankings of split-ends, flankers, slots, two-role, and three-role receivers is not as important as one ranking of the position as a whole.


    The RSP—and other independent evaluators— analyze a much larger pool of wide receivers than the average NFL team. The RSP’s grading of wide receivers distributes points across its analysis criteria to account for all three positions.


    Because many teams don’t place as much weight on the vertical game for slot receivers, this position tends to get pushed down the RSP’s board. It’s why the RSP provides a small section in the chapter that splits out slot receivers for brief discussion.


    With some NFL teams adopting a spread offenses and requiring big-play slot options with vertical skills, the RSP’s grading system is inherently more aligned with that role. The reason: versatility. The RSP’s criteria slightly favor versatility in its positional grading.


    Metcalf is a big-time split end with massive strength, blazing speed, and ability to leap tall buildings in a single bound. He plays one position well and there are skills he must address common to all three receiver roles.


    Butler also possesses star-caliber, athletic ability. However, the RSP doesn’t value bigger, stronger, faster, quicker, and higher as automatically better. Once a player’s athletic traits qualify within a specific tier, that player is then judged on skills.


    For example, the Star-Caliber Tier for separation has a minimum requirement of athletic ability that includes a combination of the 40-Yard Dash, 20- Shuttle, 3-Cone, and Vertical Leap. There are various combinations where a player may athletically qualify based on his projected role and style of play. There can be some compensating factors with skill that may give a player a slight bump to the next tier, although the RSP is generally cautious about doing so.


    Once a player meets the athletic criteria, the RSP process determines if the player possesses the baseline skills to be placed in the tier. If so, the player is awarded those points. If not, he’s placed in the next tier below. When merited, a player is awarded a small bonus within that lower tier if his athletic ability belongs in a higher tier and there’s realistic potential for him to acquire the next-tier skills.


    What often happens when grading players is that there will be players who meet the athletic criteria of a higher tier but fall in the tier just below due to deficiencies in the RSP’s skill criteria. And there are other players who meet both athletic and skills

    criteria but may not be as athletic as the first not- quite-as-skilled player. Our football society inherently values bigger, higher, faster, stronger, and quicker and doesn’t account for the missing skills and probable diminishing returns of an ESPN Sports Science Sideshow Attraction. The RSP recognizes athleticism but strongly values skill. It’s why the RSP rankings often have striking differences from its peers.


    In contrast to D.K. Metcalf, Butler plays all three receiver positions and earned significant playing time as a split-end and slot receiver. His skills have greater depth of refinement and versatility.


    It begins at the line of scrimmage. Butler has violent hands and quick feet to work past tight man coverage and press technique at the line and at the top of his stem.


    He uses shoulder reductions, arm-overs, swipes, rips, chops, double swipes, and a swim in conjunction with rocker steps and a variety of foot- fire releases. Although aggressive cornerbacks can win battles against Butler in press coverage, Butler is often the favorite to still win the war.


    Route running distinguishes Butler from most of his peers—especially as a big receiver who has the leaping ability, speed, and strength of a split-end with the ability to run routes often reserved for flankers and slot receivers.


    Butler begins his stems with good pad level and acceleration to sell his 4.48-speed to his opponent.


    He varies his pacing, the turn of his head, and makes slight changes to the angle of his stems to manipulate his opponents into considering the wrong route. He’s specifically good at bending his stem behind the back of the coverage, which leaves him out of sight of the defender or forces a turn in the wrong direction before Butler makes his break. When Butler breaks his route, he consistently earns the proper depth with his routes.


    For a big, tall receiver, Butler has the knee and ankle flexion and the quickness off a smaller player. He drops his weight into hard breaks, decelerating quickly and earning immediate separation. As mentioned a few times earlier in this chapter, Butler’s whip route is an indication of his excellent mobility and accomplished route running.


    He’s also learned how to execute a long, violent drive step into his weight drop, which is one of the keys to earning separation with timing routes against tight man coverage. This is a difficult skill many college receivers don’t master until they reach the NFL—and sometimes never do.


    Butler also has the hip mobility to execute sharp turns on speed breaks. His speed breaks aren’t as consistently refined as his hard breaks because he’s inconsistent with pointing his toe at the sharpest angle when transitioning from the drop phase of a break to the drive phase. Once he points that toe with a sharper angle, he’ll earn tighter turns and

    flatter breaks. He can do it; he must do it more often.


    These skills make him a productive route runner of curls, outs, digs, comebacks, hitches, stop routes, over routes, and whip routes. They also set up deeper routes as the first half of a double move.


    He’ll also work back to his quarterback to provide his passer a better target. His film includes broken plays where he finds open creases in the zone.


    Butler’s work in the intermediate and vertical ranges of the field earns him weekly segments on highlight reels. He’s fluid at turning inside or outside the defender to shield the opponent from the ball on routes breaking away from the quarterback.


    His boundary awareness is good, and his execution is getting better. He tends to toe-tap his feet at the boundary in situations where it would be optimal for him to drag the feet. He has shown the ability to drag the feet—and in highly difficult target scenarios—but it’s still something where his choices aren’t always optimal and could cost him important receptions at the next level if he doesn’t become more selective with the technique.


    I posted a video analyzing this point on Twitter and Butler liked it without further explanation—a sign he agrees with the assessment. It’s likely something he’s been working on with (and without) Calvin Johnson.


    Some big and tall receivers with fluid athletic ability have atendency to play small when they need to play big. Butler has no such problem. He will lean into contact and box out opponents, disrupting their play to the ball or shielding them from the catch point.


    Butler also knows how to lean into an opponent near the boundary without getting pinned to the sideline. When the ball arrives, he’s comfortable with turning his upper body so he can attack the ball at the earliest window—even when forced to turn back to a target he’s running away from.


    Butler transitions fast from a spot ahead of the defender as the ball is arriving to a back-shoulder position underneath the opponent. He extends his arms to the ball and makes receptions with sound fingertip techniques.


    When Butler drops the ball—and he’s earned criticism for a higher-than-desired drop rate—the root problem is focus. He will make the initial catch but drop it while retracting or securing the ball to his body.


    This happens because he diverts his focus to the open space ahead and he’s transitioning to a ball carrier before he’s secured the ball. Ball carriers and route runners who slip often do so because they get one-step ahead of their process and fail to finish executing the current task.


    Focus drops are the easiest to address but arethe most likely to occur. Focus drops are the only drops

    that occur frequently enough for a receiver to earn additional opportunities. If the player is game- changing option—and Butler is—teams will even live with the drops.


    Occasionally, the source of a Butler drop will be a technique issue. He’ll use less optimal hand position for the location of a target.


    If the root of this technique issue was unfamiliarity with the technique—Jets receiver Quincy Enunwa’s hand positions were so off-base at Nebraska it was clear that he didn’t have enough facility with the basic vocabulary of techniques to catch the ball—this takes a lot more effort to correct. For Butler, the issue is more about choosing the best technique for the situation—again more of a focus issue.


    On rare occasions earlier in his career, Butler attempted to clap his hands onto the ball—a poor technique. However, this wasn’t a common problem.


    While these drops will be brought up thousands of times during NFL Draft Season, the only way this will derail his career is if he lets the focus drops get into his head and begins making new mistakes because he’s lost confidence and he’s over-thinking his process. If it hasn’t happened already, it’s unlikely to happen now.


    The catches that Butler makes—and he makes a lot of them—are often spectacular. He can make the extreme high-point reception and dig out the low throw. He’ll catch the ball over defenders or reach around and pull the ball away from odd angles while airborne in tight coverage.


    When working underneath the defense, he attacks the ball at chest and waist level with active, high- hands technique with his fingers pointed upward. This is the optimal technique for these routes despite the fact it’s often considered acceptable to use the low-hands, palms-to-the-sky position.


    There are a lot of excellent open-field runners in this receiver class and Butler is among the best. He can play big or small and do so in the appropriate moment.


    Butler has a quick stutter to freeze opponents at his back after he catches an underneath route. This gives the opponent an impression Butler is about to spin one way before he executes a tight turn in the opposite direction.


    Once in the open field, he can spin, dip, stop-start, or cut to avoid pursuit. Because his change–of- direction quickness is on par with smaller receivers and he’s a big receiver, this gives him a distinct advantage against open-field defenders.


    Although Butler’s frame appears thin because of his height, he’s a strong player. He pulls through wraps, stiff-arms opponents to the ground, and bounces off hits from defensive backs and the occasional linebacker.

    Butler has runs on his film resume where he makes multiple defenders miss and breaks multiple tackles within the same play. Randy Moss had this build— and this kind of film on his resume in more dramatic displays.


    Butler carries the ball with the arm that’s working way from the direct angles of pursuit. The carriage is usually high but the elbow can consistently be a little tighter to his frame. When the ball gets loose from Butler’s chest, he’s usually in the open field or making a dramatic change of direction.


    The greatest issue with his ball security occurs when he’s initially transitioning upfield from receiver to ball carrier. In these situations, Butler doesn’t secure the ball fast enough and begins his runs with the ball in his hands like a quarterback running the option.


    Butler displays good effort as a blocker and there’s opportunity for him to develop better technique and become an excellent one. He rarely avoids confrontations and he makes the effort to punch, keep his feet moving, and drive defenders away from the ball carrier’s path. This makes him a competent stalk blocker.


    Butler uses his reach to his advantage, extending to the defender quickly and then working towards the opponent’s body without overextending his frame. This doesn’t always work as planned, so he could be wiser to close the gap between himself and his opponent before extending his arms.


    Butler needs to continue to improve this approach to develop an uppercut punch so he can maximize the force of his strikes. He’s already strong enough to put a cornerback and safety on his ass with his double jabs. However this is inefficient technique and doesn’t allow him to control the defender to the ground like an uppercut and latch to the chest.


    Butler already squares up his opponents and uses his feet well after the collision. When he can sustain contact, he turns opponents with ease. He also sets up opponents near the line of scrimmage as if he’s releasing into a route when he’s actually setting up position for a block.


    Known for his work ethic, Butler is an excellent overall prospect. All players have areas where they can improve but his skills are strong enough in every facet of the position that he can, and should, have an immediate impact and produce consistently as a rookie.


    RSP Boiler Room: Hakeem Butler RSP Boiler Room: Let It Whip



    Hakeem Butler Highlights


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Butler is worth the No.1 overall pick in dynasty leagues. If you know someone who is bent on Metcalf and can trade down a spot or two, there’s a good chance you’ll earn better value with the pick and a shot at Butler or the RSP’s No.2 option below…

  2. Miles Boykin, Notre Dame (6-4, 220)


    Depth of Talent Score: 91.85 = Franchise Starter: Immediate production and leadership anchor.


    D.K. Metcalf’s NFL Combine performance earned crazy buzz. It’s impressive to see a 6-3, 228-pound man run a 4.3-second, 40-Yard Dash, lift the bar 27 times on the Bench Press, and leap 40.5-inches vertically.


    Those metrics reflect the athleticism Metcalf draws on when running deep routes, elevating for the ball, and fighting through contact., However, his 4.5- second, 20 Shuttle and 7.38-second, 3-Cone are subpar times for an NFL player—not just among starting receivers, among all NFL players.


    If you’re seeking a receiver who can work the deep perimeter but also run routes inside and find multiple solutions for yardage as an underneath receiver, that’s acceptable. However, you’re placing higher priority on a prospect whose game is less predictable—even if that predictability is difficult to stop.


    Boykin is that guy. And if the 40-Yard Dash wasn’t an event with sponsors sporting deep pockets— rewarding the fastest time with substantial money— we might see more time spent on why that is.

    Unfortunately, the prospect of a more nuanced discussion of metrics that wouldn’t be unintentionally misleading isn’t on the immediate horizon.


    Compare Boykin and Metcalf’s metrics and it’s clear that Boykin’s athleticism includes fewer limitations than Metcalf’s and has similar high-end upside where Metcalf excelled. Boykin ran a 4.42-second, 40-Yard Dash; a sizzling 4.07-second, 20-Shuttle; a slot- receiver-like 6.77-second, 3-Cone; and outleaped Metcalf by 3 inches when he earned 43.5 inches in the Vertical.


    All of that acceleration, quickness, explosion, and leg strength comes in a 6-4, 220-pound frame that is required to run fast, stop fast, and change direction fast before and after catching the football. It makes Boykin a tremendous asset—and a more compelling all-around athlete than Metcalf. If advertising and ratings didn’t have sway big media analysis— especially in sports, which is often more about entertainment than hard-hitting news—Boykin’s NFL Combine would have completely overshadowed Metcalf’s in the public arena.


    This is the nature of our world. It has always been the case and it won’t change. Instead of lamenting it, be thankful that you recognize it, value it, and can do something actionable with it.


    Like Butler, Boykin saw time on either side of the formation and in the slot. He’s quick with his hands and feet and has enough releases to earn separation in the NFL as he continues developing his game at the line of scrimmage.

    He can reduce his shoulder, chop, double-swipe, or use an arm-over in conjunction with a rocker step or foot-fire releases of two-, three-, and four-steps.

    Boykin will also deliver a quick punch and then use the arm-over to clear his opponent. When he earns separation, Boykin often has the presence of mind to stack his opponent early in the route.


    He understands how to manipulate the coverage with the shape of his stems so he’s pressuring the seams between defenders. He’ll often bait his coverage with a head fake at the top of his stems.


    At this point of his development, Boykin’s speed breaks are better than his hard breaks, but he can perform both forms of turns at the top of a route. He gets his head around fast to find the ball. When he runs vertical routes, Boykin has an excellent stick that lands outside the shoulders of coverage and usually forces the defender to react in the wrong direction. He’s good at setting up crossover moves that create breaks across the defender’s face into open space.


    If nothing about his game improves between this evaluation and the beginning of the NFL season, Boykin will have more success on routes that break downfield because of his physical skills, ability to defeat press coverage, and his acumen at the catch point.


    Routes breaking back to the quarterback will have some inconsistencies because he has occasional lapses with the flatness of breaks on speed turns and he needs multiple steps to drop his weight into hard breaks.


    Boykin can drop his weight, but he needs to trust his feet and legs to make the drop faster. This is a common phase of development young receivers have to go through.


    Another occasional lapse is his stem length on timing routes where he’ll break too soon and not earn the proper depth on the route. None of these issues are significant enough to derail Boykin’s production potential.


    More likely, he’ll experience isolated mistakes with route depth, break flatness, and not earning enough separation with hard breaks on curls, comebacks, and dig routes. Despite these minor issues, Boykin runs a good comeback route and it wouldn’t be surprising if he sees targets with this route early in his career.


    Boykin has excellent hands. He’s consistent with fingertip technique at the catch point, extends his arms to attack the ball at an early window of arrival, and he can adjust high, low, or away from his frame with a wide radius.


    Good hand-eye coordination and fluid movements help Boykin successfully make difficult adjustments to the ball, including difficult one-handed stabs at full speed on targets that require awkward and late turns from tight coverage.

    He also executes demanding moves in fluid sequence when transitioning from receiver to runner. He can make an underhand catch with significant extension of his arms while running away from the quarterback and then drop his pads under contact of an oncoming defender.


    Boykin also shields defenders effectively and drags his feet with good technique at the boundary. Like most receivers, Boykin will have the occasional focus drop when tight coverage extends an arm across his frame. Otherwise, his hands are reliable and dynamic.


    Boykin shines after the catch. He has the elite stop- start quickness to turn inside or outside a defender playing over the top of him. Although not the professional wrestling monster Metcalf is, Boykin is a strong runner with low pad level and he extends through direct contact for extra yards.


    He’ll break through wraps, bounce off occasional hits, and he’ll break some ankles with full-speed slalom cuts. Boykin uses the correct arm to protect the ball from pursuit, but he must keep his elbow tighter in the open field.


    Boykin has upside as a blocker. He earns a square position on a consistent basis and can deliver a good punch with force. He has dropped an outside linebacker with this technique and he’ll routinely earn pushes on weakside linebackers with his position and punch.


    Like Hakeem Butler, Boykin uses a jab as his strike and must learn to uppercut and latch onto the defender after the punch. This will give him greater control, which is needed if he’s used to block at the line of scrimmage or sustain stalk blocks.


    Boykin should earn a significant role in an offense as a rookie. If he’s paired with an accurate and aggressive vertical thrower, he could generate a lot more excitement than college football fans saw from him at Notre Dame.


    If not, he’s capable of earning strong volume as a possession-plus threat who will supplement his production with deep plays or forays through a defense for longer gains on shorter targets. If Boykin was in last year’s class, he would have been the top receiver on the board and earned the highest grade the RSP has given since it began using Depth of Talent Scoring.


    Miles Boykin Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: The likely question at the top of dynasty drafts will be Metcalf or Butler. If you prefer Butler but you’re comfortable dropping a few picks lower than what is necessary to land him, Boykin is a great consolation prize who could easily outplay the player you wanted most.


  3. A.J. Brown, Ole Miss (6-0, 226) Depth of Talent Score: 91.7 = Franchise

    Starter: Immediate production and leadership anchor.


    The best receiver at Ole Miss for the past few years has been Brown. He gets overlooked a bit because he’s seen as a big slot receiver and D.K. Metcalf’s potential casts a hefty shadow. A closer look reveals an excellent playmaker with the speed and physicality to play outside, the quickness to play inside, and the football smarts to thrill the team that picks him in April.


    Brown has an arsenal of moves to release from man coverage from the line. He uses swipes, double swipes, arm-overs, shakes, swims, and chops in conjunction with various foot-fire releases of one-, two-, three-, and four-steps. He’ll combine a shake with his foot-fire and an arm maneuver to get free.


    There are moments where Brown doesn’t earn more than a half-step of separation, which could be a cause of concern about his perimeter potential.

    However, Brown can lean too much on his swim move and a little more variance of strategy should help him. His 4.49-second, 40-Yard Dash is on par with Butler and Deebo Samuel. Once he earns a runway, he can taxi into flight.


    Brown executes his stems with a quick pace and sells the potential deep route with his pads over his knees. He’ll widen his stems against off-coverage to set up a break back inside.


    He manipulates the directions of his stems and uses head and shoulder fakes to bait defenders at the top of the stem. Brown also varies his pacing and stride length to achieve a similar effect.


    Like Butler, Brown can execute a single, long drive- step into his hard breaks. He’ll finish with good bend to drop his weight into the break and come back to the quarterback. When the play breaks down, Brown is an aware receiver who works to open space.


    He uses all of these tools to execute double moves to get open in the vertical game. He’ll also run the whip route with a bend and quickness that rivals some of Keenan Allen’s work with this difficult underneath route.


    When executing speed breaks, Brown delivers a sudden snap with his turn and breaks flat or towards the ball. His speed out might be his fastest pattern. He also has a quick drag step into breaks on slants, so he can maximize his acceleration upfield.


    Brown is a clutch receiver with good technique against tight coverage and in highly trafficked areas. He knows when to use the appropriate hands position for the target location and he attacks the earliest available target window. If his route doesn’t earn him separation, he’ll battle for position with the ball in the air.


    Brown can high-point the ball or dig it out from the ground. He’ll take hits to his back and make difficult adjustments to the football with defenders hanging off him. He’ll have the occasional drop because he diverts his focus from securing the ball to turning upfield.


    Brown is a strong target for back-shoulder plays, corner routes, and comebacks. Ole Miss used him frequently on slants in the red zone because of his quickness off the line and sturdiness at the catch point.


    “Sturdy” is a good description of Brown. He’s built like a power back and often plays like one, too.

    Trailing linebackers need more than a wrap if they hope to drop Brown to the turf.


    When he’s wrapped, he’s strong enough to run through the linebacker or at least drag an opponent for extra yards. Once a defender compromises Brown’s balance, he will extend for all the yards he can get. He’s willing to throw his body around for that extra yard.


    Defensive backs have difficulty bringing Brown to the ground if they wrap him high. For a receiver, he has a low center of gravity, which helps him break reaches and wraps as well as bounce off contact.


    Brown is also shifty. He’ll square up defensive backs in space and juke them. He can spin away from direct contact and he has an excellent stick move where he can stab his leg towards an opponent and work in the opposite direction. Brown often uses that stick the way a boxer uses an active jab to set up a bigger punch.


    Brown has a good stiff-arm with some heft to its delivery. He’ll rock a defensive back when he strikes.


    He carries the ball with the appropriate arm to avoid the nearest pursuit angle. He maintains a high and tight carriage in traffic and rips and slaps to the ball don’t phase his security.


    In the open field, Brown’s ball security gets looser and he’ll tighten it when he spots pursuit closing on him. He doesn’t switch the ball to the appropriate arm when there’s space to do so.


    Brown’s effort as a blocker is inconsistent. When he makes it a point to block, he’s strong, physical, and technically-sound.


    He’ll close the gap on an opponent, square his position, bend his hips, and attack with intensity. He will roll through uppercut punches to stun a defender when stalk blocking and this technique will be good at the edge of a defense against weak side linebackers and box safeties.


    As a stalk blocker, he’ll maintain a square position, approach with patience, and maintain low pads and active hands. When he has lapses with technique, it results in Brown overextending.

    There are valid arguments Brown is the top receiver in this class. He reminds me of Anquan Boldin with more speed. He could wind up a high-volume slot receiver with big-play ability in the red zone and on the perimeter.


    Based solely on his play, he could be the safest receiver on the board. He’ll play immediately in the NFL and he’s a fit for any team.


    I’d love to see him in Dallas because I think he’d mesh well with Dak Prescott as a player who can be where he’s supposed to be in and outside of structure, but it’s unlikely. Patrick Mahomes needs more weapons that can play outside, inside, and run the football. They’d be a great pairing for years to come—especially when plays break down.


    A.J. Brown Highlights



    RSP Boiler Room: Integrated Technique


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Brown is the third of three receivers that the RSP has awarded a franchise starter grade. This has been a rare occurrence of late.


    Brown is worth a top-five pick. There isn’t a running back or tight end that I’d take before him unless the league uses a 1.5 PPR premium for tight ends.


    While a bad offensive situation could rob him of immediate upside, his skills will eventually shine through. Take him with confidence.


    Tier II: The next six players have the talent to start this year and learn as they go. All four players would have been ranked as Tier I options in 2018’s class.


  4. D.K. Metcalf, Ole Miss (6-3, 228)


    Depth of Talent Score: 87 = Starter: Capable of a larger role and learning on the go.


    In every sport, there are specific skills that capture our imagination. Metcalf’s speed-size-power combination and catch radius is the football equivalent of the high-flying power dunker, agrand- slam-hitting cleanup hitter, the tennis player with an insane serve speed, and the boxer with early knockout power. Fans love the highs and live with the lows of lackluster shoot percentages, high strikeout rates, too many double faults, and late- round losses.


    Metcalf is this guy. He’s exciting because there’s a sense that at any moment, he’s about to do something you’ve rarely seen. Even if you’ve lived long enough and watched enough sport to have seen it all, what Metcalf is capable of delivering is the stuff that never gets old.


    Yet like many of these athletic wunderkinds, he’s not a complete player. He may never become one.


    And no matter how much will be said otherwise by talking heads that double-down on hot and smelly takes, that’s ok.


    The past three profiles explain why the buzz surrounding Metcalf has a risk of inflating his value beyond healthy expectation. Now that Metcalf has been framed in a more realistic context, let’s talk about how good he is.


    He is a big and strong player who will leap over opponents, run over obstacles, and run by just about anyone when he earns enough space to get downhill. His work at the line of scrimmage is often hit-or- miss.


    Metcalf has the most violent hands in this class. NFL wide receivers need to conspire with position coaches not to let tape of DeAndre Hopkins into Metcalf’s powerful hands because if he starts swinging like Hopkins at the line, officials will have to shut down this behavior out of concern that Metcalf will be charged with felony assault.


    His swipes and chops are quick and powerful. He pairs them well with foot-fire moves of one, two, and three steps. His pace variation with this footwork helps him set up his moves and he’ll throw in a rocker step as a changeup. Although a big dude, Metcalf can also swat a defender’s reach and dip the shoulder under the press coverage.


    His 20-Shuttle acceleration is 4.5 seconds—a Reserve Tier grade—but the RSP often preaches the value of compensating factors. Metcalf’s compensating factors are his violent hands, his powerful frame, and his 4.33-second, 40-Yard speed.


    Metcalf’s heavy hands create space before he even begins his acceleration. Most players require an even balance of quickness, acceleration, and hand work to get free. Metcalf can clear the road with his strength.


    It’s likely that Metcalf will be a star deep threat even if the excuses about him tripping in the acceleration and change of direction drills fall flat. And they do. He’s slower and stiffer in short spaces—get over it.


    Metcalf’s intensity off the line often forces opponents to play off him out of sheer terror of being knocked down, run over, or sprinted past. He’ll take advantage of this fear by varying his pacing off the line.


    Metcalf has successfully baited off-coverage defenders into believing that he’s stalk blocking only to accelerate past them. When he’s not pulling this stunt, he accelerates off the line with his pads over his knees and the no-hold-barred approach is enough to keep an upcoming opponent awake at night.


    Because defenders give him healthy respect in off- coverage, Metcalf has leveraged that into easier separation on routes breaking back to the quarterback. He may not drop his weight with optimal flexibility and he has to gather his steps into breaks, but he will break back to the ball with intensity. When his quarterback scrambles, Metcalf also works well to open space.

    With vertical routes, Metcalf will take the back of the off coverage, working into the defender’s blind spot and heels to set up his breaks. He also has a nice head fake with his stems to freeze opponents to the inside before breaking on the fade.


    He can get predictable with his deep routes, trying to bait defenders with hard sticks early in the stem. However, every defender who has watched Metcalf knows he can’t bend well, so they’re not falling for a stick when he’ll give them a lot more steps into a hard break and more time to recover.


    His movement is good enough to execute flat breaks against tight man coverage when using speed turns. However, he’ll struggle with this break if he’s leaning too much during his stem—and he’s prone to do so.


    Although he uses pacing variation and some movement to bait opponents, Metcalf still needs to develop greater subtlety with his stems. While he scares a lot of cornerbacks into frozen deer mode, NFL defenders are patient wolves that will play a more physical mode of football.


    When college opponents took this approach with Metcalf, they often limited him. As with many bullies, the best solution is to bully Metcalf back. When Metcalf is forced to be subtle and make precise moves, he falters more often.


    He doesn’t bend well enough on the perimeter on comebacks. When pressured, he’s forced to make tight turns and that’s difficult. He can lose focus and step out of bounds as a result.


    He gathers his steps in and out of breaks and on the fade route—one of his best routes—he shows lapses with the timing of his stops and/or his turns to the ball. He’ll have an easier time fixing the fade route and to his credit, he often corrects mistakes he made earlier in games.


    The physical limitations may always remain. The good thing for Metcalf is that as difficult as it may be for him to develop more bend and movement at high speeds, it’s just as difficult for NFL defenses to find cornerbacks strong enough and fast enough to stay with him in the deep game.


    Metcalf’s drops deserve as much coverage as D.K. Butlers’s. He can have some trouble with throws at his belt line when breaking away from the target and the trajectory of the ball gets into his body.


    Belt line targets require quick decisions with the hands and it’s the location that crosses up many receivers when it comes to technique choice. Targets to the back hip also compound the problem because it requires an awkward turn at a rate of speed that can be difficult for a receiver to make.


    I think the best way to defend Metcalf is to play him rather than the ball. When opponents track the ball and play tight to the receiver, Metcalf has the physical skills to leap over or reach around obstacles and pull the ball away.

    Their position gives Metcalf the luxury of a counter move as he watches the play unfold from behind the opponent. Yet, when the defender turns towards Metcalf’s chest with the ball in flight and attacks the receiver as the ball arrives, the effort distracts Metcalf and leads to more drops.


    Focus issues and bad hands technique choices for the placement of the ball are Metcalf’s leading sources of drops. Teams will have to live with the focus issues.


    The technique problems are addressable—especially when he uses underhand technique on fade routes where he’s behind the coverage and reaching over top. Also to Metcalf’s credit, he’s corrected his issue in-game and caught the same target with the proper technique in a clutch situation to win the game.


    When he’s not dropping the ball—and clearly, he’s catching it frequently enough to earn this level of notoriety—he makes excellent adjustments to the ball. He extends well for the target, uses fingertip techniques, and he’ll track the ball over his head, low, and over his shoulder.


    His ability to reach for a target when the ball arrives past him while he’s on a dead run is impressive.

    Metcalf has also shown the ability to execute leaping turns into the defender, reach past the defender’s head and secure the ball with his hands while the defender’s helmet is between his forearms.


    Hard contact to his legs and back does not disrupt Metcalf’s concentration to catch the football. Neither does head-on contact when he has time and range to secure it before the hit. He’s a big-time playmaker who gives an offense a viable shot at a drive- changing play with every target.


    Once Metcalf earns the ball, he’s tough to stop. He pulls through wraps, bounces off hits, and he throws the stiff-arm at cornerbacks like he tossed an anvil into their chests.


    He’ll split defenders or run around them. If he earns enough of a runway before or after contact, Metcalf pulls through reaches with the force of a Mack Truck splintering guard rails. The best chance opponents have is to make him change direction at a high enough rate of speed to compromise his balance.


    Metcalf secures the ball under the arm that’s working away from pursuit. For whatever reason, he secures the ball differently under each arm. The left arm holds the ball lower from the chest; the right arm is looser at the elbow.


    He transitions fast from route runner to blocker. He earns a square position and gets both hands into the chest of his opponents.


    He has the strength to latch onto defensive backs and throw them aside—even when he’s hit first. He must learn to uppercut. Right now, he delivers hard shots but overextends.

    Metcalf broke his foot in 2016 and suffered a season- ending neck injury in 2018. He’ll be ready to play in 2019 and he should earn playing time as a big-play option. Even if he doesn’t start right away, he’ll have big weeks with limited targets.


    Metcalf is not another Stephen Hill story. The RSP was there for Hill and had legitimate concerns.


    There are certainly some paths that could render Metcalf a bust. He could struggle with physical play and drop the ball too much. He could get paired with a poor vertical thrower and asked to be a different receiver than his physical profile. Or, he could continue adding to his track record of injuries and never fully develop into the player his team expected as his organization loses patience and he loses confidence.


    However, Metcalf’s ability and RSP grade would have recently placed him among the top 2-3 options in other classes. The fact that he’s No.4 in this rich of a class is a testament to what he can do.


    D.K. Metcalf Highlights



    RSP Film Boiler Room: Winning And Losing the Fade


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Many leagues will likely consider him the No.1 overall prospect. If you can drop 1-3 spots in this draft and earn additional capital, you’re likely earning the more valuable player and additional compensation.


    Metcalf’s skills are worth a top pick. He may always have more highs and lows with his weekly production if he can’t improve his route running. However, I’d take my chances on the possibility that he improves.


    He may never change direction as quickly as DeAndre Hopkins, but his poor acceleration metrics are similar to Hopkins—and we know how exceptional Hopkins is against press and at the catch point. He’s one of the most consistent receivers in fantasy football.


  5. Deebo Samuel, South Carolina (5-11, 214)


    Depth of Talent Score: 86.15 = Starter: Capable of a larger role and learning on the go.


    Samuel is another receiver at the top of this board who would have been in consideration for the top position in recent classes. He’s capable of drive- changing plays from anywhere on the field and delivers his playmaking ability with greater variety than any of the four options listed before him.


    Samuel has the speed to win deep, the finesse and physicality to win in the red zone, and excellent open-field playmaking that works after the catch and in the kicking game. His combination of athletic ability and versatile skills resembles players past and present like Tim Brown, Sterling Sharpe, and Sammy Watkins.


    Samuel has a feel for earning releases against tight coverage at the line of scrimmage and he should only improve as he devotes more time to this part of

    the game. He has the hand-eye coordination to lean away from an attempted jam, grab the wrists of his opponent, and swipe the opponent’s arms to the side. He also has a single swipe, arm-over, and a chop that he’ll combine with a variety of foot-fire releases or a rocker step.


    He routinely wins without the use of his hands because he’s become adept at using a wide variety of efficient footwork patterns to force opponents off their spot and earn a lane up the field. Samuel will vary pace, step length, and add hard sticks and head and shoulder fakes to bait opponents into giving up open space. He usually can run past them with little more than a dip of the shoulder.


    He routinely earns deep separation as an outside receiver with three-step release moves layered with a head fake and stick to the outside and drive back to the inside. Because Samuel has earned separation easier than many of his peers, he isn’t as conscientious as he should be about stacking his opponents to control his pace.


    This would reduce the likelihood of him tipping off defenders because he isn’t giving them a chance to read his head and eyes. Right now, they can trail Samuel’s hip and read enough of the receiver’s body language to make a play on the ball.


    When Samuel begins plays with his pads low and accelerating with a good sale of the go route, he’s difficult to stop. He sells various routes with stutters, head fakes, shoulder turns, shakes, and arm- drumming, and stop-start moves—especially defenders in shallow zones.


    Despite having an extensive library of moves to manipulate opponents with his stems, he’s selective with pairing moves so he can execute routes with economical movement.


    He knows when to turn into a defender at the top of his stems or take the back of the off-coverage corner and run up his feet. He’s skilled at pressuring his opponents with his speed so they have to react to the possibility of the route he’s faking before his actual break.


    I didn’t see Samuel execute hard breaks with a drop of his weight into a sudden stop, but he’s excellent at speed breaks and tight turns. He accelerates into his breaks so he can drive the defender back and execute a tight, flat speed turn. Once he executes his breaks, he drives back to the ball with a square position so he’s offering a big target and shielding his opponent.


    When his quarterback breaks the pocket, Samuel works to the open space. Although he didn’t execute hard breaks on a frequent enough basis in this offense for me to see them, he can execute a one- step drive into a hitch. Mastering the ability to drive with one step into a hard break is an important skill for a pro and Samuel has shown signs of figuring out the hard part of the hard break.

    Samuel doesn’t have an extensive resume of circus catches against tight coverage, but he has shown acrobatic skill to win targets arriving wide, high, or low from his frame. He also demonstrated skill to win against tight coverage and contact on routes where the quarterback delivered well-placed targets where the adjustments were by design.


    Samuel makes tough catches over the middle with contact coming as well as high-point opporutnities on fades. He’s skilled at the high-point, pull-down, and turn to shield his opponents on fades where the ball arrives as planned. Samuel struggles when he has to jump back for the ball on underthrown targets. He has to figure out a better position to set up his leap back to the target.


    A dangerous player with the ball in his hands, Samuel uses efficient fakes and movement in tight space to wiggle past defenders. This makes him an excellent option on screen and crossing routes.


    He also has the dips, lateral cuts, spins, and stop- start moves to zig-zag the length and width of the field. He’s a sturdy option with ball carrying stamina to bounce off hits and pull through wraps. He isn’t the tackle-breaker Butler is, but he can run through multiple wraps on a play because of his skill to avoid direct angles of contact.


    He has an excellent stiff-arm he can use to surgically remove defensive backs as he turns the corner to the sidelines or as a triphammer that rocks defenders backward if he earns the leverage to deliver it as a blunt weapon.


    When it’s time to finish, Samuel drops the pads and extends for more yards or even pulls through wraps. He can win direct collisions against outside linebackers and push for positive yards because he accelerates through contact with his low pad level.


    He has no problem splitting linebackers and safeties with an aggressive dive in short-yardage situations. He’ll also use a forearm shiver to knock defensive backs to the ground.


    Want to see a lot of this encompassed in one play? Watch Samuel weave through the Clemson defense this year.


    An experienced ball carrier, Samuel uses the correct arm away from the pursuit and he’ll lock the ball into a high and tight position. He switches the ball to the appropriate arm when there’s room to handle contact to the ball. Samuel’s ball security lapses a bit with his left arm because the elbow drifts loose.


    Samuel needs to be quicker and more focused when stalk blocking. He needs to close the gap faster— especially when he’s a lead blocker so he can sustain his contact.


    This criticism may sound like Samuel is one of those receivers who try to find creative ways to avoid blocking. This is not the case.

    Samuel squares his opponents, locks on well with his arms, and moves his feet well. He has good timing with cut blocks although the trajectory of his shot at opponents’ legs can arrive too low.


    He also hustles across the field to deliver hits on cornerbacks on long-developing plays. The only major issues with him as a blocker are his punch, the height of his cut blocks, and being slow to diagnose and attack in certain stalk and lead blocking scenarios.


    His return skills are among the best in this class. He’s economical with his movements but his burst and setups of creases make him one of the most dynamic at entering and exiting running lanes. He also does work as part of punt coverage.


    A broken leg cost Samuel the 2017 season and he’s dealt with multiple hamstring issues during his college career.


    Samuel began his career ahead of the curve, absorbing the offense fast, and continued developing through its culmination. He developed into a good route runner in the middle of the field and showed he could play the left and right spots of the formation.


    Samuel may not have earned a franchise starter grade in the RSP’s Depth of Talent Scoring, but his grade rivals those of Calvin Ridley, D.J. Moore, and Dante Pettis. All three of these options had success for weeks at a time during their rookie year.


    Samuel wins in the deep aerial game as a split end, as a big-play slot option delivering the YAC, or does a little of everything as a flanker. It makes him a fit for a lot of teams.


    Baltimore could use a quick-hitting option with its option passing game that is also capable of taking the top off the defense. Even if Jaleel Scott and Jordan Lasley develop into quality receivers, Samuel could still be a focal point who moves around the offense.


    If Carolina wants to continue adding versatile receivers, Samuel can run the aerial perimeter routes that Moore doesn’t do well and run the football in the option game. Imagine Moore and the two Samuels on the field at the same time and forcing defenses to figure out who is running the ball.


    Green Bay could use a replacement for Randall Cobb that can put pressure on safeties. New England also needs a player with Samuel’s skills.


    Scott Bischoff’s RSP Scouting Report



    Deebo Samuel Highlights


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Samuel has the skills of a first-round pick. Whether there’s enough demand for him to earn that selection in April is the big question.

    If he falls to the second round, it will likely match him with a good quarterback and it could pose some difficult decisions for fantasy players—the franchise talent or the starter talent with a great fit? Either way, he’s definitely worth a first-round pick and there are valid reasons to consider him ahead of the running backs or the tight ends at the top of the board.


  6. N’Keal Harry, Arizona State (6-2, 228)


    Depth of Talent Score: 86.1= Starter: Starting immediately with large role and learning on the go.


    Is Harry a big slot receiver or a perimeter player? That’s the big question a team will have to answer. His 4.53-second, 40-Yard Dash was better than expected but he didn’t run any of the acceleration or change of direction drills. His 38.5-inch Vertical Leap is an excellent display of explosion and leg strength. He also matched D.K. Metcalf with 27 reps on the bench press.


    While Harry can win outside—and he played on the left and right sides of the Arizona State offense—he’s more of a big slot than a perimeter guy. Seeking a win in the 50/50 game? He’ll do the job at the boundary—and have moments of extraordinary play while doing so.


    Want him to earn space and run after the catch? He’s better off in the middle—and he can run. Like last year’s running back class, I actually feel a little dirty having a receiver with Harry’s caliber of skill this low—and I’m going to need an extra box of soap by the time this list winds its way to the back end of the Top 20.


    Harry’s issues as a perimeter don’t begin at the line of scrimmage. He’s physical, quick, and knowledgeable while executing a variety of techniques.


    He uses the arm-over and the rip to work through coverage at the line or the top of the stem. He’ll pair them with a rocker step or foot-fires of two and three steps.


    Harry also has chops, swipes, and an impressive push-pull move when he can land it. He’ll become even more dangerous when he can cultivate a more violent stick with his lead foot so he earns more dramatic reactions from cornerbacks.


    Patient corners that play tight will have more success with Harry early on because he is not accustomed to executing an alternate plan when his first moves don’t work. When Harry earns separation, especially on the outside, he must stack. He’s not fast enough to outrun the recovery speed of cornerbacks unless his physicality put them on the ground.


    Defenders also have success playing off-coverage on the perimeter because they can anticipate the route, shade that side where the break is heading, and jump the pattern. Harry didn’t show the acceleration

    to earn significant separation against off coverage—if he earned it at all.


    The complementary routes for deep perimeter patterns also need work. Harry drops his weight into breaks but needs multiple steps to gather into the break point. He must bend his knees more.


    One thing he does well on the perimeter is maintain eye discipline and pad level to sell the downfield route. His stems don’t drift and he gets as much out of his vertical forays as he can.


    This really comes into play when he runs the over route. He’ll often give a two-step stutter against off coverage to bait the defender and then break violently on the over. There’s a play on his film where he turns his shoulder so violently into the stair-step break of the over route that the trailing defender trying to reach for him went flying in the opposite direction.


    His hitches have a nice one-step stop and turn and he sets up the double move with a sudden turn out of this hitch look.


    His speed breaks are tight, but they could be a little sharper. It appears he can’t open his hips a full 90 degrees but there’s enough examples of him opening his hips a little more in some games than others and those turns are notably sharper.


    I think Harry plays a bit to his scouting report to bait defenders. He’ll often use a slower release on a speed out to bait his opponent and then accelerate through it much faster than he entered the break, earning a lot more space.


    There’s a long list of excellent pass catchers in this class. I think could write “he’s one of the best pass catchers in this class,” for 9 of the top 17 players on the board (and the guy at No.30 can show all of them up on any given target) and not feel like I’m lying.


    If I had to limit the list to five players, I’d probably lose sleep at night if I left Harry off it. He’s an incredible tracker of the football—Brandon Lloyd level.


    He makes one-handed, over-the-shoulder catches against tight coverage look like something that anyone with a pair of eyes and hands could do the moment they leave the womb. He makes these bucket catches so often and easily, that I was initially concerned Harry couldn’t high-point the ball.


    Then I saw some of the most extreme high-point extension at late target windows that I’ll probably ever see. He excels at jump balls because he’s skilled at earning position with his strong frame and timing his leap.


    However, I think he gets complacent about his position because he’s had so much success winning the ball in challenging situations. If he doesn’t become more conscientious about earning optimal

    position whenever there’s an opportunity, his success against tight man coverage may decline.


    Harry’s hands don’t just show up on difficult plays. He makes catches that are mundane by comparison and does so with proper hand positions and an active attack. When he drops the ball, it’s usually due to losing focus because he’s transitioning to from receiver to ball carrier too soon or he’s dealing with tight coverage and a low-percentage target.


    Although he lacks acceleration to pull away, Harry is an excellent runner. He makes quick transitions upfield and he has quick press-and-cut maneuvers in tight traffic that earns him running lanes. He reverses field quickly and pivots with quick hip flips to access a backside lane.


    He runs with better stamina than acceleration. Think of him as the Marshawn Lynch of receivers—a well- built ball carrier with the strength to pull through wraps and bounce off hits. He can knock over or shed a safety’s direct collision and continue upfield. He’ll also push a pile and drag multiple defensive backs at the end of runs.


    Harry also splits blocks with strong pad level and has the stiff-arm to ward off contact. Some of his better runs are plays where he found cutback lanes and outlasted his opponents with stamina, quick changes of direction, and stayed alive long enough to find a lane.


    Harry carries the ball with either arm and will wrap the ball with both arms when in traffic. When he can’t switch the ball to the side that’s away from pursuit and he’s about to collide with an opponent, Harry will tilt his ball-carrying shoulder away from the tackler. He also withstands strip attempts.

    When Harry is in the open field, he swings the ball low and away from his chest. This must improve because he gets caught from behind by pursuit— especially in the middle of the field and this lapse of technique will lead to punch outs.


    Harry is a willing blocker who comes off the line with intensity and attacks his opponent. He’ll get his hands inside the pads of his assignment and push or turn the man while maintaining a square position.
