    He’s skilled at latching his hands onto defenders in the run game, working consistently to get his hands in position. He’ll mix up his stride pace on his initial approach to set up his punch.


    He’s a good striker, too. Although he doesn’t always deliver the uppercut, he will roll his hips through his strikes and generate movement. When this happens, he’s forceful.


    When it doesn’t, he overextends trying to jab from a distance and loses his balance—and often the assignment. He must learn to sustain his contact more often. When he does, he’ll lock on until the defender is on the ground or the whistle has blown.


    Head injuries almost prevented Harry from ever playing football. He suffered concussions before

    college and didn’t play football again until his freshman year.


    Harry reminds me of one of my favorite receiver prospects before I got into doing this work—Michael Westbrook. He was a strong, quick player with excellent skill around the ball. I don’t think he loved football at the level he needed to maximize his skills over the long haul but when he was at his best, he did a lot of what Harry does. Harry is a little slower but more sure-handed.


    He may need an acclimation season before he produces only because the team that takes him may have trouble deciding how to best use him. I think Harry is what Carolina dreamed Kelvin Benjamin would be. He’d be a fun option for Russell Wilson in Seattle if the offense will change enough to throw back corner fades in the red zone. He’d also give Wilson the player hoped it would get from Jimmy Graham in the receiving game.


    N’Keal Harry Highlights



    RSP Boiler Room: Stacking Needed


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: At this point, it’s probably wiser to consider one of the two top running backs ahead of Harry. If the league is a 1.5 PPR premium scoring format for tight ends, the same is true for the top two tight ends on the RSP’s board. If fantasy players don’t draft until May or later, Harry’s value could rise above the running backs with a good draft-day fit.


  7. Preston Williams, Colorado State (6-4, 211)


    Depth of Talent Score: 86.05 = Starter: Starting immediately with large role and learning on the go.


    NFL.com’s draft analyst Lance Zierlein was on the RSP Cast during the fall of 2018 and he mentioned Olabisi Johnson as an under-the-radar receiver he liked after initial views. I had seen Johnson while studying quarterback K.J. Carta-Samuels but the player I couldn’t take my eyes off was Williams, a former top recruit at Tennessee whose lack of maturity of the field resulted in some changes to his life and he wound up with the Rams.


    Williams looks and plays like A.J. Green. He’s wiry strong, quick, and wins the ball with grace in physical situations. A tale of the tape with Williams and Green also shows some similarities with some of their workout metrics.



    Green

    Williams

    Height

    6'4"

    6'4"

    Weight

    Green and Williams are both in the RSP’s Starter Tier for long speed, although Green is on the upper end of the range. The rest of Wiliams’ metrics in this table are in the Starter Tier whereas Green’s are in the Star Tier.


    There was a tenor about his Pro Day that suggests Williams expected to deliver elite results. However, the fact that Williams’ style of play and athletic ability on film and in workouts is equivalent of a “Starter Tier A.J. Green” rather than the “All-Pro Version” in Cincinnati still makes him a coveted receiver prospect.


    One could argue that Stefon Diggs is the starter version of Odell Beckham, Jr. There will be those who argue that point vociferously but regardless of where you actually stand on this potential debate, the point is that a player who might be a notch or half a notch below a top talent can still be a valuable player.


    Williams has that potential. He plays on either side of the formation and delivers as a route runner, rebounder, and ball carrier with flair and toughness befitting of the Green comparison—even if he isn’t as dynamic.


    Williams is skilled at separating from the line of scrimmage. He’ll mix and match shoulder fakes and dips, wipes, chops, and swipes with rocker steps and foot-fire variations to get free of press coverage. He also varies his pacing effectively so he’s changing up his release techniques. Once Williams earns separation, he’ll stalk his man.


    He had some issues with slips while trying to release from press coverage. He needs to keep his eyes focused on the task at hand and not skip ahead.

    When he fails to do this during foot-fires, he slips.


    Williams doesn’t drop his pads and attack with a downfield intent as often as he should when facing off coverage. On his worst reps, Williams can be too slow off the line and get hung up against contact.


    Once into his stem, Williams wins his routes with good manipulations to set up breaks. He baits defender with bends of his stems and head fakes. Once he makes his break on routes back to the quarterback he will work hard to get to the ball.


    He has flexibility to drop his weight into breaks, but he must drop deeper and do it more often. His crossing routes earn good depth against man coverage. When facing zone coverage, Williams settles into open space and makes himself a good target. His speed breaks can be a little tighter on outs and digs.


    Like players in the A.J. Green-style, Williams is graceful on targets where he must go airborne. He’ll turn through the target and execute a quick pull- down and shield of the defender at the catch point of fades.


    If he’s facing tight coverage, he’ll take the hit and maintain possession of the football and he’s willing to

    attack the ball in the Honey-Hole of Cover 2 zone that often leads to him being the meat in a defensive back sandwich. Whether it’s a hard hit or a defender hanging off him, it doesn’t deter Williams’ focus.


    He also possesses strong body control, reaching behind his break momentum with arms fully extended to catch not-so-accurate targets. Find Williams at the end line and he can track and snare the ball over his shoulder and land in time to tap the feet inbounds with a defender glued to him.


    Williams uses active hands technique to attack the ball and knows when to use high or low positions based on the location of the target. One thing he has to address immediately is the tendency to leave his feet unnecessarily on routes thrown at waist and chest level over the middle. When he leaves his feet, it prevents him from transition upfield as quickly.


    While not a burner, Williams is a tough and elusive runner after the catch. He can pull through high and low wraps, bounce off glancing blows to his body, and spin and dip away from angles of pursuit— sometimes on the same play.


    Once at full speed, Williams can work past good pursuit angles and use his stiff-arm to ward off reaches. He sees the field well and finds efficient ways to work away form pursuit lanes.


    While his carriage can be tighter at the elbow, Williams holds the ball high and uses the correct arm to carry it.


    He’s a decent blocker with potential to be even better. He works downfield with a balance of urgency and patience to set up stalk blocks. He’ll also bait defenders into thinking he’s releasing on a route when actually setting up a block.


    Once Williams earns position with his hands, he’ll drive the opponent away from the ball. He has the strength to shove opponents to the ground when they aren’t bringing their A-game to the interaction.


    Although off-field issues don’t factor in RSP evaluations, the story behind Williams is worth knowing. He’s a former top-tier high school prospect who committed to Tennessee and eventually earned Freshman of the Week honors for his play.


    He transferred from Tennessee in 2016 and sat out the entire 2017 season. In September of 2017, Williams earned a suspension for a misdemeanor charge of assult and pled guilty.


    According to police reports, Williams had an argument with his girlfriend and when she tried to leave, he physically blocked her path and then held her back from leaving. He also left well over a hundred messages on her cell phone.


    The Reporter-Herald ran a story about Williams’ maturation. Here’s an excerpt:

    “Apparently, it wasn’t just the coaches that were happy to see Williams redeem himself. He also seemed to have the support of his teammates.


    ‘I’m very impressed,’ wideout Bisi Johnson said, according to a report from Reporter-Herald. ‘I mean, he turned his whole life around. It was a little sketchy there at first, but he’s definitely figured it out, and we needed him. It’s good to have him on the team.’”


    If Williams has matured,— he has the skills to start now as a secondary option and develop into a primary threat.


    RSP Boiler Room: Upper Body Mobility And Pass Catching Technique

    Preston Williams Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Williams should be available in the second round of fantasy drafts— possibly the third—depending on whether he’s a second or third-down pick in the NFL Draft. He’s the type of player that could be a nice value for fantasy players in dire need of tight ends, running backs, and/or quarterbacks and know they can’t wait to get value at the position.


  8. Stanley Morgan, Jr. Nebraska (6-0, 202)


    Depth of Talent Score: 85.15 = Starter: Starting immediately with large role and learning on the go (On the cusp of Rotational Starter Tier).


    I haven’t said or written much about certain players this year because I wanted to save my enthusiasm for this publication. Morgan is at the top of this list and while I could fake how befuddled I am that he isn’t earning more attention, it would be disingenuous.


    Just look back at the first six receivers on the board—the draft community drools over big and tall receivers. So much so, Equanimeous St. Brown and Courtland Sutton were heralded beyond their abilities.


    I am confused that Morgan didn’t earn any invitations to college all-star games. Senior Bowl Director Jim Nagy stated a desire to showcase small school talents, which can lead to snubs of players with a valid argument of being deserving. There are only so many spots and the fact that Morgan earned an invitation to the NFL Combine was far more important.


    Morgan will get the J.A.G. (“Just a Guy”) label from a lot of evaluators. And if I’m wrong about Morgan, he’ll prove these evaluators correct. However, I think Morgan is an absolute dog who plays with technique, and has quickness, consistency, and a hard-nosed mentality that will make him a good starting receiver for a lot of years.


    Morgan plays on either side of the formation. Based on his ability to work with his quarterback, his physicality, and his quickness, he could probably become a good slot player if called upon.


    His 4.53-second, 40-speed is average but as mentioned in the Underrated Section of this chapter, his 20 Shuttle-3 Cone combination is one of the best in this class and he uses his acceleration and quickness well.


    Morgan gets his pads over his knees and sells the vertical route against off coverage. He can beat good cornerback prospects straight-up on routes that earn targets 30-35 yards downfield because of his acceleration. This is good enough to command respect from defenses—especially once his team crosses midfield.


    Morgan has a swipe, an arm-over, and a chop that he combines with foot-fires to gain a release from tight coverage at the line. He’ll need to expand his arsenal of skills at the line to compete at a higher level of Sunday football.


    Because he has the quickness and acceleration to win at 30-35 yards, he can prevent defenders from sitting on every route. When covered tightly, he can drop his weight into breaks, but he must take one drive step before making the move with greater consistency.


    Morgan executes this move well with hitches and stop routes and snaps his turns quickly. This move pairs well with his stick at the top of stems that break into slants, digs, outs, and other routes breaking towards the middle of the field or the sideline. This jab step does a tremendous job of baiting the defender—especially when he turns his chest and pads into the move.


    The underlying reason this works so well is that Morgan stops fast. Even without perfect hard breaks, he decelerates with excellent skill and this is the baseline for strong route running. It also sets up moves that bait defenders into thinking that Morgan is about to break-down.


    Morgan’s dig route is a beneficiary of this skill. He drops his weight well into this route break and works back to the ball. His sticks, head fakes, and shoulder turns are well-timed to set up intermediate and vertical routes. He often executes these fakes violently and at the last possible moment. This makes him skilled at baiting off-man coverage as well as defenders in zone.


    His sudden stops earn him great position on timing routes and it’s no wonder that he runs the stop-and- go double move and hook-and-go as adeptly as anyone in this class. When working underneath the coverage, Morgan will slow his break down if the ball isn’t in the air and give his quarterback time to find him.


    Morgan has reliable hands. Whether the target is high, low, or away from his frame, facing tight coverage, or an impending collision, his technique is rock-solid and earns him second-chance opportunities to win the ball in difficult target scenarios.

    Morgan makes strong plays to the ball against tight coverage. He extends well for the ball and isn’t concerned about banging against opponents to win the football.


    Although he’s 20-25 pounds lighter than many of the box-out specialists in this draft, Morgan is skilled and makes the last-second move to gain position. His boundary awareness is also strong.


    Morgan has underrated hand-eye coordination and tracking. He executes one-handed stabs with his back to the target and he’ll use his back shoulder or arm to maintain leverage and box out an opponent while tracking the target into his downfield hand— similar to the targets I raved about when profiling Harry.


    Where Morgan shows the “dog” in his game is with the ball in his hands. His notable quickness shows up after the catch. His first step or change of direction usually leaves an outstretched opponent in its wake.


    If he doesn’t avoid first contact, he’ll pull through it or attack with good pad level. He works through the trash of outstretched limbs effectively to find open creases for larger gains.


    In addition to fighting through wraps and leaning for extra yardage, he can hurdle opponents shooting for his legs. Morgan has the kind of gait that supports good acceleration when taking a curvilinear path away from pursuit.


    Because of this skill, defenders can let up a step as he nears the sideline, thinking that Morgan is going too fast to stay inbounds. He’ll also use a stiff-arm to ward off reaches as he’s bending around this pursuit to open spaces.


    In addition to this style of movement, Morgan can sequence a variety of stop-start moves, dips, and spins. He can make a cornerback miss and a step later spin through a linebacker’s wrap.


    Morgan carries the ball under the correct arm and switches his carriage arm when possible to avoid new angles to the ball.


    Although an average-sized receiver, he attacks linebackers in the run game. He’ll seal them with good footwork and a punch or square up and deliver a blow. He must attack with a better punch rather than lean into them. He tends to have this lapse of technique with larger defenders.


    Otherwise, he’ll close the gap, punch, and roll his hips through safeties and cornerbacks. He gets under the skin of defensive backs because he’s become more aggressive as the years have gone by. Now he attacks fast, latches on quickly, and sustains his hands with excellent grip strength.


    He understands when to bypass a cornerback to attack a safety with a better angle to his teammate. He also will show good judgment with leaving his feet and throwing his body around to earn contact

    when he senses that he won’t reach his assignment in time otherwise.


    As a Browns fan I’d love to see Morgan in Cleveland because I think he gives a little bit of that Hines Ward edge and versatility as a flanker opposite Odell Beckham, Jr. and moves Jarvis Landry to the slot. If he can add about 10 pounds of muscle and maintain his explosiveness, he could develop into a player with some of Roddy White’s game.


    Stanley Morgan, Jr. Highlights



    RSP Boiler Room: Good Technique Affords Second Chances


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Morgan probably isn’t going before the fourth round in the NFL Draft— likely lower. It will make him a nice mid-to-late fantasy value.


  9. Parris Campbell, Ohio State (6-0, 205)


    Depth of Talent Score: 85.05 = Starter: Starting immediately with large role and learning on the go (On the cusp of Rotational Starter Tier).


    In contrast to Morgan, Campbell is a raw receiver but there’s a good chance he’ll earn a first- or second-round pick because of his explosive athletic profile. Normally, I’m skeptical about selecting less refined players this early on the basis of upside, but Campbell is an exception. He has enough baseline skills that he should develop quickly.


    Although featured in the slot, Campbell has shown combinations of arm-overs and rips while pairing them with duck walks and rocker steps. He releases with intensity and his pads down to avoid the jam.


    Right now, Campbell uses his hands more like blunt weapons than surgical tools. He’ll have to gain more precision to earn consistent separation against tight coverage when he’s not in the slot.


    Although he didn’t run close to the full route tree at Ohio State, Campbell exhibits the skills of top route- running technicians. He runs angular stems to manipulate defenders before his beraks. His speed turns are sharper than most receivers, and he can drop his weight into breaks and work back to the ball.


    Especially notable is Campbell’s ability to enter these hard breaks with one long drive step rather than several gathered steps. He may not have been called on to execute these behaviors frequently, but he has been working on these skills that are necessary to translate to the NFL’s route game.


    Campbell’s catch techniques are also strong. He attacks targets at the first available window and uses proper hand position for the location of the target.


    He’ll get airborne and highpoint or slide and dig out the low target. When working as an outlet on screens or wide routes, Campbell adjusts his body with the ball in the air so he can catch the target in a

    downhill position. He’s fluid and processes one step ahead of the present task.


    Occasionally this processing results in focus drops because he’s thinking too far ahead and fails to secure the ball. Known as a finesse player with great speed and quickness, Campbell will catch the ball over the middle and take a shot to the chest. This is a football player, not a track star.


    Opponents may beg to differ when trying to catch him in the open field with his 4.31-speed. He makes sharp-angled turns in the open field, accelerates to top speed with only a small runway needed, and he’ll run through arms reaching for his feet and ankles.


    He has good parallel cuts and slalom cuts to make the first man miss and a stiff-arm to ward off additional reaches as he accesses a lane and blows by pursuit. Campbell will weave through a defense with the grace of an avalanche skier averting the natural disaster.


    When he faces contact, he has good pad level to work off the collision and fall forward. The only issue with Campbell the ball carrier is his transitions downfield. He’ll take wide angles that initially costs him yardage rather than turning tight or pivoting immediately downhill.


    It works at Ohio State and it will probably work for him more than most receivers in the NFL. However, it will only work a fraction of the time it did in the past.


    Campbell practices good ball security that’s high and tight. He carries it with the appropriate arm.


    For a big-play, fleet-footed receiver, Campbell will do the dirty work without the ball. He works inside and delivers a punch to safeties and linebackers in the run game. He’s good at squaring his opponents and locks on with tight grip strength. He’ll maintain his position with smooth footwork. He can move outside linebackers and safeties with his technique and he has no problem redirecting and fighting for position.


    He’s one of the best blockers in this class. He’s also sneaky good for a “raw” receiver. The team that gets Campbell will be thrilled.


    If Tom Brady is serious about playing another 5-7 years, Campbell would be a great addition. However, I think the collective draft world is projecting a tight end in the first round. You never know…


    Parris Campbell Highlights



    RSP Boiler Room: A Projection Worth the Investment


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Something has to give in a draft with this many good receivers and tight end prospects because there’s no way the top 3-4 running back prospects in any class fall to the second around. It means a player like Campbell might be available in the second round and that’s a bargain I would love acquire.

    Tier III: The next nine players could start this year, but won’t express their fullest potential without another year or two of work. Even if they produce at a high rate, they will likely be used in ways that limit their range of use.


  10. Kelvin Harmon, NC State. (6-2, 221)


    Depth of Talent Score: 84.75 = Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths. (On the cusp of Starter Tier)


    If there’s a player who I’ll bet I ranked too low in this class, Harmon would top the list. If you think I felt dirty about Harry earning the No.6 spot, Harmon’s placement is borderline filthy.


    It’s what happens when you’re the least explosive player in the top tier of this class. The RSP has standards and there’s only so much “play” one can have within them.


    Harmon’s long speed and change of direction are Committee Tier. He wins with his acceleration, his strength, and excellent hand-eye coordination. If you round up—and a round-up has validity with his Depth of Talent Score—Harmon lands in the Starter Tier.


    That’s my lame attempt to apologize for not having him in the upper part of spots 6-10. However, I’m not really sorry. He’s a good prospect in a great class and good starters with great fits can out-produce great talents.


    Harmon is skilled with releases. He uses his hands well to swipe defenders at the top of his stem as well as off the line in conjunction with a three-step pattern. He also has a four-step pattern working into the slant to freeze his coverage before he begins his acceleration into the break. He also runs the slant with a three-step foot-fire and stutter afterwards.


    Harmon’s combination of footwork patterns bait off- coverage defenders and he’ll often clean up with a wipe or arm over. He uses a chop or shoulder dip with quicker releases and he has a decent swim when he can set it up.


    Although he’s not especially quick in and out of breaks, he has quick hands in tight spaces to earn position, and his acceleration is starter quality. He’ll pull away from cornerbacks when he can execute a good release. He also has some nice inside-out mainipulations with his stems to set up routes like the skinny post. He’ll even stack defenders after a quick head fake.


    Harmon executes effective double moves to get open in the deep game. Although he lacks great cutting ability, he possesses good acceleration when moving in a curvilinear pattern and this helps him sell double moves that often turn defenders around. He actually ran the most thorough double move I saw this year in the college game.

    Harmon executes flat breaks and works back to the ball on speed outs. If nitpicking, Harmon can break a little flatter with a sharper turn. He tends to flatten out his turn with his third step of the break. When this step is good, his breaks are flat. It’s not as consistent as it can be.


    He works back to the ball well on routes breaking to the quarterback. On routes breaking across the middle, Harmon squares well to the target. He’ll drop his weight into hard breaks and gets his knees over his pads. His turns are sudden with intermediate routes.


    Harmon excels at the catch point. He snatches the ball with authority from just about every angle. He’ll catch the ball over his shoulder, pull down the high- point target, and duck under defenders after making an underhanded, bucket-catch while barreling towards contact.


    Harmon attacks the ball at the earliest window of arrival and his techniques match the location of the target. He’s a tough guy who will take hits to his chest while making a play to the ball and still come down with the catch. He’ll use one hand to maintain position away from the tight coverage and the other for a one-handed grab.


    He’ll fade away from contact with back shoulder grabs and still come down inside the boundary. He toe-taps or toe-drags as the situation demands.

    When Harmon has lapses with his receiving technique, he tries to clap onto the ball’s sides.


    Harmon’s game has finesse, but it’s a savvy change- up to a baseline serving of physicality. After the catch, he’s strong enough to continue forward through wraps until a second defender can chop him to the ground. He runs through direct hits from cornerbacks. Cornerbacks and safeties hitting him high will realize it was a mistake.a split-second later


    He’ll also drop the pads to split defenders, push piles, or pull through contact. Harmon will also deliver head and shoulder fakes to eliminate direct angles of contact and transform them to glancing shots that he can run through.


    He carries the ball high to his frame. It’s a little loose at the elbow.


    Harmon is more of a reacher than a striker when blocking. However, he squares his opponents and delivers his hands. On occasion, he’ll deliver his hands with an uppercut motion, but he’s usually too far from the defender to earn power and maintain position with the technique.


    When he can latch onto a defensive back, that defender is going where Harmon wants him to go. He works to the whistle even if he misses the first angle to his opponent and has to work to earn a second, or find another assignment.


    Harmon’s most skilled at using the defender’s reach to his own advantage and creating good leverage to push or turn the man out of the play. When he

    closes the gap quicker with his blocks, he’s tough to stop.


    Harmon has the tools to earn a strong career as a possession-plus receiver capable of stretching the field with play-action targets and winning on routes 20-25 yards downfield without the need for trickery. He isn’t a flashy athlete, but his skill, physicality, and hands should translate to starter production.


    RSP Boiler Room: Tandem Movements RSP Boiler Room: Give Me Three Steps…



    Kelvin Harmon Highlights


    Pre-Draft Fantasy Advice: With a good fit, Harmon could be an immediate starter with strong fantasy production. I have a feeling his average value will have a lot of variation, which means you might get him as your second receiver or he’ll be off the board in the mid-to-late first round.


  11. Marquise Brown, Oklahoma (5-9, 166)


    Depth of Talent Score: 84.3=Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths.


    Oklahoma used Brown on the left and right sides of the formation as well as the slot. He’s a big-play artist wherever he’s used because of top-end speed, acceleration, and change of direction.


    His burst off the line is notable and opposing defenders are forced to pay healthy respect to Brown’s ability to get behind them. Brown sells that possibility with his pads over his knees when he begins his release from the line.


    Brown has a shoulder dip, swipe, arm-over, and chop to work away from coverage. He delivers the arm-over and the chop with violence and he can set up his moves with a rocker step or three-step release pattern.


    More frequently than not, Brown faces off-coverage, and this is where his moves come into play. When he faces tight coverage at the line, Brown leans more on pace variation, stop-start moves, and a widening or narrowing of his stem and a head fake.


    He’s quick enough to get away with earning separation without using his hands. For a player with his diminutive dimensions it’s understandable that he’s avoiding contact as much as possible.


    Desean Jackson is an inch taller and 10 pounds heavier than Brown, but he entered the league at 168 pounds and he’s had a good career. He has made a living avoiding contact. Jackson is a more explosive player but not by such a large degree that Brown’s lack of hand usage against tight coverage at the line will derail him.


    Brown doesn’t run routes by the book. With his speed and quickness, he can freelance a bit and earn separation. He’s good at telling a story with his routes and forcing coverage into a bad position.

    He sells his stems with various movements that will earn him breaks into open space. He’s especially good at deeper stems. Brown will work to the back of his off-coverage, and his pressure on the opponent’s blind spot creates openings when he breaks across the defender’s body to the inside.


    Brown has effective timing with his acceleration late in a route. This helps him in the vertical game because he can bait coverage with his pacing.


    Oklahoma used Brown extensively on rub routes and screens so he earned space with a downhill path without facing early contact. When sturdier corners make contact with Brown, he’ll lose his balance and wind up on the ground.


    On shorter routes where he’s earning separation on his own, Brown has a quick stick move to work in and out of breaks. He doesn’t drop his weight into breaks unless he’s running a double move. Still, he maintains a flat line on breaks and works back to the football.


    Brown has a feel for when to angle away from the quarterback and get downhill as the ball arrives. When he runs the comeback, he breaks back to the ball with urgency and he can execute hairpin turns near the boundary without leaving the field of play.


    The skill to make these tight turns and sudden stops has excused Brown from traditional route techniques. It should remain the case in the NFL but if he struggles to get open, his lack of refined technique or his difficulty getting open with the necessary timing will be root causes.


    Brown is seen primarily as an outside threat in some circles of our community, but he does a good job of finding creases in zone coverage in the middle of the field. He doesn’t play with fear in the middle of the field, and he’s quick enough to earn a target and avoid first contact. He won’t be a traditional slot receiver in the NFL, but he’ll earn some work in the middle of the field—especially in offenses that spread the field.


    Brown catches the ball with correct hand position for the location of the target. He attacks the ball with good extension towards the earliest window of arrival.


    He has trouble with targets arriving at difficult angles above his head with contact looming. He can usually go up for the ball, make the initial catch, and even turn away from the defender but once he’s hit and rebounds off the ground, the ball comes out. Contact to his legs or torso also disrupts his focus as he’s reaching for the ball.


    He has difficulty tracking the ball over his shoulder. He’ll catch the ball often enough, but there’s just enough issues that you’ll occasionally see Brown make 1-2 adjustments with his path to the target on deep throws. Sometimes the second adjustment is a correction of the first decision.

    When he drops the ball on deep targets with his back to the pass, you’ll see the ball drop between his arms or wrists and not his hands—a sign that Brown didn’t track the ball well. His hands can also get passive with belt line targets. He usually catches these targets but it’s something to be aware of.


    Brown, like Jackson, is one of the few receivers who will have success with a succession of stop-start moves rather than cuts that continue moving him downhill. Once he earns a crease with his movement, he’ll accelerate into the open field and sustain his speed for long gains.


    Contact usually ends Brown’s runs. Wraps high to his frame drop him easily. Direct contact will mow him down. At best, Brown can use his stiff-arm with enough leverage to ward off reaches.


    Although he comes back to the ball well, he should learn to come to a complete stop and turn directly upfield rather than try to dip or angle with his momentum. This transition technique could make Brown more sudden after the catch and prevent good angles of pursuit. Although fast, I believe his acceleration is the strength of his athletic profile because Brown gets caught by defensive backs in the open field on longer runs.


    Brown’s carriage is too loose. Direct hits separate him from the ball. He is quick to switch the ball from one arm to the other when he’s in the open field.

    When in traffic, Brown will tighten the ball to his chest but not cinch the elbow to his side.


    Brown can run off defenders and then turn and shield them with hand position and footwork. That’s the extent of what he’ll do as a run blocker.


    Although small, Brown played through a Lisfranc injury that required offseason surgery this winter. There’s optimism he’ll be ready to practice when training camp opens, but this news usually ends with the player on the PUP list for 3-5 weeks to begin the year.


    Teams like Seattle or Cleveland could be nice fits for Brown but any team that uses trips bunch sets or twin stacks to let him rub and work quickly downfield will be a good environment for his skills.


    Brown is a patience play this year with big-play ability. If he’s used mostly as an outside receiver, he’ll lack the consistency of volume he’d see as a big-play slot option.


    Marquise Brown Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Brown’s value also has a great deal of variation this year. His injury is one factor but so is his use in an offense. I don’t think he’s at DeSean Jackson’s level of skill, but if given a slot role in a spread attack he could produce to the ceiling of expectations.


    I bet he’ll have fantasy players that pick him late in the first round and there will be leagues where he

    drops to the third round due to his injury and boom- bust potential.


  12. Jalen Hurd, Baylor (6-5, 226)


    Depth of Talent Score: 83.7 = Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to his strengths.


    Hurd deserves a ton of praise for making a position switch (see the Underrated Section) because he looks like he’s played the position for a lot longer than he has. Baylor also deserves credit for featuring Hurd in the slot where he could run a more limited route tree and maximize his skills—and Hurd’s confidence in his own development.


    At some point, Hurd will develop into a perimeter option. When he does, he’ll have a true shot at a starting role and quality production. He’s that promising.


    Hurd accelerates with urgency off the line and has a shoulder reduction and chop with his outside arm, which he uses to work inside the off-coverage. He keeps his eyes up and down field as he begins his stems.


    At the stop of his stems, Hurd executes a violent chop. His fade routes feature a good three-step release to earn separation and set up his break.


    Hurd must learn to combine the techniques of his upper and lower body into effective release work. His best combination right now is a reduction of his shoulder and stack. He can execute this at a quick pace and at a timely point late in the stem.


    Hurd’s route work past his initial release really shines for a player with his level of experience. He sets a strong pace with his stems and will widen them to setup breaks. His head fakes can get defenders leaning in the wrong direction.


    Hurd uses effective pace variation and shake moves on shallow and intermediate routes. He sells double moves in convincing fashion with turns of his head, shoulders, hips, and knees. Even his ankle flexion makes the false break appear convincing. The post- corner and post-out are two of his better double- moves.


    Hurd sells the deeper routes with an intense pace and then breaks back on the curl. He comes back to the ball well. His hitches feature one long drive step into to a hard break, dropping his weight effectively. He also drops his weight well into a quick whip route.


    Hurd’s execution of these two routes speaks well to his fast development at the position. The fact he can already execute the one long drive step into the hard break is a big plus.


    He also executes speed breaks with a hard drive step, a tight turn, and good acceleration through the break path. His boundary awareness is strong on comeback routes and he gets his head around fast on routes breaking towards the boundary or the

    middle of the field. His over routes have a violent turn at the end of its stair-step break.


    He’s even showing some strong diagnostic skill to read blitzes and adjust his routes. Hurd has some issues slipping during his releases against off coverage. He’s still getting comfortable with certain routes and his mind can be ahead of his feet.


    Although he’s skilled at staying inbounds at the catch point, Hurd must develop more sideline awareness so he doesn’t run out of bounds on scramble drills.

    His speed breaks can get a step tighter and flatter. As you can see, much of what he needs to do as a route runner is refinement; the basic skills are there—and this isn’t the case with many top prospects in any given draft.


    Hurd’s techniques as a pass catcher are in place. He uses fingertip techniques to catch the ball. Highpoint passes present some difficulty for him at this point when he’s required to make a full extension for the ball. The technique is good, the results are inconsistent.


    Hurd attacks the ball and he can snatch it from the air to his body. He’s better at low throws. He’s also consistent at applying the correct hands technique for the location of the target. Although he’s less consistent with high targets, he wins his share of them and can make these catches on fades and over routes.


    Speaking of fades, Hurd jumps back towards the ball on deep fades when the target arrives behind his break path. When contact arrives, Hurd secures the ball despite contact to his back.


    Hurd has potential as a fade route player because of his leaping. He can really elevate. He also can take contact to his chest and still make the play. This ability to make clutch catches and with good technique is why the occasional drop of highpoint throws isn’t a major concern.


    Hurd still carries the ball like a running back and it’s a major compliment. In fact, he runs with better footwork and balance than he did before he learned the skills of the wide receiver position. The work helped his game.


    Hurd could always drive through contact and extend his frame for extra yards. He also had skill with slalom cuts, strong pad level, and the sheer strength to run through wraps.


    Now, Hurd has an easier time avoiding contact to his legs, working around penetration into the backfield, and running with greater balance that helps him bounce off defensive backs, linebackers and defensive tackles. Hurd is 20 pounds lighter, but he still runs like a five-star recruit who earned a full- time role as an SEC running back.


    He can bend away from defenders, shake past them, or spin through contact. Baylor often used Hurd as a short-yardage back in the red zone or as a change of pace with gap plays.


    Whether it’s the backfield or the open field as a receiver after the catch, Hurd has the lateral agility, balance, and vision to gain positive yards. If he’s amenable to playing running back as a situational option at Baylor, he’ll likely do the same in the NFL. This versatility adds to Hurd’s overall appeal, because he’s good enough to be a second or third back on an NFL roster if he wasn’t interested in playing wide receiver.


    Hurd transitions well from route runner to blocker. He’s strong enough to maintain his grip inside a defender’s chest play. He also strikes with an uppercut and rolls his hips through the motion when stalk blocking.


    He’s an intense competitor as a blocker and he moves his feet to stay with his opponent after that defender disengages. If Hurd can move his feet a little better, he’ll have less issues with overextending his frame into his attack.


    Hurd’s path to Baylor and the wide receiver position is a fascinating read. Much like Campbell, there’s a perception that Hurd is a raw prospect. In some ways this is true, but a better label is inexperienced with specific tasks. Both Campbell and Hurd have strong fundamental skills to build on and very little to unlearn.


    Hurd doesn’t catch the ball as well as Kenny Golladay, but he could produce in a similar role as Golladay had two years ago in Detroit. Perhaps even a more expanded role because he is a superior route runner.


    Jalen Hurd Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Hurd is one of many excellent value picks at the position. He’s a bit of a patience play but it would be surprising if he isn’t contributing early at least in a supporting role. If you can land him in the third round, you did well. He may go even later.

  13. Riley Ridley, Georgia (6-1, 199) Depth of Talent Score: 83.45 = Rotational

    Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role

    playing to his strengths.


    There’s a split between the analytics and film factions of the draft community regarding Ridley. At least there was in January when individuals looked at Ridley’s production and wondered aloud what all the fuss was about. Individuals touting Ridley’s tape got sucked into a debate over the value of production, which led to individuals skeptical of Ridley pondering if film evaluation is on par with reading tea leaves.


    Whether it’s evaluating players with film, stats, or both, sample sizes are usually problematic. The added difficulty with evaluating Ridley is that he played in an offense where there were even fewer exposures of him demonstrating skills that might help evaluators see a complete game.

    Based on what I’ve seen and how I record observational data, Ridley’s tape shows evidence of a complete game that volume-based data won’t. Of course, the sample size will be cited as problematic.


    Ridley has starter-tier speed and star-tier acceleration. Watch his routes and you’ll see excellent precision and control. Data-bent analysts argue that Ridley ran such a limited route tree that it doesn’t prove he’s going to be a good route runner.


    Learn the mechanics of route running and it becomes apparent that Ridley executes the techniques required to run the most difficult routes. I don’t think Ridley is a special player but he’s a competent prospect who can deliver contributor production and develop into a starting possession receiver who will do more than what he had to do at Georgia.


    Ridley exhibits strong work against tight coverage. He uses double swipes, swats, shoulder dips, and arm-overs in tandem with rocker steps, three-step patterns, and various foot-fires to earn space into his stems. He also uses hard jabs, arm-drumming, and pace variation to bait defenders into bad decisions.


    Whether it’s a long release pattern, or a one-step move with an arm-over, Ridley is sudden and precise. He has the speed to earn separation on fades and go routes when a defender doesn’t provide resistance early in the route. He also has the skill to cross the face of defenders on slants and he finds open creases against zone coverage.


    Ridley is skilled at altering his pacing to set up his breaks. He gets his head around fast after the break point and his breaks on speed turns are flat.


    Ridley also executes the single drive-step into hard breaks with a great drop of weight to earn the sudden stop. Some evaluators see him run hitch after hitch after hitch and wonder why others praise Ridley for his route running. It’s because the way he runs the hitch translates well to the dig, the curl, the comeback, and out, and a variety of double moves.


    His stick is so strong it also sets up intermediate and vertical routes because it can be mistaken for a drive step leading to the breaks on shorter routes above. This may not show up in a box score as production, but when you define criteria and track it—be it yards or techniques—you’re tracking data.


    On deeper routes, Ridley bends his stems to bait coverage over the top in the wrong direction. He widens stems early enough to get into the corner’s blind spot and force the defender to stumble. He also supplements these bends in the stem with head fakes at the top of the stem.


    When the defender is trailing Ridley on a longer route, Ridley will use his head and eyes to bait his opponent. When a receiver can decelerate as well as Ridley these various methods of baiting opponents, he becomes that much more effective.


    Ridley can high-point the ball well. He also will take contact to his chest or back and maintain possession

    of the football. He snares the ball well over his shoulder and uses the correct hands position based on the target’s location.


    Georgia didn’t feature Ridley on fade routes. On the rare occasion he earned this type of target, he displayed perfect technique with his position on the defender, his turn to the ball, the catch, and his pull- down. His turns in the air are notably fluid and has that timing with his leaps where it appears as if he’s hanging in the air just a little longer than his opponents.


    In addition to seemingly slowing time down on fade routes, Ridley can make the quick turn away from the momentum of his break path and make a full extension for the ball. He also makes shin-high grabs over the middle while keeping his feet with his hands way extended from his body without losing balance.


    The weakest aspect of Ridley’s receiving game is his boundary work. He must practice getting both feet inbounds and use a toe drag rather than exclusively a toe tap.


    Ridley is quick enough to make efficient transitions upfield after the catch. He ducks and turns his pads away from reaches and pulls through them. He has the balance to remain upright through contact and at least lean for extra yardage.


    Ridley has jump cuts, jukes, sticks, stutters, and spins to avoid contact. He’ll pair his movements with a stiff-arm. His power is functional at best, but he has a good balance-touch technique to bleed all he can from a run.


    Ridley carries the ball high to his chest but a little loose at the elbow. He also must switch the ball to the outside arm.


    Ridley squares opponents as a blocker and he’ll work to keep his hands on his assignments. He transitions quickly from route runner to blocker and he’ll uppercut his hands inside and locks them into the chest plate of his opponent.


    As a cut blocker, Ridley shows the savvy to raise his forearm above his head if he finds that his dive for the legs of his opponents is too low. This will often compensate enough to make the block effective.


    Ridley has lapses with cut blocks when he takes the wrong leg. He also overextends with his approach and tips off the move.


    Although Ridley can punch as a stand-up blocker, he drops his head and overextends in an attempt to deliver a hard shot instead of the technically-sound punch. This makes him a hit-or-miss producer as a blocker.


    Ridley missed two games during his career with a foot injury and required surgery. He also had a left ankle injury.


    The three players who come to mind when watching Ridley are Chad Johnson, Robert Woods, and

    Brandon Lloyd. He has specific elements of route running and attacking the football that resemble all three players.


    If he delivers anywhere close to them when they were at their best, Ridley will have a better career than I expect. Still, he should be a helpful option as a third or fourth receiver who has a solid shot at becoming a solid No.2 option. I just don’t know if he’ll have the vertical element that set these three options apart from their peers.


    RSP Boiler Room: Subtleties Often Missed



    Riley Ridley Highlights


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Ridley might earn an earlier pick in the NFL Draft than many expect. If he does, his value will climb in fantasy leagues. I think his best value is the late-third or early-fourth round.


  14. Emmanuel Butler, Northern Arizona (6-3, 217)


    Depth of Talent Score: 82.85 = Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths (On the cusp of Contributor Tier).


    There wasn’t a ton of tape on Butler. I asked around, but the Northern Arizona Lumberjacks are a tough “get.” Even when I did, Butler was hurt during those games.


    This is the challenge with his evaluation. Still, based on what I saw, he’s a legit talent who will have a shot at earning a late-round selection in the NFL Draft—especially with an invitation to the NFL Combine as part of his pre-draft process.


    Butler is strong enough to shed cornerbacks who attempt to jam him. He has a powerful chop and arm-over. He uses them well with three-step release patterns.


    He leans a lot on his power but his 4.22-second 20 Shuttle is a testament to quickness that falls into the Star Tier for acceleration. When he makes the effort to explode off the line, he can separate quickly and maintain his distance on cornerbacks for at least the first 25-30 yards.


    At the top of his routes, Butler uses his hands with precision and power. His turns could be more sudden, and he doesn’t get his pads over his knees as far as you’d like to see.


    Butler can drop his weight into breaks. He must develop the one long drive step, but his work with his routes is heading in the right direction.


    Butler is a stud at the catch point. He didn’t have quite the displays of acrobatic receptions of his peers at the very top of the board, but it was so close, that I have regrets about not giving him a star-caliber grade for his hands. He certainly displayed the same skill against the FBS teams as he did FCS opponents.

    He has excellent high-point technique and catches the ball consistently with active extensions to the target. Defenders can be at his chest or his back and Butler secures targets with his arms away from his frame. He excellent grip strength to maintain possession of the ball as he hits the ground or when a defender delivers a shot.


    He has supreme confidence in his ability to win the ball against tight coverage and Butler’s quarterback often trusted him enough to target him against double-teams. He can make plays over his shoulder in tight coverage as well as earn one-handed stabs in similar situations. His boundary awareness is also strong.


    The only thing holding Butler back from the Star Tier was the lack of extreme extensions to the ball where he secured them without the need to juggle them. I think he’s capable of more than what I saw on tape but didn’t have the proof.


    After the catch, Butler has the size to run over cornerbacks with the drop of his pads and the acceleration and short-area quickness to dip and cut across the face of oncoming defenders into open field.


    He tucks the ball high to his frame, but I only saw him carry the ball under his left arm. His punches have good uppercut form and location, but he must roll the hips for additional power.


    Butler missed all but two games with a shoulder injury in 2017. When he’s healthy, there are some resemblances to Larry Fitzgerald when it comes to his build, running style, and skill at the catch point.


    Like Preston Williams to A.J. Green, if Butler can become Larry Fitzgerald the “Starter Version” compared to the real Fitzgerald “Future Hall of Famer,” his career will be a smashing success.

    I like what I see enough to believe there’s a chance.



    Emmanuel Butler vs. Eastern Washington

    RSP Boiler Room: Emmanuel Butler




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Consider Butler a late-round pick, at best in fantasy leagues. If he gets drafted, he could earn a spot on a practice squad, wihch will make him a worthwhile stash on larger rosters with practice squad space. Otherwise, he’ll be a player to monitor from afar.

  15. JJ Arcega-Whiteside (6-2, 225)


Depth of Talent Score: 82.3 = Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to his strengths.


Arcega-Whiteside is known as a box-out specialist, but he has proven that he’s a more versatile player than a simple red-zone big man. However, his career will climb only as high as his hands technique, which has some small flaws—probably not enough to derail him but there is some concern.


He plays on either side of the field and occasionally in the slot. He has a full arsenal of moves to work through tight man coverage at the line. He’ll dip his shoulder, rip, swat, or wipe past the reach of opponents while executing three-step moves, shakes, stutters, and rocker-steps with pace variations.


He lacks blazing speed, but he has the build-up speed to work past some cornerbacks on longer routes against off-coverage. His burst is good enough to earn separation against tight coverage with the help of some physical play but even then, Arcega-Whiteside needs a little more open space to accelerate.


He works his stems with his eyes downfield, which maintains the possibility of him going deep. He’ll issue head fakes and sticks to set up breaks. He’ll also deliver a shake at the top of his stems to influence his opponents.


On short routes, Whiteside can drop his hips and make a sharp turn with good footwork. He only drops his pads into short-route stems and not consistently. He has to improve his breaks back to the quarterback on these routes. He’s made strides this year, but it’s still worth monitoring because it’s inconsistent.


He can execute flat breaks on speed turns. He makes quick snap turns to enhance his separation.


On longer routes, Whiteside doesn’t get as much lead into his stems as he should. It’s inconsistent from route to route. He also had a curious choice of using a stutter step to set up a break on a post route. It was an unnecessary choice.


He excels at posting up defenders in the red zone or the sidelines. He’ll earn position, move an opponent backwards, and rebound.


Whiteside has some skill for trapping the ball when posting up, but it is not the preferable tactic. He can extend his arms well to the target and turn his body effectively to shield as he pulls down.


He’ll also make one-handed catches on end-zone fades. He’ll maintain possession even with contact or when falling backwards to the turf. When bracketed, Whiteside will leap between the defenders to attack the ball.

He tracks the ball well over his shoulder and uses the appropriate high and low techniques for catching targets. He also displays the boundary awareness to get both feet inbounds.


There are issues with his hands. Although the techniques are essentially correct, there are enough small flaws that may render Arcega-Whiteside less reliable. His hands can be too far apart when attacking the ball and the ball either goes through them or he has to clap onto the ball and winds up fighting the target.


Even when he has his hands in ideal position, he’s not tracking the ball to his fingertips. The ball often bounces off his palms. He’s dropped passes because of this palms-first strike of the ball. He also leaves his feet on targets where he could have remained grounded. There are too many instances where he fights the ball to ignore it.


Whiteside has a quick shake move in the open field and can side-step a defender that is over the top of him. He’ll spin off contact as well as juke or stiff-arm his opponents. He carries the ball under either arm and secures the ball high and tight.


As a blocker, Whiteside uses the uppercut motion with his punch but it lacks violence and power because he overextends his position. He’s better at exploding into contact as a stalk blocker. He’ll hustle to the point of attack and throw his arms.


The problem with these blocks is that he doesn’t use good punching technique. He’s at his best when boxing out defenders and moving his feet to remain square.


He’s an improving player with his routes and hands. If he continues along this trajectory, he might develop into a starter. However, I’m not sold on him improving his hands without a ton of work and his speed, acceleration, and quickness remain question marks.


JJ Arcega-Whiteside Highlights




Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Arcega-Whiteside’s draft stock is likely late-second or early-third day.

He’ll have his fans because of red zone appeal, but if he’s not a starter it won’t be that fruitful of a fantasy relationship.
